{"title_page": "First Rohilla War", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n\nThe '''First Rohilla War''' of 1773\u20131774 was a punitive campaign by [[Shuja-ud-Daula]], [[Nawab of Awadh]] on the behalf of [[Mughal Emperor]], against the [[Rohilla]]s, Afghan highlanders settled in [[Rohilkhand]], northern India. The Nawab was supported by troops  of the [[British East India Company]], in a successful campaign brought about by the Rohillas reneging on a debt to the Nawab.\n\nRohillas was very brave people are gurrila yudh niti . British company was damage to Rohillas Maharaj Ranjeet Singh from north India.\n\nRohilla rastriy udhan (HP) was born 1900 satabdi something that is not available for the use of this time. This time was spent the last chance to Maharaj Ranjeet Singh from Jammu Kashmir valley.\n\n\n\n<br />\n\n==Background==\n\nHaving been driven into the mountains by the [[Maratha]]s, a few years earlier, the Rohillas had appealed for aid to Shuja-ud-Daulah, at that time an ally of the British. The Nawab demanded in return 40 rods of gold, that Rohilla chiefs refused to pay. The Nawab then decided to annex their country, and appealed to [[Warren Hastings]] for assistance, which was given in return for a sum of forty [[lakh]]s of rupees.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Rohilla |volume=23 |page=461 |inline=1}}</ref>\n\nHastings justified his action on the ground that the Rohillas were a danger to the British as uncovering the flank of [[Awadh]].<ref name=EB1911/>\n\n==Course of the war==\nThe Rohillas under [[Hafiz Rahmat Ali Khan]] <ref>[http://www.library.upenn.edu/collections/sasia/crafts1820/introduc.html Introduction to the Eleven Illustrations of Ghulam Yahya]</ref> were defeated by Colonel [[Alexander Champion (East India Company officer)|Alexander Champion]] on 23 April 1774 at the [[Battle of Miranpur Katra]]. The decisive battle, in which Hafiz Rahmat Khan died, caused the Rohillas to flee to the mountains near Loll Dong.<ref>[http://www.india9.com/i9show/Miranpur-Katra-80142.htm Miranpur Katra in India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n=== Guerrilla War and Siege===\nBy October 1774, the war evolved into a war of attrition. Faizullah Khan with the remaining loyal Rohillas retreated to a forest located in the hills of Lal Dang. The combined forces of the British and Awadh laid siege to the area from late August 1774 to October of the same year. Both sides were worn down and wished for peace. \n\nShah Shuja, who was suffering from cancer in his leg, wanted an early peace and thus after several attempts to break Rohilla unity under Faizullah Khan, he finally decided to release Mohabbat Khan, son of the late Hafiz Rehmat Khan in an attempt to undermine Faizullah's authority while at the same time he kept communication with Faizullah. His strategy worked and on 7 October 1774 Faizullah signed an amicable treaty of Lal dang and was granted a Princely State in the area of his choosing, leading to the creation of Rampur State. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=PRASAD |first1=ALOK |title=ROHILLA RESISTANCE AGAINST COLONIAL INTERVENTION UNDER NAWAB FAIZULLAH KHAN OF RAMPUR (1774-1794) |journal=  Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|volume=73 |pages=563\u2013572 |jstor=44156249 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n\nRohilkhand fell to Awadh, was plundered and occupied. The majority of the Rohillas left. They fled across the [[Ganges]] in numbers, to start a guerrilla war; or emigrated. A Rohilla state under British protection was set up in [[Rampur, Uttar Pradesh|Rampur]].\n\nThere was a [[Second Rohilla War]], in 1794.\n\n==Warren Hastings==\n\nThe war became a matter of Westminster politics during the [[Impeachment of Warren Hastings]]. Charges of destroying a nation were brought against Hastings by [[Edmund Burke]] and later [[Thomas Macaulay]].<ref name=EB1911/>\n\n==References==\n*[[John Strachey (civil servant)|John Strachey]] (1892), ''Hastings and the Rohilla War''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rangan-datta.info/photo/viewpic.php?gallery=41&id=206 Photo of Rohilla War Memorial at the St. John's Church compound Calcutta]\n\n\n[[Category:Invasions]]\n[[Category:Rohilla]]\n[[Category:History of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1773 in India]]\n[[Category:1774 in India]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1773]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1774]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = The First Rohilla War\n| width       = \n| partof      = [[Rohilla Wars]]\n| image       = Rohilla Horsemen.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Rohilla Cavalry\n| date        = 1773-1774\n| place       = [[Rohilkhand]] \n| coordinates = <!--Use the {{coord}} template -->\n| map_type    = \n| map_relief  = \n| map_size    = \n| map_marksize = \n| map_caption = \n| map_label   = \n| territory   = Annexation of the [[Kingdom of Rohilkhand]] and the Creation of [[Rampur State|Rampur Princely State]].\n| result      = Rohilla Defeat. Treaty of Lal Dang\n| status      = \n| combatants_header = \n| combatant1  = [[File:Rampur flag.svg|23px]] [[Kingdom of Rohilkhand]]\n| combatant2  = {{flagcountry|UKGBI}}\n*[[File:Flag of Awadh.svg|23px]] [[Oudh State]]\n| combatant3  = \n|commander1   = [[File:Rampur flag.svg|23px]] [[Faizullah Khan|Nawab Faizullah Khan of Rohilkhand]] \n\n[[File:Rampur flag.svg| 23px]] [[Hafiz Rahmat Khan Barech|Hafiz Rehmat Khan Barech]] {{KIA}}\n\n[[File:Rampur flag.svg|23px]] [[Abdullah Khan of Rohilkhand|Nawab Abdullah Khan of Rohilkhand]] {{KIA}}\n\n[[File:Rampur flag.svg|23px]] [[Muhammad Yar Khan of Bareilly|Nawab Muhammad Yar Khan of Bareilly]]{{KIA}}\n| commander2  = [[File:Flag of the United Kingdom.svg|23px]] [[Warren Hastings]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the British East India Company (1707).svg|23px]] [[Alexander Champion (East India Company officer)|Colonel Alexander Champion]]\n\n[[File:Flag of Awadh.svg|23px]] [[Shuja-ud-Daula|Shuja-ad-Daula]] \n| commander3  = \n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| units3      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| strength3   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| casualties3 = \n| notes       = \n| campaignbox = \n}}\nThe '''First Rohilla War''' of 1773\u20131774 was a punitive campaign by [[Shuja-ud-Daula]], [[Nawab of Awadh]] on the behalf of [[Mughal Emperor]], against the [[Rohilla]]s, Afghan highlanders settled in [[Rohilkhand]], northern India. The Nawab was supported by troops  of the [[British East India Company]], in a successful campaign brought about by the Rohillas reneging on a debt to the Nawab.\n\n==Background==\n\nHaving been driven into the mountains by the [[Maratha]]s, a few years earlier, the Rohillas had appealed for aid to Shuja-ud-Daulah, at that time an ally of the British. The Nawab demanded in return 40 rods of gold, that Rohilla chiefs refused to pay. The Nawab then decided to annex their country, and appealed to [[Warren Hastings]] for assistance, which was given in return for a sum of forty [[lakh]]s of rupees.<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911 |wstitle=Rohilla |volume=23 |page=461 |inline=1}}</ref>\n\nHastings justified his action on the ground that the Rohillas were a danger to the British as uncovering the flank of [[Awadh]].<ref name=EB1911/>\n\n==Course of the war==\nThe Rohillas under [[Hafiz Rahmat Ali Khan]] <ref>[http://www.library.upenn.edu/collections/sasia/crafts1820/introduc.html Introduction to the Eleven Illustrations of Ghulam Yahya]</ref> were defeated by Colonel [[Alexander Champion (East India Company officer)|Alexander Champion]] on 23 April 1774 at the [[Battle of Miranpur Katra]]. The decisive battle, in which Hafiz Rahmat Khan died, caused the Rohillas to flee to the mountains near Loll Dong.<ref>[http://www.india9.com/i9show/Miranpur-Katra-80142.htm Miranpur Katra in India<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n=== Guerrilla War and Siege===\nBy October 1774, the war evolved into a war of attrition. Faizullah Khan with the remaining loyal Rohillas retreated to a forest located in the hills of Lal Dang. The combined forces of the British and Awadh laid siege to the area from late August 1774 to October of the same year. Both sides were worn down and wished for peace. \n\nShah Shuja, who was suffering from cancer in his leg, wanted an early peace and thus after several attempts to break Rohilla unity under Faizullah Khan, he finally decided to release Mohabbat Khan, son of the late Hafiz Rehmat Khan in an attempt to undermine Faizullah's authority while at the same time he kept communication with Faizullah. His strategy worked and on 7 October 1774 Faizullah signed an amicable treaty of Lal dang and was granted a Princely State in the area of his choosing, leading to the creation of Rampur State. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=PRASAD |first1=ALOK |title=ROHILLA RESISTANCE AGAINST COLONIAL INTERVENTION UNDER NAWAB FAIZULLAH KHAN OF RAMPUR (1774-1794) |journal=  Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|volume=73 |pages=563\u2013572 |jstor=44156249 |year=2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Consequences==\n\nRohilkhand fell to Awadh, was plundered and occupied. The majority of the Rohillas left. They fled across the [[Ganges]] in numbers, to start a guerrilla war; or emigrated. A Rohilla state under British protection was set up in [[Rampur, Uttar Pradesh|Rampur]].\n\nThere was a [[Second Rohilla War]], in 1794.\n\n==Warren Hastings==\n\nThe war became a matter of Westminster politics during the [[Impeachment of Warren Hastings]]. Charges of destroying a nation were brought against Hastings by [[Edmund Burke]] and later [[Thomas Macaulay]].<ref name=EB1911/>\n\n==References==\n*[[John Strachey (civil servant)|John Strachey]] (1892), ''Hastings and the Rohilla War''\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.rangan-datta.info/photo/viewpic.php?gallery=41&id=206 Photo of Rohilla War Memorial at the St. John's Church compound Calcutta]\n\n\n[[