\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Wayne Messam|Messam]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Ryan]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~13,000 donors on July 12)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"ryan-fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Joe Sestak|Sestak]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n|[[Bill de Blasio|de Blasio]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~7,000 donors on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" /><ref name=\"db \"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Fourth Democratic debate\n|host          = [[CNN]]<br />''[[The New York Times]]''\n|date          = October 15, 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=CNN's Democratic Debate. Aired October 15, 2019  8-9p ET |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1910/15/se.01.html |website=transcripts.cnn.com |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CNN Hosts Democratic Primary Debate. Aired October 15, 2019 9-10p ET |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1910/15/se.02.html |website=transcripts.cnn.com |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=CNN Hosts Democratic Debate. Aired October 15, 2019 10-11:05p ET |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1910/15/se.03.html |website=transcripts.cnn.com |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n|venue         = [[Otterbein University#Rike Physical Education Center|Rike&nbsp;Physical&nbsp;Education&nbsp;Center]]<br />[[Otterbein University]]\n|location      = [[Westerville, Ohio|Westerville]], [[Ohio]]\n|leadmoderator = [[Anderson Cooper]]\n|othermoderators = [[Erin Burnett]]<br />Marc Lacey\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = CNN<br />The New York Times <br />Democratic Debate, <br />Westerville, Ohio<br />October 15, 2019\n| video1 = [https://www.facebook.com/CNNReplay/videos/432856137365607/ CNN Replay], <br />[[CNN]] ''via [[Facebook]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/CNNReplay/videos/432856137365607/ |title=CNN Replay \u2013 CNN/New York Times Democratic Presidential Debate &#124; Facebook |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| video2 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-1-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn full video \u2013 Part 1]<ref>{{cite web |title=October 15, 2019 Democratic debate full video \u2013 Part 1 |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-1-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| video3 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-2-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn full video \u2013 Part 2]<ref>{{cite web |title=October 15, 2019 Democratic debate full video \u2013 Part 2 |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-2-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| video4 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-3-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn full video \u2013 Part 3]<ref>{{cite web |title=October 15, 2019 Democratic debate full video \u2013 Part 3 |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-3-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| video5 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-4-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn full video \u2013 Part 4]<ref>{{cite web |title=October 15, 2019 Democratic debate full video \u2013 Part 4 |url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/10/16/part-4-cnn-nyt-democratic-presidential-debate-ohio-october-15-2019.cnn |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n| video6 = [https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/16/app-news-section/watch-full-cnn-nyt-democratic-debate/index.html full video \u2013 Parts 1,2,3,4]<ref>{{cite web |title=October 15, 2019 Democratic debate full video \u2013 Part 4 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/16/app-news-section/watch-full-cnn-nyt-democratic-debate/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's fourth presidential debate''' was held on Tuesday October 15, 2019 in [[Westerville, Ohio|Westerville]], [[Ohio]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/09/13/politics/october-democratic-presidential-debate/index.html |title=CNN and New York Times to co-host next Democratic presidential debate |publisher=CNN |date=September 13, 2019 |access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> from 8 to 11 p.m. EDT.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/27/politics/democratic-debate-october-one-night/index.html |title=October Democratic debate to take place on one night |author=Kyle Blaine |website=CNN |access-date=September 27, 2019}}</ref> On September 27, the DNC announced that the debate would include all 12 candidates on one night, although some had assumed it would take place on two nights since it had more than 10 participants. From left to right, the candidates were: Gabbard (who missed the previous debate), Steyer (in his first debate), Booker, Harris, Sanders, Biden and Warren (who shared center stage), Buttigieg, Yang, O'Rourke, Klobuchar, and Castro. Podium order for the debate was determined based on an average of the 10 most recently released qualifying polls. [[CNN]] anchors [[Erin Burnett]] and [[Anderson Cooper]] and ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' national editor Marc Lacey served as the debate moderators.<ref name=\"Preston_podium\"-order>{{cite web |work=[[CNN]] |date=October 3, 2019 |title=Podium order announced for the CNN/New York Times Democratic presidential debate |author=Mark Preston |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/10/02/politics/democratic-debate-podium-order/index.html}}</ref>\n\nThe debate aired exclusively on CNN, CNN International and CNN en Espa\u00f1ol, and was streamed on CNN.com's homepage and NYTimes.com's homepage. The debate also streamed live on the following Facebook Pages: CNN, CNN International, CNN Politics, CNN Replay, AC360 and Erin Burnett OutFront.\n\nIn addition, the debate was available across mobile devices via CNN's and New York Times' apps for iOS and Android, via CNNgo apps for Apple TV, Roku, Amazon Fire, Chromecast and Android TV, SiriusXM Channels 116, 454 and 795, the Westwood One Radio Network and National Public Radio.<ref>{{cite web |title=How to watch the Democratic debate tonight |last=Sullivan |first=Kate |authorlink=Kate Sullivan |date=October 15, 2019 |access-date=October 15, 2019 |website=[[CNN]] |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/15/politics/how-to-watch-democratic-debate/}}</ref>\n\nThe Ohio debate featured 12 candidates, setting a record for the highest number of candidates in one presidential debate.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n!Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/10/15/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |title=Live Tracking Each Candidate's Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |last=Cai |first=Weiyi |date=October 15, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=October 16, 2019 |last2=Lee |first2=Jasmine C. |issn=0362-4331 |last3=Patel |first3=Jugal K.}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n|22.8\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n|16.7\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n|13.3\n|-\n|[[Beto O'Rourke|O'Rourke]]\n|13.2\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n|13.1\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n|13.0\n|-\n|[[Kamala Harris|Harris]]\n|12.4\n|-\n|[[Cory Booker|Booker]]\n|11.7\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n|8.5\n|-\n|[[Julian Castro|Castro]]\n|8.4\n|-\n|[[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n|8.4\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n|7.2\n|-\n|'''Average'''\n|'''12.4'''\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Fifth debate (November 20, 2019) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nA memo released by the DNC on September 23 indicated that the qualification period for the November debate started on September 13, and ended on November 13. To qualify in terms of polling, candidates needed to reach three percent or more in four polls approved by the DNC. Alternatively, reaching five percent or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada or South Carolina was also accepted as meeting the polling threshold. To qualify in terms of donors, candidates needed to receive donations from 165,000 unique donors with 600 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/09/23/dnc-debate-1508516 |title=DNC raises threshold to make November debate stage |author=Zach Montellaro |date=September 23, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> Three candidates (Messam, O'Rourke, and Ryan) suspended their campaigns between the fourth and fifth debates.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the fifth debate<ref>{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For Fifth Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-fifth-presidential-primary-debate/ |website=Democratic National Committee |access-date=September 23, 2019 |language=en |date=September 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate needed to get at '''least three percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between September 13 and November 13, which could not be based on open-ended questions and may have covered either the national level or one of the first four primary/caucus states (Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, and South Carolina). Only one poll from each approved pollster counted towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters were the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'', [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]], ''[[Nevada Independent|The Nevada Independent]]'',<ref name=\"NevIndDNC\">{{cite tweet |last1=Ralston |first1=Jon |title=Big news: The DNC has decided that our @TheNVIndy poll conducted by @MarkMellman on the Democratic presidential race in Nevada will count as a qualifying poll for the November and December debates. Expect results soon. #WeMatter |user=RalstonReports |number=1190378181183754240 |access-date=November 4, 2019 |language=en |date=November 1, 2019}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], the [[University of New Hampshire]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings were permitted.  Organizations listed individually may have partnered with any other entity or fielded polls independently.\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate could have qualified with at '''least five percent support''' in any '''two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period.  This threshold did not require that different organizations or regions be used, but did not include national polls.\n|-\n|'''Fundraising criterion'''\n|By the November 13 deadline, a candidate needed to receive financial support from a minimum of 165,000 unique donors, with at least 600 unique donors per state in at least 20 states.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates by this order:\n(1) All criteria met.\n(2) Polling criterion met.\n(3) Donor criterion met.\n(4) No criteria met.\n* and they are further presorted within these 4 categories by polling average & polls-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the fifth debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met donor criterion<br />\n! Met four-poll criterion<br />{{small|(as of November 13)<ref name=\"pollingdata5\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=900260735 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=November 13, 2019}}</ref>}}\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of November 14)<ref name=\"pollingdata5\" />}}\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 3)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(25 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|39.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(18 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by February 20)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(25 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|21}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(18 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto35\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/20/politics/bernie-sanders-2020-24-hour-fundraising-6-million/index.html |title=Bernie Sanders raises nearly $6 million in 24 hours after 2020 launch, campaign says |author=David Wright |website=CNN}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 8)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(25 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|29.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(18 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 1)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(24 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|18.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(11 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Kamala Harris|Harris]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 5)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(23 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|6.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"politicooct30\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/30/biden-2020-poll-061903 |title=Biden's lead over Warren shrinks by half in new 2020 poll |author1=Quint Forgey |author2=Zach Montellaro |publisher=[[Politico]] |access-date=October 30, 2019 |date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by August 15)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(14 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"politico8aug \"/><ref name=\"ayaug15\">{{cite tweet |user=andrewyang |number=1161954947954544640 |title=We just passed 200,000 donors |first=Andrew |last=Yang |authorlink=Andrew Yang |access-date=September 24, 2019 |date=August 15, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by September 23)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(11 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"klobuchar-donor\" /><ref name=\"auto39\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/24/klobuchar-qualifies-for-november-debate-056454 |title=Klobuchar qualifies for November debate |author=Zach Montellaro |publisher=Politico |access-date=October 24, 2019 |date=October 24, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by August 26)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(5 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/TulsiGabbard/posts/2507348579321546 |title=Tulsi is coming back from active duty |first=Tulsi |last=Gabbard |publisher=Tulsi Gabbard on Facebook |access-date=September 24, 2019 |date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by September 23)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(13 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"steyer-donor\" /><ref name=\"politicosept8 \"/>\n|-\n| [[Cory Booker|Booker]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by September 29)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|3}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"Booker-donor\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto37\">{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/sep/29/cory-booker-2020-race-funding-goals |title=Cory Booker may quit 2020 race by Tuesday despite 'avalanche of support' |last=Martin Pengelly |publisher=The Guardian |access-date=September 29, 2019 |date=September 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Julian Castro|Castro]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by September 23)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"castro-qualifies\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto36\">{{cite tweet |user=TrackerDebate |number=1175457989991575553 |title=Donor update: A @JulianCastro fundraising email says he is \"inches\" away from 175K donors |last=The Debate Tracker |publisher=The Debate Tracker on Twitter |access-date=September 23, 2019 |date=September 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Marianne Williamson|Williamson]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(~140,000 donors on October 4)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"auto34\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/warren-surpasses-biden-latest-fundraising-haul-falls-short/story?id=65978063 |title=Warren surpasses Biden in latest fundraising hall but falls short of Sanders |first1=Soo Rin |last1=Kim |first2=Kendall |last2=Karson |publisher=ABC News |date=October 4, 2019 |access-date=October 5, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~28,000 donors on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Bullock]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~17,000 donors on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~8,000 donors on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n|[[Joe Sestak|Sestak]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Beto O'Rourke|O'Rourke]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(before June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|3.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"nytimes_map\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/08/02/us/politics/2020-democratic-fundraising.html |title=Detailed Maps of the Donors Powering the 2020 Democratic Campaigns |first=Josh |last=Katz |work=New York Times |access-date=September 23, 2019 |date=June 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Ryan]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~13,000 donors on July 12)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"ryan-fundraising\" />\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Wayne Messam|Messam]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}} {{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| colspan=6 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Fifth Democratic debate\n|host          = [[MSNBC]]<br />''[[The Washington Post]]''\n|date          = November 20, 2019\n|venue         =Oprah Winfrey Soundstage 1,<ref name=\"D5location\" /><br />Van Horn Rd,<ref>{{cite AV media |date=November 4, 2019 |title=Oprah Winfrey Sound Stage at Tyler Perry Studios will host November Democratic debate in Atlanta |medium=Video clip |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bzy22tRDbP0 |access-date=November 14, 2019 |location=Tyler Perry Studios (Van Horn Rd) |publisher=Youtube}}</ref><br />[[Tyler Perry Studios]]\n|location      = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n|leadmoderator = \n|othermoderators = [[Rachel Maddow]]<br />[[Andrea Mitchell]]<br />[[Kristen Welker]]<br />[[Ashley Parker]]<ref name=\"nbcoct23\" />\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's fifth presidential debate''' was held on November 20, 2019 from 9 to 11:20&nbsp;p.m. ET,<ref name=\"nbcoct23\" /> at [[Tyler Perry Studios]] in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/breaking-georgia-host-next-democratic-debate/l34ozoORYdlqpwa2HflOkL/amp.html |title=BREAKING: Georgia to host November presidential debate |author=Greg Bluestein |date=October 8, 2019 |work=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/464920-fifth-dnc-debate-to-be-held-nov-20-in-georgia?amp=1&amp_recirculation=1 |title=Fifth DNC debate to be held Nov. 20 in Georgia |author=Rachel Frazin |date=October 8, 2019 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ajc \"/> It was moderated by [[Rachel Maddow]], [[Andrea Mitchell]], [[Kristen Welker]] and [[Ashley Parker]].<ref name=\"nbcoct23 \"/>\n\nThe candidates who qualified were Biden, Booker, Buttigieg, Gabbard, Harris, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren and Yang.<ref name=\"Fifthlineup \"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n!Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/11/20/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |title=Live Tracking Each Candidate's Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |last=Cai |first=Weiyi |date=November 20, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=November 20, 2019 |last2=Lee |first2=Jasmine C. |last3=Patel |first3=Jugal K.}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n|13.5\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n|12.9\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n|12.8\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n|11.8\n|-\n|[[Cory Booker|Booker]]\n|11.5\n|-\n|[[Kamala Harris|Harris]]\n|11.5\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n|11.0\n|-\n|[[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n|9.2\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n|8.4\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n|6.8\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Sixth debate (December 19, 2019) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nA memo released by the DNC on October 25 indicated that the qualification period for the December debate started on October 16, and ended on December 12. To qualify in terms of polling, candidates had to reach four percent or more in four polls approved by the DNC. Alternatively, reaching six percent or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina was also accepted as meeting the polling threshold. To qualify in terms of donors, candidates had to receive donations from 200,000 unique donors with 800 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.<ref name=\"poloct25\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/25/dnc-raises-thresholds-for-december-debate-000297 |title=DNC raises thresholds for December debate |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=October 25, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=October 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the sixth debate<ref name=\"poloct25 \"/>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate needed at '''least four percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between October 16 and December 12, which could not be based on open-ended questions and covered either the national level or one of the first four primary/caucus states (Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, and South Carolina). Only one poll from each approved pollster counted towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters were the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'', [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]], ''The Nevada Independent'',<ref name=\"NevIndDNC\" /> ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], the [[University of New Hampshire]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings were permitted.  Organizations listed individually could partner with any other entity or field polls independently.\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate qualified with at '''least six percent support''' in any '''two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period.  This threshold did not require that different organizations or regions be used, but did not include national polls.\n|-\n|'''Fundraising criterion'''\n|By the December 12 deadline, a candidate needed to receive financial support from a minimum of 200,000 unique donors, with at least 800 unique donors per state in at least 20 states.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates by this order:\n(1) All criteria met.\n(2) Polling criterion met.\n(3) Donor criterion met.\n(4) No criteria met.\n* and they are further presorted within these 4 categories by polling average & polls-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the sixth debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met donor criterion<br />\n! Met four-poll criterion<br />{{small|(as of December 13)<ref name=\"pollingdata6\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=1424726684 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>}}\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of December 13)<ref name=\"pollingdata6\" />}}\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 3)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(22 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|36.25}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by February 20)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(22 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|21.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto35\" />\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 8)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(22 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|26.25}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 1)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(21 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|21.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(14 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"politicooct29\">{{cite web |author1=Trent Spiner |author2=Zach Montellaro |title=Sanders leads, Biden slumps in N.H. poll |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/29/bernie-sanders-joe-biden-new-hampshire-poll-061068 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=December 20, 2019 |date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by October 26)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5.25}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"klobuchar-donor2\">{{cite tweet |user=ZachMontellaro |number=1187802324749733888 |title=Two updates here: Klobuchar's campaign told @ec_schneider that she's crossed the 200,000 donor threshold. And Booker sent a fundraising email putting him at a bit over 178,000 donors |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=October 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"polnov1 \"/>\n|-\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by December 3)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(4 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"politicodec3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/03/tom-steyer-qualifies-for-december-debate-074874 |title=Tom Steyer qualifies for December debate |author=Zach Montellaro |date=December 3, 2019 |access-date=December 3, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by August 15)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(4 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|4.25}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"ayaug15 \"/><ref name=\"nprdec10\">{{ci