on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~8,000 donors on June 30)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Deval Patrick|Patrick]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Kamala Harris|Harris]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 5)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(10 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"polnov1\">{{cite web |author=Zach Montellaro |title=Kamala Harris qualifies for December primary debate |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/03/kamala-harris-december-primary-debate-064630 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=November 3, 2019 |date=November 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Bullock]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Joe Sestak|Sestak]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| colspan=6 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Sixth Democratic debate\n|host          = ''[[PBS NewsHour]]''<br />''[[Politico]]''\n|date          = December 19, 2019\n|venue         = [[Gersten Pavilion]]<br />[[Loyola Marymount University|Loyola&nbsp;Marymount&nbsp;University]]\n|location      = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n|leadmoderator = \n|othermoderators = Tim Alberta<br />[[Yamiche Alcindor]]<br />[[Amna Nawaz]]<br />[[Judy Woodruff]]<ref name=\"deadlinenov27 \"/>\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = PBS NewsHour<br />Politico <br />Democratic Debate, <br />Los Angeles, California, <br />December 19, 2019\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DFJru2XOrtY Live Stream Recording], <br />[[Politico]] ''via [[YouTube]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DFJru2XOrtY |title=WATCH LIVE: The PBS NewsHour/POLITICO Debate |access-date=2020-02-25 |via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n| video2 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GVcD7c-_KEY Live Stream Recording], <br />[[PBS NewsHour]] ''via [[YouTube]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GVcD7c-_KEY |title=6th Democratic Debate hosted by PBS NewsHour and Politico |access-date=2020-02-25 |via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's sixth presidential debate''' was held on December 19, 2019 at 8 p.m. ET<ref name=\"cbsdec17 \"/> at [[Loyola Marymount University]] in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]],<ref name=\"politiconov8 \"/> and was hosted by ''[[PBS NewsHour]]'' and ''[[Politico]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/10/25/politico-pbs-december-democratic-debate-057271 |title=POLITICO to partner with PBS NewsHour to host December Democratic debate |first=Quint |last=Forgey |date=October 25, 2019 |publisher=Politico |access-date=October 26, 2019}}</ref> It was initially set to be held at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"uclaoct29\">{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/stories/royce-hall-will-be-site-of-december-democratic-debate |title=UCLA's Royce Hall will be site of December Democratic debate |publisher=UCLA Newsroom |date=October 29, 2019 |access-date=November 5, 2019}}</ref> However, the DNC announced on November 6 that UCLA was no longer hosting the debate due to a labor dispute.<ref name=\"politiconov6\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/11/06/ucla-dnc-democratic-debate-066905 |title=DNC says UCLA will no longer host upcoming Democratic debate |author=Quint Forgey |date=November 6, 2019 |access-date=December 19, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> Three candidates (Sestak, Bullock and Harris) suspended their campaigns between the fifth and sixth Democratic debates; Harris would have qualified for the sixth debate had her campaign continued.\n\nGabbard, a few days before failing to qualify for the debate,<ref name=\"cbsdec17 \"/> announced on December 9 that she would not participate regardless of whether she qualifies.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/tulsi-gabbard-out-democrats-debate-polls |title=Tulsi Gabbard opts out of next Dem debate as poll deadline looms |last=Wulfsohn |first=Joseph |date=December 9, 2019 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |access-date=December 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe debate aired on Politico.com, PBS, and CNN.<ref name=\"bidec17 \"/>\n\nThe candidates who qualified were Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren and Yang.<ref name=\"cbsdec17 \"/> Highlights included: an exchange between Buttigieg, Warren, and Sanders about campaign financing (including mention of a Buttigieg fundraiser in a [[Napa Valley AVA|Napa Valley]] [[wine cave]]), differences between Klobuchar and Buttigieg on the issue of experience, and a discussion about health care between Sanders and Biden. The candidates were in agreement about the [[Impeachment inquiry against Donald Trump|impeachment of Donald Trump]], which had been approved by the House of Representatives the day before. Sanders and Klobuchar had a disagreement about the [[United States\u2013Mexico\u2013Canada Agreement]], with the former opposed to and the latter in favor of ratification. Yang, the only candidate of color, expressed lament that Kamala Harris and Cory Booker were absent, and declared that his [[Basic income|universal-basic-income proposal]] would diversify the field. Sanders, Biden, and Warren parried a question about age.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/19/democratic-debate-highlights-088428 |title=Wine caves, health care clashes and age attacks: Biggest debate moments |date=December 19, 2019 |access-date=December 21, 2019 |author1=Marc Caputo |author2=Nolan D. McCaskill |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/20/politics/pbs-politico-debate-highlights/index.html |title=8 takeaways from the sixth Democratic presidential debate |date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 21, 2019 |author1=Eric Bradner |author2=Dan Merica |work=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Steyer stated that climate change would be his top priority as president, and the issue was discussed at length by all the candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/5753060/debate-live-updates/ |title=7 Democrats Face Off In The Last Democratic Presidential Primary Debate of 2019: Highlights |author1=Madeleine Carlisle |author2=Tara Law |author3=Josiah Bates |date=December 20, 2019 |access-date=December 21, 2019 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/19/democratic-debate-recap-highlights-and-top-moments-from-la.html |title=Here are the top moments from the sixth Democratic debate in Los Angeles |author1=Yelena Dzhanova |author2=Lauren Hirsch |author3=Kevin Breuninger |author4=Tucker Higgins |date=December 20, 2019 |website=CNBC}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese government censored a live feed of the debate after moderator [[Judy Woodruff]] asked Pete Buttigieg if the U.S. should boycott the [[2022 Winter Olympics]] in Beijing over China's alleged [[Human rights in China|human rights abuses of Uyghur citizens]].<ref>{{cite web |website=CNN World |title=Chinese government cuts US Democratic debate feed during Xinjiang discussion |date=December 20, 2019 |author1=Ben Westcott |author2=David Culver |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/12/19/asia/democratic-debate-china-feed-cut-intl-hnk/index.html?iid=ob_lockedrail_topeditorial}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n!Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/12/19/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |title=Live Tracking Each Candidate's Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |last=Cai |first=Weiyi |date=December 19, 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=December 19, 2019 |last2=Lee |first2=Jasmine C. |last3=Smart |first3=Charlie}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n|20.5\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n|19.9\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n|19.6\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n|19.6\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n|15.5\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n|11.8\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n|10.9\n|-\n|}\n\n== Debates in 2020 ==\n\n=== Seventh debate (January 14, 2020) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nA memo released by the DNC on December 20 indicated that the qualification period for the January debate started on November 14, 2019, and ended on January 10, 2020. A candidate needed to meet both polling and donor criteria. Candidates had to reach 5% or more in four polls approved by the DNC, or 7% or more in two DNC-approved polls conducted in Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina. In addition, candidates must have received donations from 225,000 unique donors, including 1,000 unique donors in 20 different states, territories or the District of Columbia.<ref name=\"538dec20\">{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/five-democrats-have-qualified-for-the-january-debate-who-else-might-make-it/ |title=Five Democrats Have Qualified For The January Debate \u2014 Who Else Might Make It? |author=Geoffrey Skelley |date=December 20, 2019 |work=[[FiveThirtyEight]] |access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> The candidates who qualified were Biden, Buttigieg,  Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer and Warren.<ref name=\"politicojan11 \"/>  This debate stage featured all of the candidates from the sixth debate except for Yang. Steyer qualified with 2 early-state polls on the penultimate day to qualify, while the other five all qualified much earlier. Yang and Booker met the fundraising criterion but failed to meet the polling criteria. Bloomberg met polling criteria but not the fundraising criterion, as he is not currently asking for donations.<ref name=\"pollingdata7\" />  Three candidates (Castro, Williamson and Booker) suspended their campaigns between the sixth and seventh debates, with Booker dropping out two days after the qualifying candidates were announced.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the seventh debate<ref name=\"DNC-seventh-rules\">{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Details For Seventh Democratic Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-details-for-seventh-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/ |publisher=[[Democratic National Committee|DNC]] |access-date=December 20, 2019 |language=en |date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate needed '''at least five percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between November 14, 2019 and January 10, 2020, which could not be based on open-ended questions and must have covered either the national level or one of the first four primary/caucus states (Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, and South Carolina). Only one poll from each approved pollster counts towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters were the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'', [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]], ''The Nevada Independent''/Mellman Group, ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], the [[University of New Hampshire]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings are permitted. Organizations listed individually can partner with any other entity or field polls independently.\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate qualified with at '''least seven percent support''' in any '''two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period. This threshold did not require that different organizations or regions be used, but also did not include national polls.\n|-\n|'''Fundraising criterion'''\n|By the January 10, 2020 deadline, a candidate needed to receive financial support from a minimum of 225,000 unique donors, with at least 1,000 unique donors per state in at least 20 states and/or territories.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates by this order:\n(1) All criteria met.\n(2) Polling criterion met.\n(3) Donor criterion met.\n(4) No criteria met.\n* and they are further presorted within these 4 categories by polling average & polls-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the seventh debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met donor criterion<br />\n! Met four-poll criterion<br />{{small|(as of January 10, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata7\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=1399569380 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>}}\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of January 10, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata7\" />}}\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 3, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(16 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|36}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(13 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by February 20, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(16 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|23.75}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(13 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto35\" />\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 8, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(16 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|22}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(13 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 1, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|21}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(10 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"politicooct29 \"/>\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by December 20, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|6.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"klobuchar-polls\">{{cite tweet |user=reidepstein |number=1208055343898513408 |title=Deleted incorrect tweet. FIVE candidates are qualified for January. Biden/Bernie/Warren/Pete/Klobuchar are in. Yang needs two more 5%+ polls, Steyer needs three more by Jan 10 to qualify. |last=Epstein |first=Reid |date=December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(by January 3, 2020)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|10.67}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/09/tom-steyer-qualifies-democratic-debate-096915 |title=Surging Steyer qualifies for Democratic debate |author=Zach Montellaro |work=[[Politico]] |date=January 9, 2020 |access-date=January 9, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| {{No}}{{efn|name=bloom_donors}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(5 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5.75}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by August 15, 2019)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|<ref name=\"ayaug15 \"/><ref name=\"nprdec10 \"/>\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(216,751  donors by January 4, 2020)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"nov7Gabbard\" /><ref name=\"auto13\" /><ref name=\"hilldec10 \"/>\n|-\n| [[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~28,000 donors on June 30, 2019)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~8,000 donors on June 30, 2019)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Deval Patrick|Patrick]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n|[[Cory Booker|Booker]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(by December 20, 2019)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|<ref name=\"klobuchar-donor2\" /><ref name=\"hillnov21 \"/>\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Julian Castro|Castro]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(~200,000 donors on December 5, 2019)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"jcdec5 \"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/02/us/politics/julian-castro-dropping-out.html |title=Juli\u00e1n Castro Ends Presidential Run: 'It Simply Isn't Our Time' |first1=Jennifer |last1=Medina |first2=Matt |last2=Stevens |date=January 2, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Marianne Williamson|Williamson]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(~140,000 donors on October 4, 2019)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"auto34\" />\n|-\n| colspan=6 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Seventh Democratic debate\n|host          = [[CNN]]<br />''[[Des Moines Register]]''\n|date          = January 14, 2020\n|venue         = [[Drake University|Drake&nbsp;University]]\n|location      = [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Iowa]]\n|leadmoderator =  [[Wolf Blitzer]]<ref name=\"cnndmr\" />\n|othermoderators = Brianne Pfannenstiel<br />[[Abby Phillip]]<ref name=\"cnndmr\" />\n}}\nThe '''Democratic Party's seventh presidential debate''' was held from 8 to 10:15&nbsp;p.m. CT<ref name=\"Jan14time \"/> on Tuesday, January 14, 2020, at [[Drake University]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa|Des Moines]], [[Iowa]]. It was hosted by [[CNN]] and ''[[The Des Moines Register]]''.<ref name=\"politicodec12 \"/> Several sources noted an exchange between Warren and Sanders. They discussed Warren's accusation that Sanders told her privately that women could not successfully win the presidency. Sanders flatly denied this accusation and pointed to his deference to Warren before running for president in 2016. Warren insisted that Sanders had said women could not win and pointed out that the women on stage had not lost any election, while the men on stage had lost 10 elections combined.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/live/2020/jan/14/democratic-debate-live-news-tonight-bernie-sanders-elizabeth-warren-biden-latest-updates-2020 |title=Democratic debate: Warren appears to reject handshake with Sanders after clash \u2013 as it happened |last1=Greeve |first1=Joan E. |date=January 14, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the debate when candidates were shaking hands with one another, Warren was seen declining a handshake from Bernie Sanders; the two candidates then appeared to argue with each other. It was later revealed that Warren commented to Sanders, \"I think you called me a liar on national TV.\" Sanders replied, \"Let's not do it right now. You want to have that discussion, we'll have that discussion. You called me a liar.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/15/politics/bernie-sanders-elizabeth-warren-debate-audio/index.html |title=Exclusive: Warren accused Sanders in tense post-debate exchange of calling her a 'liar' on national TV |author1=Kyle Blaine |author2=Jeff Zeleny |author3=Marshall Cohen |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n!Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/01/14/us/politics/debate-speaking-time.html |title=Which Candidates Got the Most Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |last=Cai |first=Weiyi |date=January 14, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Leatherby |first2=Lauren |last3=Smart |first3=Charlie |access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| 18.9\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| 17.8\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| 17.6\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| 16.7\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| 16.3\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| 12.6\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Eighth debate (February 7, 2020) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nThe qualifications for the eighth debate were similar to those for the January debate (5% nationally/early states, or 7% in early states, this time excluding Iowa) except for the added provision that all candidates who gained at least one pledged delegate in the [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa caucus]] (which is expected to apply only to candidates supported by at least 15% of the final votes statewide or in a district) would also automatically qualify for the debate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dnc-outlines-qualifying-criteria-abc-news-debate-adds/story?id=68337999 |title=DNC outlines qualifying criteria for ABC News debate, adds new delegate threshold |work=[[ABC News]] |date=January 17, 2020 |access-date=January 19, 2020 |author=Kendall Karson}}</ref> Candidates had until February 6 to qualify.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/17/us/politics/next-democratic-debate-qualify.html |title=Democrats Can Qualify for the Next Debate by Winning a Single Delegate in Iowa |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=January 17, 2020 |access-date=January 18, 2020 |author=Maggie Astor}}</ref>\n\nThe candidates who qualified included Biden, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer, Warren, and Yang.<ref name=\"Eighthlineup \"/>\n\nOne candidate (Delaney) suspended his campaign between the seventh and eighth debates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/31/john-delaney-drops-out-2020-election-109854 |title=Delaney drops out of White House race days before Iowa |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=January 31, 2020 |date=January 31, 2020 |author=Quint Forgey}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the eighth debate<ref name=\"DNC-eighth-rules\">{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For New Hampshire Democratic Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-new-hampshire-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/ |publisher=[[Democratic National Committee|DNC]] |access-date=January 17, 2020 |language=en |date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate needed '''at least five percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between December 13, 2019 and February 6, 2020, which can not be based on open-ended questions and must cover either the national level or the remaining early states of New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina. Only one poll from each approved pollster counted towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters are the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]]/[[PBS Newshour]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]],''[[The New York Times]]''/[[Siena College Research Institute|Siena College]], ''The Nevada Independent''/Mellman Group, [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], the [[University of New Hampshire]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings are permitted. Organizations listed individually can partner with any other entity or field polls independently.\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate qualified with at least '''seven percent support''' in '''any two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period in the remaining early states of New Hampshire, Nevada, or South Carolina. This threshold does not require that different organizations or regions be used, but also does not include national polls.\n|-\n|'''Fundraising criterion'''\n|By the February 6, 2020 deadline, a candidate needed to receive financial support from a minimum of 225,000 unique donors, with at least 1,000 unique donors per state in at least 20 states and/or territories.\n|-\n|'''Delegate Threshold'''\n| A candidate will automatically qualify if he or she gained at least one pledged delegate from [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]] for the Democratic National Convention even if no other requirements are met.  Because the opinions of Iowa voters are included in this way, polls of Iowa can no longer be considered qualifying under either the Four Poll Threshold or the Early State Polling Threshold.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates as follows:\nFirst candidates are ordered by the number of delegates they have been pledged (or are projected to be pledged, for states with a multi-step process) in primaries and caucuses that have already occurred.\nSecond, ties are broken based on the number of other criteria met.\nThird, candidates still tied are sorted based on polling.\nFourth, candidates still tied are sorted based on donor count (but not date by which a donor threshold is reached).\nAny remaining ties are listed alphabetically.\n-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the eighth debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met donor criterion<br />\n! Met four-poll criterion<br />{{small|(as of February 7, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata8\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=496516214 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>}}\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of February 7, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata8\" />}}\n! Met delegate threshold<ref name=\"IA-official\">{{cite web |title=IDP Caucus 2020 |url=https://results.thecaucuses.org/ |website=results.thecaucuses.org |publisher=Iowa Democratic Party |access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 1, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(14 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|16.25}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(14 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"politicooct29 \"/>\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by February 20, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|26.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(12 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" /><ref name=\"auto35\" />\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 8, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|17.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by July 3, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|31.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=\"CNN\" /><ref name=\"HillJuly30\" />\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by December 20, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|8}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(1 delegate)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"klobuchar-polls\" />\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{nowrap|{{small|(by January 3, 2020)}}}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|11.67}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"auto1\" />\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by August 15, 2019)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|<ref name=\"ayaug15 \"/><ref name=\"jangabdonors\" />\n|-\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| {{No}}{{efn|name=bloom_donors}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(7 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|9}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(by January 26, 2020)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|5.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"jangabdonors\">{{cite tweet |last1=Jester |first1=Julia |title=With today's plethora of polls, @AndrewYang becomes the 7th candidate to make it onto the February DNC debate stage in #FITN New Hampshire.@TulsiGabbard now has 2 of 4 qualifying polls \u2014 her campaign confirms to @NBCNews that Gabbard has reached the 225k unique donor threshold. |user=JulesJester |number=1221451594719514626 |access-date=January 26, 2020 |language=en |date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~28,000 donors on June 30, 2019)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"NYT fundraising\" />\n|-\n| [[Deval Patrick|Patrick]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(~8,000 donors on June 30, 2019)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|0}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/john-delaney-says-hes-dropping-out-of-presidential-race/2020/01/31/69187b22-41fe-11ea-b5fc-eefa848cde99_story.html |title=John Delaney says he's dropping out of presidential race |first=Amy B |last=Wang |date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n|-\n| colspan=7 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Eighth Democratic debate\n|host          = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC News]]<br />[[WMUR-TV]]<br />[[Apple News]]\n|date          = February 7, 2020\n|venue         = [[Saint Anselm College]]\n|location      = [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], [[New Hampshire]]\n|othermoderators = Linsey Davis<br />Monica Hernandez<br />[[David Muir]]<br />Adam Sexton<br />[[George Stephanopoulos]]\n}}\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = ABC News <br />Democratic Debate, <br />Manchester, New Hampshire, <br />February 7, 2020\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_JCTY6MxJ4I Live Stream Recording], <br />[[ABC News]] ''via [[YouTube]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_JCTY6MxJ4I |title=WATCH LIVE: Democratic Presidential Candidates Debate in New Hampshire &#124; ABC News Live |access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's eighth presidential debate''' was held from 8\u201310:30&nbsp;p.m. ET<ref name=\"NHABC \"/> on Friday, February 7, 2020, at [[Saint Anselm College]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], [[New Hampshire]]. It was hosted by ABC's New Hampshire affiliate [[WMUR-TV]] and [[Apple News]].<ref name=\"abdec12\">{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/primary-debates-2020-announced-including-abc-news-debate/story?id=67463859 |title=First 4 primary debates of 2020 announced, including ABC News debate in New Hampshire |author=Kendall Karson |date=December 12, 2019 |work=[[ABC News]] |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEmerging as frontrunners after the Iowa caucuses, Buttigieg and Sanders came under attack by other candidates. Klobuchar questioned Buttigieg on his lack of political experience, whereas Biden pressed Sanders to clarify how he would fund [[Single-payer healthcare#United States|Medicare For All]] and brought up his past stances on gun control, citing Sanders's votes against the [[Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act|Brady Bill]] in the 1990s. Moderator Linsey Davis also inquired Buttigieg on the rise in marijuana-related incarcerations of African Americans in [[South Bend, Indiana|South Bend]] during his tenure as mayor, which he attributed to \"systemic racism\". Candidates also voiced praise for Senator [[Mitt Romney]] of Utah, who was the only Republican senator to vote against Donald Trump's acquittal in his [[Impeachment trial of Donald Trump|Senate impeachment trial]] two days earlier, and  Lt. Col. [[Alexander Vindman]], who was fired from the [[United States National Security Council|National Security Council]] by Trump after serving as a key witness on the trial.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bradner |first1=Eric |last2=Merica |first2=Dan |last3=Krieg |first3=Gregory |title=7 takeaways from the Democratic debate in New Hampshire |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/08/politics/february-debate-recap/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=February 8, 2020 |date=February 8, 2020}}</ref> On the topic of campaign finance, Elizabeth Warren stated that political action committees had assisted all of the non-billionaire candidates except for Amy Klobuchar and herself. The ''New York Times'' challenged this claim by pointing out two PACs that have funded Warren's 2020 campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://westlakelegal.com/highlights-from-the-democratic-debate-in-new-hampshire/ |title=Highlights from the Democratic Debate in New Hampshire |first1=Reid |last1=Epstein |first2=Shane |last2=Goldmacher |work=The New York Times |date=February 8, 2020 |access-date=February 9, 2020}}</ref> Another prominent issue discussed in the debate was abortion, with several candidates pledging to only support [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] nominees who will uphold abortion rights and pushed for the [[Codification (law)#United States|codification]] of ''[[Roe v. Wade]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Saul |first1=Stephanie |title=Democrats Discuss Abortion Rights in Depth at Debate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/07/us/politics/abortion-litmus-test-debate.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 8, 2020 |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n! Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Almukhtar |first1=Sarah |last2=Bui |first2=Quoctrung |last3=Cai |first3=Weiyi |title=Which Candidates Got the Most Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/02/07/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |access-date=February 8, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| 20.1\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| 19.6\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| 18.5\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| 16.5\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| 15.9\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| 13.9\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| 8.1\n|-\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Ninth debate (February 19, 2020) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nThe DNC announced on January 31 that it was eliminating the donor threshold as a debate qualification requirement for any debate following the New Hampshire debate on February 7,<ref name=\"politicojan31\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/01/31/dnc-shifts-debate-requirements-opening-door-for-bloomberg-110017 |title=DNC overhauls debate requirements, opening door for Bloomberg |author1=Zach Montellaro |author2=Sally Goldenberg |author3=Christopher Cadelago |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=January 31, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> which prompted criticism from several candidates as it was perceived to accommodate Bloomberg, who is not accepting individual donations. The polling thresholds were drastically increased since the last debate, with candidates now having to reach 10% in DNC-approved national polls or 12% in early state polls conducted in Nevada and South Carolina. Candidates who won at least one pledged delegate in the [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa caucuses]] or [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire primary]] were automatically qualified for the debate. Candidates had until February 18 to qualify.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Epstein |first1=Reid J. |last2=Stevens |first2=Matt |title=D.N.C. Rules Change for Nevada Debate Could Open Door for Bloomberg |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/31/us/politics/dnc-democratic-debate-rules.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe candidates who qualified included Biden, Bloomberg, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, and Warren. Three candidates (Yang, Bennet, and Patrick) suspended their campaigns between the eighth and ninth debates.<ref name=\"Ninthlineup\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the ninth debate<ref name=\"DNC-ninth-rules\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/31/democrats-drop-donor-requirement-for-debates-opening-door-for-bloomberg.html |title=Democrats ditch donor requirement for debates, meaning Bloomberg could qualify |date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=January 20, 2020 |author=Higgins, Tucker |publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref name=\"DNC-press-release9\">{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For Nevada Democratic Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-nevada-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/ |website=Democrats |publisher=DNC |access-date=February 3, 2020 |language=en |date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate needed '''at least ten percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between January 15 and February 18, 2020, which could not be based on open-ended questions and must have covered either the national level or the remaining early states of Nevada or South Carolina. Only one poll from each approved pollster counted towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters were the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]], ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''The Nevada Independent''/Mellman Group, [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings were permitted. Organizations listed individually could partner with any other entity or field polls independently.  Additionally, the DNC elected to add the Nevada poll commissioned by the [[Las Vegas Review-Journal]] and [[AARP]] Nevada, and fielded by WPA Intelligence.<ref name=\"DNC-added-Nevada\" />\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate theoretically could have qualified with at least '''twelve percent support''' in '''any two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period in either of the remaining early states, Nevada or South Carolina. This threshold does not require that different organizations or regions be used, but also does not include national polls.  However, no poll from the original list of qualifying organizations in either Nevada or South Carolina was published during the qualifying period.<ref name=\"pollingdata9\" /> With only the single poll of Nevada added by the DNC available as an early state poll, meeting the early state threshold was impossible.\n|-\n|'''Delegate Threshold'''\n| A candidate could also automatically qualify if he or she gained at least one pledged delegate from [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]] or [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire]] for the Democratic National Convention even if no other requirements were met.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates as follows:\nFirst candidates are ordered by the number of delegates they have been pledged (or are projected to be pledged, for states with a multi-step process) in primaries and caucuses that have already occurred.\nSecond, ties are broken based on the number of other criteria met.\nThird, candidates still tied are sorted based on polling.\nAny remaining ties are listed alphabetically.\n-->\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the ninth debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met four-poll criterion<ref name=\"pollingdata9\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=994931539 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(not applicable, only 1 poll)<ref name=\"pollingdata9\" />}}\n! Met delegate threshold<ref name=\"IA-official\" /><ref name=\"NHAPResults\">{{cite news |author1=Steve Peoples |author2=Kathleen Ronayne |author3=Hunter Woodall |title=Sanders edges Buttigieg in NH, giving Dems 2 front-runners |url=https://apnews.com/3d16640da86f6e5c30b1b5fba8d91936 |access-date=February 12, 2020 |work=AP NEWS |publisher=Associated Press |date=February 11, 2020}}</ref>\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(5 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|11.75}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(23 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|27.75}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(21 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|14.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}{{hs|5.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(7 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|27.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(5 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|14.75}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}{{hs|11}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"DNC-added-Nevada\" />\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Deval Patrick|Patrick]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| colspan=6 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Ninth Democratic debate\n|host          = [[NBC News]]<br />[[MSNBC]]<br />''The Nevada Independent''\n|date          = February 19, 2020\n|venue         = [[Paris Las Vegas]]\n|location      = [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]]\n|othermoderators = Vanessa Hauc<br />[[Lester Holt]]<br />[[Hallie Jackson]]<br />[[Jon Ralston]]<br />[[Chuck Todd]]\n}}{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = NBC News / MSNBC <br />Democratic Debate, <br />Las Vegas, Nevada, <br />February 20, 2020\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TZkV0ISxcQY Live Stream Recording], <br />[[NBC News]] ''via [[YouTube]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RjPhkrfOesc |title=2020 Democratic Presidential Debate &#124; NBC News (Live Stream Recording) |access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's ninth presidential debate''' was held from 6\u20138&nbsp;p.m. PST<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/feb/19/nevada-democratic-debate-sanders-bloomberg-klobuchar |title='Gloves will be off': Nevada debate could be pivotal for Bloomberg |first=Sam |last=Levin |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=February 19, 2020 |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> on Wednesday, February 19, 2020, at [[Paris Las Vegas]] in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]]. It was hosted by [[NBC News]] and [[MSNBC]], in partnership with ''[[The Nevada Independent]]''.<ref name=\"abdec12 \"/>\n\nBloomberg, who made his debate stage debut after qualifying only a day prior,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Epstein |first1=Reid J. |last2=Astor |first2=Maggie |title=Michael Bloomberg Surges in Polls and Qualifies for 2 Democratic Debates |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/18/us/politics/bloomberg-debate-poll-numbers.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 18, 2020}}</ref> was widely regarded by multiple news outlets as having performed poorly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/19/politics/who-won-democratic-debate/index.html |title=Chris Cilliza's winners and losers from the 9th Democratic debate |website=[[CNN]] |last1=Cilliza |first1=Chris |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Montanaro |first1=Domenico |title=6 Takeaways From The Nevada Democratic Debate |url=https://www.npr.org/2020/02/20/807639778/6-takeaways-from-the-nevada-democratic-debate |website=[[NPR]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Bloomberg's political and personal record came under heavy scrutiny by other candidates, including his previous support of [[Stop-and-frisk in New York City|stop-and-frisk]] policies during his tenure as [[mayor of New York City]]. The controversial program, which disproportionately targeted racial minorities, was referred to by Biden as \"abhorrent\" and \"a violation of every right people have\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/483774-rivals-rip-into-bloomberg-over-stop-and-frisk-policy-at-debate |title=Rivals rip Bloomberg over stop-and-frisk policy at debate |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |last1=Coleman |first1=Justine |date=February 19, 2020 |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Warren reprimanded Bloomberg for his recently resurfaced derogatory comments on women and called for him to rescind the [[non-disclosure agreement]]s he signed with several of [[Bloomberg L.P.|his company]]'s former female employees over sexual harassment and workplace discrimination, accusing Bloomberg of attempting to \"muzzle\" them.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Egan |first1=Lauren |title=#MeToo moment: Bloomberg on debate hot seat for comments about women, NDAs |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/bloomberg-hot-seat-comments-about-women-non-disclosure-agreements-n1139411 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSanders's electability was also brought up in the debate, when moderator [[Lester Holt]] mentioned the findings of a recent ''NBC News/Wall Street Journal'' poll which showed that two thirds of American voters would not be comfortable with a socialist presidential candidate; Sanders retorted by touting his wide lead over other candidates in the same poll.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph A. |title=Bernie Sanders challenges NBC moderator over question about unfavorable poll on socialism: 'Who was winning?' |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/bernie-sanders-challenges-lester-holt-over-question-unfavorable-poll-socialism |website=[[Fox News]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Mark |title=NBC News/WSJ poll: Sanders opens up double-digit lead nationally in Democratic race |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/meet-the-press/nbc-news-wsj-poll-sanders-opens-double-digit-national-lead-n1138191 |website=[[NBC News]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 18, 2020}}</ref> Bloomberg criticized Sanders's advocacy of [[democratic socialism]] by comparing it to communism, which Sanders dismissed as a \"cheap shot,\" arguing that his economic policies were closer to [[Nordic model|Nordic social democracy]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stableford |first1=Dylan |title='Cheap shot': Sanders fires back when Bloomberg goes after 'socialism' |url=https://news.yahoo.com/bernie-bloomberg-socialist-three-homes-billionaire-communism-042240189.html |website=[[Yahoo! News]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Bowden |first1=John |title=Sanders: 'Cheap shot' for Bloomberg to attack 'democratic socialism' as 'communism' |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/483783-sanders-cheap-shot-for-bloomberg-to-attack-democratic-socialism-as |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> Buttigieg, meanwhile, branded both Sanders and Bloomberg as polarizing figures who would further divide the party if one of them were to receive the nomination.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hirsch |first1=Lauren |title=Pete Buttigieg turns fire on 'socialist' Bernie Sanders amid Bloomberg pile-on |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/19/nevada-democratic-debate-buttigieg-turns-fire-on-socialist-bernie-sanders.html |website=[[CNBC]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHealthcare was another issue discussed by the candidates, in light of the [[Culinary Workers Union]]'s recent criticism that Sanders's [[Medicare for All]] policy would replace their existing union healthcare in favor of a government plan.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Kate |title=Culinary Union says Bernie Sanders would end its health care |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/12/politics/culinary-union-bernie-sanders-health-care/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 12, 2020}}</ref> In response, Sanders defended his plan by saying that it would expand, rather than take away, healthcare benefits for union members.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Carlisle |first1=Madeleine |last2=Bates |first2=Josiah |title=Six Democratic Candidates Take the Nevada Debate Stage Tonight at a Crucial Moment in the 2020 Primary Cycle. Follow Along Live |url=https://time.com/5787015/democratic-debate-live-february-19/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |language=en |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> Warren attacked Buttigieg and Klobuchar on their more moderate healthcare plans, likening their lack of details to a \"[[Microsoft PowerPoint|PowerPoint]]\" presentation and \"[[Post-it Note]]\" respectively.<ref>{{cite web |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Paul |title=Warren calls Klobuchar's health care plan 'like a Post-it Note' in fiery debate moment |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/19/politics/debate-elizabeth-warren-amy-klobuchar-post-it-note/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> On the other hand, Klobuchar argued that Sanders's Medicare for All proposal would be too radical to garner enough support in the Senate, whereas Buttigieg expressed disapproval at the idea of letting the government decide what healthcare plan is best for unions, calling it \"condescension and arrogance\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sullivan |first1=Peter |title=Democratic clash over 'Medicare for All' reaches new heights in debate |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/483769-democratic-clash-over-medicare-for-all-reaches-new-heights-in-debate |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe televised debate drew a combined 19.7 million viewers on NBC and MSNBC, making it the most-watched Democratic primary debate of all time.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Darcy |first1=Oliver |title=Monster ratings for Las Vegas debate break record for Democratic Party |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/20/media/democratic-debate-ratings-las-vegas/index.html |website=[[CNN Business]] |access-date=February 20, 2020 |date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n! Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |last1=Almukhtar |first1=Sarah |last2=Leatherby |first2=Lauren |last3=Cai |first3=Weiyi |title=Which Candidates Got the Most Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/02/19/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |access-date=February 19, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| 16.6\n|-\n| [[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| 15.9\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| 15.4\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| 14.8\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| 13.4\n|-\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| 13.0\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Tenth debate (February 25, 2020) ===\n==== Qualification ====\nThe qualification criteria remained largely unchanged from the last debate, with candidates having to either garner at least 10% support in DNC-approved national polls or 12% in early state polls conducted in the remaining state of South Carolina in order to meet the polling threshold. Candidates could also qualify via the delegate threshold by winning at least one pledged delegate in [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]], [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire]] or [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|Nevada]]. The qualification deadline for the debate was February 24.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Karson |first1=Kendall |title=DNC unveils qualifications for last Democratic debate ahead of South Carolina primary |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/dnc-unveils-qualifiers-democratic-debate-ahead-south-carolina/story?id=69008355 |website=[[ABC News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAll candidates still in the race at the time (Biden, Bloomberg, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Sanders, Steyer and Warren), except for Gabbard, qualified for the debate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quinn |first1=Melissa |last2=Perry |first2=Tim |last3=Ewall-Wice |first3=Sarah |title=Who has qualified for the South Carolina Democratic debate? |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-carolina-debate-who-has-qualified-for-south-carolina-democratic-presidential-debate/ |website=[[CBS News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the tenth debate<ref name=\"DNC-added-Nevada\" /><ref name=\"DNC-tenth-rules\">{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For South Carolina Democratic Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-south-carolina-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/ |website=Democrats |access-date=February 18, 2020 |language=en |date=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''Four-Poll Threshold'''\n|A candidate will need '''at least ten percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between February 4, 2020 and February 24, 2020, which can not be based on open-ended questions and must cover either the national level or the remaining early state of South Carolina. Only one poll from each approved pollster counts towards meeting the threshold for each region. The approved pollsters are the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]]/''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[CBS News]]/[[YouGov]], [[CNN]], [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]]/''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', [[NBC News]]/[[Marist Poll|Marist]],''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], ''[[USA Today]]''/[[Suffolk University Political Research Center|Suffolk]], and [[Winthrop University]]. For organizations that appear in pairs with other entities, only polls conducted by the listed pairings are permitted. Organizations listed individually can partner with any other entity or field polls independently.  The DNC may choose to add an additional South Carolina-specific poll sponsor to this list.\n|-\n|'''Early State Polling Threshold'''\n|Alternatively to the four-poll threshold, a candidate will qualify with at least '''twelve percent support''' in '''any two polls''' from the same list of organizations and time period in the remaining early state, South Carolina. This threshold does not require that different organizations or regions be used, but also does not include national polls.\n|-\n|'''Delegate Threshold'''\n| A candidate will automatically qualify if he or she gains at least one pledged delegate from any of the three preceding early states of [[2020 Iowa Democratic caucuses|Iowa]], [[2020 New Hampshire Democratic primary|New Hampshire]], or [[2020 Nevada Democratic caucuses|Nevada]] for the Democratic National Convention even if no other requirements are met.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates as follows:\nFirst candidates are ordered by the number of delegates they have been pledged (or are projected to be pledged, for states with a multi-step process) in primaries and caucuses that have already occurred.\nSecond, ties are broken based on the number of other criteria met.\nThird, candidates still tied are sorted based on polling.\nAny remaining ties are listed alphabetically.\n-->\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the tenth debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met four-poll criterion<br />{{small|(as of February 24, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata10\">{{cite web |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |title=2020 Democratic polls |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=419062485 |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=February 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n! Met early state polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of February 24, 2020)<ref name=\"pollingdata10\" />}}\n! Met delegate threshold<ref name=\"IA-official\" /><ref name=\"NHAPResults\" /><ref name=\"AP-Nevada-dels\">{{cite web |title=AP Delegate Count,100 |url=https://apnews.com/a0cba3b58ed445d6bed6bc86af90b50c |website=AP NEWS |publisher=Associated Press |access-date=February 24, 2020 |date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n! Qualified for debate\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(9 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p6_6_3_3|6 from national; 3 from South Carolina}}{{hs|29.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(45 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(5 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p4_4_1_1|4 from national 1 from South Carolina}}{{hs|11.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(26 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(9 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p6_6_3_3}}{{hs|24}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(7 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p6_6_1_1|6 from national; 1 from South Carolina}}{{hs|15}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(8 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|7}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(7 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(6 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p6_6_0_0|6 from national}}{{hs|15.5}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}{{efn|name=p0_0_3_3|3 from South Carolina}}{{hs|12.5}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/23/steyer-debate-stage-south-carolina-116826 |title=Steyer will return to debate stage in South Carolina |work=[[Politico]] |date=February 23, 2020 |access-date=February 23, 2020 |author=Zach Montellaro}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}{{hs|1}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Tenth Democratic debate\n|host          = [[CBS News]]<br />[[Congressional Black Caucus]] Institute\n|date          = February 25, 2020\n|venue         = [[Gaillard Center]]\n|location      = [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]]\n|othermoderators = [[Margaret Brennan]]<br />[[Major Garrett]]<br />[[Gayle King]]<br />[[Norah O'Donnell]]<br />[[Bill Whitaker (journalist)|Bill Whitaker]]\n}}\n\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = CBS News <br />Democratic Debate, <br />Charleston, South Carolina, <br />February 25, 2020\n| video1 = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_JCTY6MxJ4I Live Stream Recording], <br />[[CBS News]] ''via [[YouTube]]''<ref name=\"2020-02-25-SC-CBS-DD\">{{cite web |author1=CBS News |authorlink1=CBS News |title=Watch full South Carolina Democratic debate |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=klDbFuxmXrA |website=YouTube |access-date=27 February 2020 |date=2020-02-25 |quote=Streamed live on Feb 25, 2020  Debate starts at 1:00:00}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's tenth presidential debate''' was held from 8\u201310&nbsp;p.m. ET on Tuesday, February 25, 2020, at the [[Gaillard Center]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina|Charleston]], [[South Carolina]]. It was hosted by [[CBS News]] and the [[Congressional Black Caucus]] Institute in partnership with [[Twitter]], and aired on [[CBS]] and [[BET]].<ref name=\"abdec12 \"/>\n\nFollowing his landslide victory in Nevada the prior week, Sanders was targeted by several other candidates who attempted to dampen his momentum going into the upcoming [[2020 South Carolina Democratic primary|South Carolina]] and [[Super Tuesday#2020|Super Tuesday]] primaries. Biden hit Sanders on the issue of gun control by drawing a contrast between Sanders's voting record and his own, noting that he was a consistent supporter of more stringent gun regulations throughout his Senate career. Biden highlighted his role in passing legislation to expand [[universal background check]]s and extend [[Waiting period#For firearms purchases|waiting periods for purchasing guns]], while pointing out that Sanders previously had a relatively moderate stance on gun control, voting against the [[Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act|Brady Bill]] and in favor of the [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act|PLCAA]] during his tenure as a congressman.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vigdor |first1=Neil |title=Bernie Sanders, Confronted on Immunity for Gun Manufacturers, Says That Was a \u2018Bad Vote\u2019 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/us/politics/bernie-sanders-brady-bill-guns.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> However, his claim that \"150 million people have been killed since 2007\" by guns was fact-checked by [[CNN]] as being incorrect, with a Biden campaign spokesperson suggesting that he might have intended to say 150,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact checking the South Carolina debate |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/25/politics/charleston-south-carolina-debate-fact-check/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Sanders expressed regret at his decisions, admitting that he has \"cast thousands of votes, including bad votes\", and noted that he currently has a D-minus rating from the [[National Rifle Association]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Reston |first1=Maeve |title=Democratic candidates try to put Bernie Sanders in the hot seat in last debate before crucial primaries |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/25/politics/cbs-democratic-presidential-debate/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nForeign policy was extensively discussed by the candidates, which took up about 25 minutes of the debate.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Segers |first1=Grace |last2=Watson |first2=Kathryn |last3=Linton |first3=Caroline |last4=Quinn |first4=Melissa |title=Democrats try to stop Sanders' momentum in fiery debate |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-updates/democratic-debate-south-carolina-cbs-news-recap/ |website=[[CBS News]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> Sanders and Bloomberg clashed over past comments they have made regarding foreign authoritarian leaders; Bloomberg emphasized recent allegations that Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] was trying to prop up the Sanders campaign.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Easley |first1=Jonathan |title=Bloomberg attacks Sanders over reports of Russian interference |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/484633-bloomberg-attacks-sanders-over-reports-of-russian-interference |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> When Sanders's praise for [[Fidel Castro]]'s literacy programs in Cuba on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' was brought up by Bloomberg, Sanders responded by calling out Bloomberg's refusal to call China's [[paramount leader]] [[Xi Jinping]] a dictator in an interview,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Goldmacher |first1=Shane |last2=Epstein |first2=Reid J. |title=Highlights From the Democratic Debate in South Carolina |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/us/politics/democratic-debate-tonight-time.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> and pointed out that [[Barack Obama]] had also previously praised Cuba's healthcare and education. This provoked a reaction from Biden, who said that while Obama did acknowledge Cuba's progress in increasing life expectancy during a 2016 town hall, he did not \"in any way suggest that there was anything positive about the Cuban government\" and proceeded to condemn the dictatorial regime.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bernal |first1=Rafael |title=Biden, Sanders battle over Cuba, Obama |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/484654-biden-sanders-battle-over-cuba-obama |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe debate moderators received staunch criticism for focusing too much on narrowly-focused policy issues, failure to keep control of the candidates' speaking times, allowing candidates to interrupt other candidates during their allotted speaking times, applying the debate rules regarding giving candidates time to respond to personal attacks in a non-equitable way, and for permitting the audience to boo and jeer certain candidates without consequence. Both Biden and Sanders criticized the moderators on stage for failing to enforce the debate rules.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Grynbaum |first1=Michael M. |title=Coronavirus? Yes, but First: Soda Ban. CBS Criticized After a Chaotic Debate. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/us/politics/cbs-democratic-debate-moderators.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Budryk |first1=Zack |title=Moderators come under criticism online over contentious debate |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/484647-debate-moderators-come-under-criticism-online |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> The crowd's negative reception of Sanders led to the proliferation of rumors on social media that the debate audience had been \"stacked against\" him, pointing to the high entry costs which ranged from $1,750 to $3,200 as evidence. The [[Democratic National Committee]] has denied this claim, explaining that the debate tickets were allocated among political organizations (DNC, [[Congressional Black Caucus|CBCI]] and [[South Carolina Democratic Party|SCDP]]) and media entities (CBS and Twitter) hosting the debate as well as participating candidates' campaigns, with each campaign being given an equal quota. Tickets were guaranteed to sponsors, and the ticket costs referred to the cost of sponsorship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Peters |first1=Jeremy W. |title=With Tickets $1,750, Debate Audiences Are Elite of the Elite. But That\u2019s Not New. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/25/us/politics/south-carolina-debate-audience.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! Candidates\n!Airtime (min.)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2020/02/25/us/elections/debate-speaking-time.html |title=Which Candidates Got the Most Speaking Time in the Democratic Debate |last=Cai |first=Weiyi |date=February 25, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |last2=Collins |first2=Keith |last3=Leatherby |first3=Lauren |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| 15.5\n|-\n|[[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| 13.6\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| 13.4\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| 12.9\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| 12.6\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| 11.6\n|-\n|[[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| 7.1\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Eleventh debate (March 15, 2020) ===\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Eleventh Democratic debate\n|host          = [[CNN]]<br />[[Univision]]<br />[[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]]\n|dates         = March 15, 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/2003/15/se.03.html|title=CNN Democration Presidential Primary Debate. Aired 8-10p ET  |publisher=[[CNN]] |website=transcripts.cnn.com|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n|venue         = CNN studio<ref name=\"CNNmar12\" />\n|location      = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|leadmoderator = [[Jake Tapper]]<ref name=\"CNNmar12\"/>\n|othermoderators = [[Dana Bash]]<br />[[Ilia Calder\u00f3n]]<ref name=\"CNNmar12\"/>\n}}\n\n{{external media\n| float  = right\n| topic  = CNN/Univision/Congressional Hispanic Caucus Democratic Debate, <br />Washington, D.C., March 15, 2020\n| video1 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-1-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 1]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-1-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 1: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n| video2 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-2-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 2]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-2-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 2: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n| video3 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-3-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 3]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-3-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 3: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n| video4 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-4-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 4]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-4-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 4: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n| video5 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-5-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 5]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-5-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 5: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n\n| video6 = [https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-6-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn full video \u2013 Part 6]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2020/03/16/part-6-entire-cnn-univision-debate-washington-dc-sot-vpx.cnn|title=Part 6: Entire CNN-Univision Democratic debate - CNN Video|accessdate=2020-03-16 |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref>\n}}\n[[CNN]], [[Univision]], and the [[Congressional Hispanic Caucus]] <!-- \"BOLD\" is not a formatting mistake.  It is part of the name. --> hosted the eleventh debate in [[Washington, DC]] from 8 P.M. to 10 P.M. Eastern Time.<ref>{{cite web | last =  Reid J. Epstein, Katie Glueck and Astead W. Herndon | title = Live Updates Ahead of Sunday\u2019s Democratic Debate  | publisher = [[The New York Times]]  | date = March 15, 2020 | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/us/politics/democratic-debate-tonight-time.html  | accessdate = 2020-03-15 }}</ref>\n\nFive candidates (Steyer, Buttigieg, Klobuchar, Bloomberg, and Warren) suspended their campaigns between the tenth and eleventh debates.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kinnard |first1=Meg |title=Billionaire Tom Steyer ends 2020 Democratic presidential bid |url=https://apnews.com/05d111c102cb0a113a59046407171e6f |access-date=March 1, 2020 |work=AP NEWS |publisher=Associated Press |date=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51700771 |title=Pete Buttigieg drops out of Democratic race for White House |date=March 2, 2020 |work=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-51710945 |title=Amy Klobuchar ends bid to challenge Trump |date=March 2, 2020 |work=[[BBC]] |access-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"BloombergOut\">{{cite news |last1=Morin |first1=Rebecca |title=After spending millions of his own dollars, Bloomberg ends his bid for the Democratic nomination |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2020/03/04/election-2020-michael-bloomberg-drops-out-of-presidential-race/2595841001/ |access-date=March 4, 2020 |work=USA TODAY}}</ref><ref name=\"WarrenOut\">{{cite news |last1=Herndon |first1=Astead W. |last2=Goldmacher |first2=Shane |title=Elizabeth Warren, Once a Front-Runner, Will Drop Out of Presidential Race |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/politics/elizabeth-warren-drops-out.html |access-date=March 5, 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> On March 6, the DNC announced that qualification would be based on \"earning at least 20 percent of delegates awarded by March 15\",<ref name=hillmarch6>{{cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/486348-new-standards-eliminate-tulsi-gabbard-from-next-democratic-debate|title=New standards eliminate Tulsi Gabbard from next Democratic debate|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|author=J. Edward Moreno|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> as calculated by the [[Associated Press]] or [[CNN]].<ref name=\"DNC-rules-release11\">{{cite web |title=DNC Announces Qualification Criteria For Arizona Democratic Presidential Primary Debate |url=https://democrats.org/news/dnc-announces-qualification-criteria-for-arizona-democratic-presidential-primary-debate/ |website=Democrats |publisher=Democratic National Committee |accessdate=March 12, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Democratic National Committee announced on March 10 that the debate would no longer allow a live audience, nor would press (beyond CNN and Univision) be allowed to attend, due to fears about the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|spread of the coronavirus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ktar.com/story/3014272/dems-say-no-live-audience-at-phoenix-debate-amid-coronavirus-fears/|title=Dems say no live audience at Phoenix debate amid coronavirus fears|date=2020-03-10|website=KTAR.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the Democratic National Committee announced that the March 15 debate, originally scheduled to take place at the Arizona Federal Theatre<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ap.org/live-and-location-services/events/arizona-democratic-debate|title=Arizona Democratic Debate|website=Associated Press|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref> in Phoenix, Arizona, would instead be held at CNN's studio in Washington, DC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/4d727288195cca13588c388c5ff706ab|title=Pandemic forces CNN into a debate unique to campaign cycle|date=2020-03-16|website=AP NEWS|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref> It also announced that [[Jorge Ramos (news anchor)|Jorge Ramos]] was no longer a moderator because he had contact with a person with coronavirus.<ref name=\"CNNmar12\"/>\n\n==== Qualification ====\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the eleventh debate'''\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Candidate\n! colspan=2 | 20% delegate threshold \n! rowspan=2 | Qualified<br />for debate\n! rowspan=2 class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n! [[Associated Press|AP]]<ref name=\"AP-11-delegates\">{{cite web |title=Delegate Tracker |url=https://interactives.ap.org/delegate-tracker/ |website=interactives.ap.org |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n! [[CNN]]<ref name=\"CNN-11-delegates\">{{cite web |title=View 2020 primary and caucus results |url=https://www.cnn.com/election/2020/primaries-and-caucuses |website=www.cnn.com |publisher=CNN |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(890 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(809 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=hillmarch6/>\n|-\n| [[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(736 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(666 delegates)}}\n| {{Yes}}\n| <ref name=hillmarch6/>\n|-\n| [[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"bimar6\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(71 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(44 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Michael Bloomberg|Bloomberg]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(61 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(24 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(26 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(26 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(7 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(7 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 delegates)}}\n| {{No}}\n| \n|-\n| colspan=6 class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\nThe debate was primarily focused on the COVID-19 pandemic, which was discussed for 17 minutes and 45 seconds, with Biden claiming the Trump administration rejected test kits from the [[WHO]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politifact.com/factchecks/2020/mar/16/joe-biden/biden-falsely-says-trump-administration-rejected-w/ |website=Politifact |title=Biden falsely says Trump administration rejected WHO coronavirus test kits (that were never offered)  |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/11th-democratic-debate-2020-topic-tracker-washington-dc-n1159766|title=NBC Debate Topic Tracker|date=2020-03-15|website=NBC News|accessdate=2020-03-16}}</ref> Both candidates also compared the pandemic to that of the [[List of Ebola outbreaks|Ebola epidemic]].\n{{Clear}}\n\n=== Potential twelfth debate ===\nIn an interview with ''[[Politico]]'' regarding the March 15 debate, a [[Democratic National Committee|DNC]] official confirmed a twelfth debate was still being planned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/06/joe-biden-bernie-sanders-debate-122998|title=DNC sets up Biden vs. Bernie clash in next debate|last=Montellaro|first=Zach|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> Two candidates (Gabbard and Sanders) suspended their campaigns between the eleventh and twelfth debates, leaving Biden as the only remaining major candidate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rep. Tulsi Gabbard drops out of the Democratic presidential primary, endorses Joe Biden |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/19/tulsi-gabbard-drops-out-of-the-democratic-presidential-primary.html |last1=Dzhanova|first1=Yelena|last2=Kim|first2=Sunny|accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=CNBC |date=March 19, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Bernie Sanders suspends his presidential campaign|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/04/08/bernie-sanders-suspends-his-presidential-campaign-175137|last1=Otterbein|first1=Holly|last2=Siders|first2=David|accessdate=April 8, 2020 |work=Politico |date=April 8, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Prior to suspending his campaign, Sanders stated that he planned to participate in the debate.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/politics/sanders-plans-to-participate-in-april-dnc-debate/ar-BB11EMMX|title=Sanders plans to participate in April DNC debate|last=Coleman|first=Justin|website=MSN|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Biden dismissed the idea, however, and replied, \"My focus is just dealing with [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|this crisis]] right now. I haven\u2019t thought about any more debates. I think we\u2019ve had enough debates. I think we should get on with this.\"<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=ericbradner|number=1242867881383284736|title=Joe Biden on Bernie Sanders' aides saying he'd debate in April: \"My focus is just dealing with this crisis right now. I haven\u2019t thought about any more debates. I think we\u2019ve had enough debates. I think we should get on with this.\"|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=2020-03-25|website=@ericbradner|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> On April 8, Sanders dropped out of the Democratic Primary for President, leaving only Joe Biden competing. As a result, there would, assumbly, be no more debates, however the DNC has not confirmed anything as of yet.\n\n== Incidents and controversies ==\n{{Overly detailed|section|details = the section contains too many minor disputes and overrates their importance and long-term relevance. There is also excessive detail about individual public figures' responses to these controversies|date=March 2020}}\n\n=== Climate change debate ===\nOn April 22, 2019, [[Jay Inslee]] proposed that the DNC dedicate one of its presidential debates to [[climate change]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://medium.com/@Jay_Inslee/my-fellow-democratic-candidates-for-president-lets-debate-climate-change-1e237329c0ec |title=My Fellow Democratic Candidates for President: Let's Debate Climate Change |last=Inslee |first=Jay |date=April 22, 2019 |work=Medium |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> giving candidates a chance to elaborate in full detail on how they intend to implement [[climate action]] and achieve the goals presented by the [[Green New Deal]] (a progressive climate resolution proposed by Democratic members of the House of Representatives).<ref name=\"ClimateDebate\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/29/climate-change-democrats-2020-1465563 |title=A climate debate could be risky for Dems \u2014 but many want it anyway |last=Adragna |first=Anthony |date=May 29, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> Recent polls of both Democratic voters and the electorate in general had identified this topic to be of the highest importance (for example, a [[CNN]] poll<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cdn.cnn.com/cnn/2019/images/03/09/rel1_ia1.pdf |title=CNN/Des Moines Register/Mediacom Iowa Poll (embargoed for release: Saturday March 9) |date=March 9, 2019 |publisher=CNN |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> found 80% of Democrats wanted presidential candidates to make climate change a top priority, and a [[Morning Consult]] poll<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/f/?id=0000016a-dc4a-df31-a1ee-fdea3be80002 |title=Morning Consult + Politico National Tracking Poll (Project 190534, May 17-19, 2019) |date=May 19, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> of registered voters nationwide found that 63% said it's either important or a top priority for Congress to pass a bill to address climate change). Despite support from seven other candidates ([[Bernie Sanders]], [[Elizabeth Warren]], [[Kirsten Gillibrand]], [[Julian Castro]], [[Michael Bennet]], [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|John Delaney]]<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1137048484740292609 |user=ZachMontellaro |title=.@JohnDelaney was in POLITICO HQ yesterday and I asked him about this, for what it's worth. He thinks there should be dedicated debates for climate change and health care |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=June 7, 2019}}</ref> and [[Seth Moulton]]<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1137052856236875777 |user=sethmoulton |title=.@JayInslee is right, we need a climate debate. While we're at it, let's have a national security debate too. The American people deserve to hear all candidates' positions on these critical issues. |last=Moulton |first=Seth |date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>), several progressive and environmental groups ([[Sierra Club]], [[CREDO Action]], [[Sunrise Movement]], [[Friends of the Earth Action]], [[Public Citizen]], [[350.org|350 Action]], [[MoveOn]], [[School strike for climate|Youth Climate Strike]]), at least two dozen Democratic lawmakers from the House and Senate,<ref name=\"ClimateDebate\" /> and over 52,000 signatories of a petition,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://act.credoaction.com/sign/climate-debate |title=Tell the Democratic National Committee: Hold a climate debate |publisher=CREDO Action |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref> the DNC turned down the idea of limiting some of their debates to only one debate topic.<ref name=\"NoClimateDebate\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/05/dnc-opts-against-climate-change-debate-inslee-says-1355867 |title=DNC opts against climate change debate, Inslee says |last=Adragna |first=Anthony |date=June 5, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=June 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"DNCdebatesPerez\" /> On June 29, 2019, however, the DNC referred to a committee a proposal \"calling for an official debate on climate change\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaufman |first=Alexander C. |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/dnc-climate-debate_n_5d1a5df7e4b082e5536de208 |title=Democrats To Consider Climate Debate Amid Mounting Pressure |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=July 1, 2019 |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref> On August 22, the resolutions committee voted to reject the proposal.<ref>{{cite web |author=Benjamin Siegel |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/democratic-party-officials-oppose-climate-change-debate/story?id=65126611 |title=Democratic Party officials oppose debate focused on climate change |work=[[ABC News]] |date=August 22, 2019 |access-date=August 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Steve Bullock's qualification for first debate ===\nAfter [[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]] received 1% in an open-ended ABC News/''Washington Post'' poll, controversy arose as the DNC's official qualification rules, published on February 14 and updated on May 9,<ref name=\"DNC-qualify\" /> did not state whether open-ended polls would count towards qualification. The DNC later stated during rule guidance given on June 10 and 11,<ref name=\"DNCcertificationForm\" /> that \"polls based on open-ended questions will not be considered\". This additional rule was initially orally communicated between DNC chairman [[Tom Perez]] and the Bullock campaign in March 2019, and was only publicly confirmed via a statement to a [[Politico]] reporter on June 6,<ref name=\"NewQualStatus\" /> but was never confirmed in writing by any primary DNC sources ahead of the qualification deadline.<ref name=\"BullockUncertainty\">{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/06/13/steve-bullock-democrats-debate-1362900 |title=Gov. Bullock demands entry into first DNC debate |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |date=June 13, 2019 |work=Politico |access-date=June 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 12, the Bullock campaign wrote a certification letter to the DNC claiming that Bullock qualified for participation in the first debate through the polling criteria (as they believed the open-ended poll from ABC News/''Washington Post'' should be counted as Bullock's third qualifying poll, according to the official published rules).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/f/?id=0000016b-4f1f-df00-a9fb-6f7f81b80000 |title=Dear Chairman Perez |last=Ridder |first=Jennifer |date=June 12, 2019 |work=Politico |access-date=June 13, 2019}}</ref> If Bullock had been deemed a qualifying candidate by the DNC, then 21 total candidates would have qualified by the polling criteria. However, the DNC explicitly limited the debate stage to 20 candidates, so that would have triggered tiebreak rules. Bullock and [[Eric Swalwell]] were tied for the 20th spot with each candidate having 1% polling averages and three qualifying polls with exactly 1% support. In that scenario, the DNC would have had to accept inviting 21 candidates, or invent a supplementing final tiebreak rule (for example, drawing lots for the last spot, or deciding the tie by their number of unique donors).<ref name=\"BullockUncertainty\" /> However, Bullock's certification letter was rejected and he failed to qualify for the first debate,<ref name=\"PoliticoDraw1\" /> though he qualified for the second debate.<ref name=\"BullockJuly\" />\n\n=== Debate protests ===\n\n==== Second debate protest ====\nOn the second night of the second debate, protesters motivated by the death of [[Death of Eric Garner|Eric Garner]] and the continued employment of Staten Island police officer Daniel Pantaleo shouted during [[Bill de Blasio]]'s opening remarks, and then entirely halted [[Cory Booker]]'s, disrupting the debate for nearly 30 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.silive.com/news/2019/08/eric-garner-supporters-shout-fire-pantaleo-interrupting-mayor-cory-booker-during-democratic-debate.html |title=Eric Garner supporters shout \"fire Pantaleo,\" interrupting mayor, Cory Booker during Democratic debate |last=Kashiwagi |first=Sydney |date=August 1, 2019 |website=silive.com |language=en-US |access-date=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Third debate protest ====\nDuring the closing statements for the third debate, in which candidates were asked to recall moments of resilience after a professional setback, protesters interrupted [[Joe Biden]] for approximately two minutes. According to Jess Davidson, they shouted \"we are [[Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals|DACA]] recipients; our lives are at risk!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/protesters-interrupt-joe-biden-during-third-democratic-debate/ |title=Protesters interrupt Joe Biden during third Democratic debate |author=J. Clara Chan |publisher=The Wrap |date=September 12, 2019 |access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> The Trump campaign accused the protesters of having insensitive timing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/live-updates/election-2020/third-democratic-debate-analysis-and-fact-checking/trump-campaign-defends-biden-from-protesters/ |title=Trump campaign defends Biden from protesters |first=Colby |last=Ikowitz |work=The Washington Post |date=September 12, 2019 |access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Ninth debate protest ====\nImmigrant rights protestors interrupted Biden's closing statement.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/joe-bidens-closing-remarks-interrupted-protesters-raices-chanting-no-kids-cages-1488166 |title=Joe Biden's Closing Remarks Interrupted by Protesters From RAICES Chanting 'No Kids In Cages' |author=Jeffery Martin |publisher=Newsweek |date=February 20, 2020 |access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Tulsi Gabbard disputes with DNC ===\n\n==== Pollster selection and poll frequency ====\nOn August 23, Gabbard's campaign protested the failure of the DNC to release \"their criteria for selecting the 16 polling organizations they deem 'certified'\" for qualifying candidates for the third debate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.civilbeat.org/beat/gabbard-campaign-asks-dnc-to-revise-debate-criteria/ |title=Gabbard Campaign Asks DNC To Revise Debate Criteria |last=Blair |first=Chad |date=August 23, 2019 |website=Honolulu Civil Beat |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> In the campaign's statement, they listed 26 polls in which Gabbard reached the 2% threshold and alleged that certain \"DNC-certified\" polls were rated lower than non-certified polls by organizations such as the [[American Research Group]] and ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'', and questioned why only four qualifying polls were released following the second debate, while fourteen were released following the first debate; and why only two polls were released in the first two weeks after the second debate while six polls were released in the first two weeks after the first debate.<ref name=\"auto32\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/458551-gabbard-hits-dnc-over-mysteriously-incoherent-poll-criteria-for-debates |title=Gabbard hits DNC over poll criteria for debates |date=August 23, 2019 |author=Rebeccca Klar |website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |language=en-US |access-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref> The campaign further argued that the lack of polling was \"particularly harmful to candidates with lower name-recognition.\"<ref name=\"auto32\" /> They called on the DNC to revise the set of polls it considers for qualifying and also asked them \"to hold true to their promise and make adjustments to the process now to ensure transparency and fairness.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thestarpress.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/08/03/qualified-third-debate-candidates/1909474001/ |title=As debate lineup solidifies, some 2020 Democrats cry foul over polling requirements |last=Spangler |first=Todd |last2=Aschbrenner |first2=Annah |website=The Star Press |language=en |access-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto33\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/08/29/democratic-debate-2019-who-made-the-third-presidential-debate/2131404001/ |title=Lineup cut in half: Here's who made the third Democratic presidential debate |last=Aschbrenner |first=Annah |last2=Wu |first2=Nicholas |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other campaigns, including those of [[Michael Bennet 2020 presidential campaign|Michael Bennet]], [[Tom Steyer]], and [[Marianne Williamson 2020 presidential campaign|Marianne Williamson]] also criticized the unclear criteria, and overall lack, of qualifying polls.<ref name=\"auto33\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/08/29/755148906/debate-stage-cut-in-half-for-1-night-september-showdown |title=Debate Stage Cut In Half For 1-Night September Showdown |website=[[NPR]] |language=en |date=August 29, 2019 |author=Jessica Taylor |access-date=September 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/458603-steyer-calls-on-dnc-to-expand-polling-criteria-for-debates |title=Steyer calls on DNC to expand polling criteria for debates |first=Tal |last=Axelrod |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=August 23, 2019 |access-date=August 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Qualifying polls for October debate ====\nOn September 8, a ''[[Washington Post]]''/[[ABC News]] poll was released. An initial report from ABC claimed that Gabbard had not received the 2% necessary for the poll to count as a qualifying poll, but the Gabbard campaign announced that she had indeed received the 2% necessary for the poll to count as a qualifying poll, citing the ''Washington Post'' figures directly.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Langer |first1=Langer |title=Warren gains, Harris slips -- and the room for movement is vast |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/warren-gains-harris-slips-room-movement-vast/story?id=65414558 |access-date=September 10, 2019 |work=ABC News |date=September 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |number=1171233419277168640 |user=CullenYossarian |title=@Tulsi Gabbard's Campaign Announces Third Qualifying Poll for October Debate|author Tiernen, Cullen |date=September 9, 2019}}</ref> To further complicate matters, ''[[FiveThirtyEight]]'' claimed that it had received confirmation from the DNC that the poll did not count for Gabbard but the Gabbard campaign countered by stating that no official DNC ruling had been delivered.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Skelley |first1=Geoffrey |title=Who Will Make The Fourth Democratic Debate? |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/at-least-11-candidates-will-make-the-fourth-democratic-debate/ |access-date=September 10, 2019 |work=FiveThirtyEight |date=September 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |number=1170718272746119175 |user=Geofferyvs |title=Just got confirmation from DNC that the ABC/WaPo figure that counts toward debate qualification will be the adult sample, just as it was with ABC/WaPo's July poll.|author Skelley, Geoffery |date=September 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Cocke |first1=Sophie |title=Gabbard says she's closer to the debate stage,despite national reports to the contrary |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2019/09/09/breaking-news/gabbard-says-shes-closer-to-the-debate-stage-despite-national-reports-to-the-contrary/ |access-date=September 10, 2019 |work=StarAdvertiser |date=September 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe confusion stemmed from the fact that the poll data was presented with two sets of results: one of all adults, and one of registered voters. Gabbard reached 1% among all adults and 2% among registered voters. An approved poll conducted on July 1 was conducted similarly, but it is unclear which category was used for the qualification for the debates, as no candidate had 2% in one category and 1% in the other.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/context/sept-2-5-2019-washington-post-abc-news-poll/d4e18b36-79bf-492d-91e3-d1c7a49d37e2/ |title=Sept. 2-5, 2019 Washington Post-ABC News poll |date=September 8, 2019 |author=Marisa Schultz |website=[[Washington Post]] |language=en-US |access-date=September 10, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"PollingData3and4\" /> Gabbard later reached 2% in two other qualifying polls, allowing her to qualify for the fourth debate.<ref name=\"nytsept24 \"/>\n\n==== Threatened boycotts ====\nOn October 10, Gabbard threatened to boycott the fourth debate, saying that she believed the DNC and the media were rigging the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/tulsi-gabbard-threatens-boycott-upcoming-debate-claiming-dnc/story?id=66183235 |title=Gabbard threatens to boycott upcoming debate |author1=Beatrice Peterson |author2=Justin Gomez |publisher=[[ABC News]] |date=October 10, 2019 |access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> On October 14, Gabbard announced that she would be attending the debate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/465640-gabbard-vows-to-attend-debate-after-threatening-boycott |title=Gabbard says she will attend debate after threatening boycott |first=Zack |last=Budryk |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=October 14, 2019 |access-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> On December 9, Gabbard announced that she would boycott the sixth debate, and that instead she would be prioritizing campaigning in New Hampshire and South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/tulsi-gabbard-declines-join-december-democratic-debate-regardless-qualification-1476347%3f |title=Tulsi Gabbard Declines to Join December Democratic Debate Regardless of Qualification |first=Matt |last=Keeley |date=December 9, 2019 |access-date=December 10, 2019 |work=Newsweek}}</ref> She failed to qualify for the sixth debate by the deadline, December 12.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fox6now.com/2019/12/14/7-candidates-qualify-for-dnc-presidential-primary-debate/ |title=7 candidates qualify for DNC presidential primary debate |date=December 14, 2019 |agency=CNN Wire Service |access-date=December 15, 2019 |website=Fox 6 Now}}</ref>\n\n==== Eleventh debate qualification ====\nOn March 3, as [[Super Tuesday]] results were announced, DNC communications director Xochitl Hinojosa tweeted that the qualification threshold would likely increase, giving the reason that almost 2,000 delegates would have been allocated by the time of the debate.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=XochitlHinojosa|number=1235009904634728448|title=We have two more debates-- of course the threshold will go up. By the time we have the March debate, almost 2,000 delegates will be allocated. The threshold will reflect where we are in the race, as it always has.|date=March 3, 2020|access-date=March 4, 2020|work=[Twitter]]}}</ref> This tweet was sent after Gabbard apparently received a delegate and would qualify for the March debate, per the previous three debates' threshold of one delegate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tulsi-gabbard-may-have-qualified-for-the-next-dem-debate-2020-3 |title=Tulsi Gabbard may have just qualified for the next Democratic debate thanks to American Samoa|work=Business Insider |author=Jake Lahut |date=March 5, 2020 |access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> She later gained another delegate.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=missbeae |number=1235660300382334976?s=21 |title=New: The Democratic Party of American Samoa has extended a formal apology after a miscalculation of delegates following it's #SuperTuesday caucus. @TulsiGabbard now has 2 delegates from American Samoa. https://twitter.com/MissBeaE/status/1235007327755001856&nbsp;\u2026pic.twitter.com/A4T8VzAxBO |last=Peterson |first=Beatrice-Elizabeth |date=2020-03-05 |website=[[Twitter]] |language=en |access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> On March 6, the DNC confirmed that the single qualification for entry to the eleventh debate would be for a candidate to have earned at least 20 percent of awarded delegates by March 15.<ref> {{cite web |url=https://www.thehill.com/homenews/campaign/486348-new-standards-eliminate-tulsi-gabbard-from-next-democratic-debate%3famp | title=New standards eliminate Tulsi Gabbard from next Democratic debate | work=The Hill| author=J. Edward Moreno | date=March 6, 2020 | access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref> The threshold was impossible for her to meet to qualify for the eleventh debate.<ref name=\"bimar6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/dnc-made-it-impossible-tulsi-gabbard-make-the-next-debate-2020-3|title=The DNC just made it mathematically impossible for Tulsi Gabbard to make the next debate, leaving Biden & Sanders one-on-one|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020|work=[[Business Insider]]|author=Jake Lahut}}</ref>\n\n=== Andrew Yang disputes ===\n\n==== Microphone complaints in first debate ====\nYang, along with [[Marianne Williamson]] and [[Eric Swalwell]], complained of microphone problems not allowing them to speak unless called upon when other candidates seemed to be able to freely interject at all times. NBC responded by stating that none of the candidates' microphones were turned off or muted.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/national/article232067952.html |title=Andrew Yang says mic was cut during Democratic debate, but NBC denies muting him |author=Jared Gilmour |date=June 28, 2019 |work=[[Miami Herald]] |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Yang qualification for third debate ====\nAfter Yang had received what he considered to be his fourth qualifying poll, the DNC revealed that qualifying polls conducted by different organizations would not be counted separately if they were sponsored by the same DNC-approved sponsor. The ruling was controversially disclosed by the DNC on July 30, less than one day after Yang had obtained 2% in four polls, rather than on July 19 when the second of these polls had been completed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/455337-exclusive-dnc-rejects-yang-poll-leaving-him-off-september-debate-stage |title=Yang campaign slams DNC over poll qualification criteria for September debate |last1=Frazin |first1=Rachel |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=August 23, 2019 |date=June 30, 2019}}</ref> In spite of this, Yang qualified for the third debate.<ref name=\"sept12d \"/>\n\n==== Yang disputes with MSNBC ====\nIn the fifth debate, Yang did not receive his first question until 32 minutes into the debate and spoke for considerably less time than all the other participants.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/andrew-yang-low-speaking-time-dem-debates-given-polling-2019-11 |title=Presidential contender Andrew Yang has had considerably low speaking times at Democratic debates compared to his strong polling |last=Hickey |first=Walt |date=November 24, 2019 |website=Business Insider |url-status=live |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref> Yang and his supporters criticized the network for what they saw as an undemocratic process.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/471789-yang-to-msnbc-issue-an-on-air-apology-for-lack-of-speaking-time-during |title=Yang to MSNBC: Apologize 'on-air' for lack of speaking time during debate |author=Johnson, Marty |date=November 23, 2019 |access-date=November 24, 2019}},</ref> MSNBC asked Yang to join an undisclosed program the weekend of November 24, but Yang said he would not appear until the network \"apologizes on-air\" and \"discusses and includes [his] campaign consistent with [his] polling\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=AndrewYang |number=1198258580996214784 |title=MSNBC thinks we need them. We don't. |date=November 24, 2019 |access-date=November 24, 2019}}</ref> Yang ended his self-imposed boycott on December 27 by going on the TV show ''[[All in with Chris Hayes]]'', stating \"I decided that I'd prefer to speak to as many Americans as possible \u2013 our message is too important\" on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/andrew-yang-msnbc-hiatus-ends |title=Andrew Yang ends self-imposed MSNBC boycott, wants to reach 'as many Americans as possible' |last=Dorman |first=Sam |website=[[Fox News]] |access-date=December 30, 2019 |date=December 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Yang qualification for seventh debate ====\nYang requested for the DNC to conduct more early state polls in December due to a lack of early state polling by qualifying pollsters. The DNC rejected this idea saying that conducting its own polls would call into question its impartiality.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/elections/articles/2019-12-30/democratic-national-committee-denies-andrew-yangs-request-for-more-polls-before-january-debate |title=DNC Denies Andrew Yang's Request for More Polls Before January Debate |author=Alexa Lardieri |work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |date=December 30, 2019 |access-date=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Sixth debate labor disputes ===\nThe sixth debate was initially set to be held at the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"uclaoct29 \"/> However, the DNC announced on November 6 that UCLA was no longer hosting the debate due to a labor dispute.<ref name=\"politiconov6 \"/>\n\nDue to a [[Sodexo]] worker strike at the new venue, [[Loyola Marymount University]], Warren announced that she would not attend the debate unless the labor dispute was resolved, followed soon after by Sanders and Yang. All of the remaining qualifying candidates (Biden,  Buttigieg, Klobuchar, and Steyer) then followed suit over the next several days.<ref name=\"AWangWP\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Amy |title=Several Democratic candidates threaten to skip next week's presidential debate in Los Angeles |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/several-democratic-candidates-threaten-to-skip-next-weeks-presidential-debate-in-los-angeles/2019/12/13/d6c03e0a-1dd5-11ea-b4c1-fd0d91b60d9e_story.html |website=Washington Post |access-date=December 13, 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/13/warren-biden-and-sanders-threaten-to-skip-2020-democratic-debate.html |website=CNBC |date=December 13, 2019 |access-date=December 13, 2019 |title=All the 2020 Democrats in next week's debate threaten to skip event, refuse to cross picket line |author=Jacob Pramuk}}</ref> The dispute was resolved on December 17, allowing the debate to move forward.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/17/democratic-debate-labor-fight-086423 |title=Democratic debate to move forward after tentative agreement in labor fight |author1=Quint Forgey |author2=Laura Barr\u00f3n-L\u00f3pez |date=December 17, 2019 |access-date=December 17, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\n\n=== 2020 debates rule-change petition ===\nDays before the December 2019 debate, for which Booker did not qualify, he sent a petition to the other candidates' campaigns in which he urged the DNC to change the qualification requirements for the upcoming debates in 2020 so that more non-white candidates could participate. All candidates that qualified for the December debate as well as Castro signed the petition. The DNC rejected the request to change the qualification criteria.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/474592-booker-asks-other-2020-dems-to-sign-petition-urging-dnc-to-change-debate |title=Booker leads other 2020 Dems in petition urging DNC to change debate qualifications |author=Axelrod, Tal |date=December 14, 2019 |access-date=December 15, 2019 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/rubycramer/cory-booker-debate-rules-dnc-letter |title=The Top Democratic Candidates Are Urging The DNC To Change Its Debate Rules |author=Cramer, Ruby |date=December 14, 2019 |access-date=December 15, 2019 |work=[[BuzzFeed News]]}}</ref> The petition cites the New Hampshire Democratic Party central committee which voted to urge the DNC to \"lift the barriers\" on participation in further debates.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wmur.com/article/nh-primary-source-nhdp-push-to-expand-debate-diversity-gains-traction-at-state-chairs-group-meeting/30202416 |title=NH Primary Source: NHDP push to expand debate diversity gains traction at state chairs group meeting |last1=DiStaso |first1=John |date=December 12, 2019 |access-date=December 15, 2019 |work=[[WMUR]]}}</ref>\n\n=== Seventh debate moderation controversies ===\nDuring the seventh Democratic debate, January 14, hosted by CNN and the ''Des Moines Register'', the wording of a series of questions from moderator [[Abby Phillip]] directed at senators Sanders and Warren drew criticisms from various other news outlets and from Sanders supporters. Following reports alleging that Sanders said to Warren in a 2018 private conversation that he did not believe that a woman could defeat Donald Trump in the 2020 presidential election, Sanders was given the question \"Senator Warren confirmed in a statement, that in 2018 you told her that you did not believe that a woman could win the election. Why did you say that?\" Sanders stated in his reply \"as a matter of fact, I didn't say it\" and received the follow-up question from Phillip: \"I do want to be clear here, you're saying that you never told Senator Warren that a woman could not win the election?\" to which Sanders replied \"That is correct.\" Phillip's next question was directed at Warren, and was phrased: \"Senator Warren, what did you think when Senator Sanders told you a woman could not win the election?\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/elections-2020/cnn-draws-fire-for-debate-question-that-ignores-denial/ar-BBYZhNE?li=BBnb7Kx |title=CNN draws fire for debate question that ignores denial |last1=Bauder |first1=David |date=January 15, 2020 |website=MSN |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/478340-cnn-moderator-criticized-for-question-to-sanders |title=CNN moderator criticized for question to Sanders |last=Swanson |first=Ian |date=January 15, 2020 |website=TheHill |language=en |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[MSNBC]] hosts [[Mika Brzezinski]] and [[Donny Deutsch]] the next day on ''[[Morning Joe]]'' criticized the question, describing it as \"bizarre\" and \"a miss\" respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/morning-joe-hammers-cnns-abby-phillip-bizarre-questioning-of-elizabeth-warren-it-was-a-miss/ |title=Morning Joe: Abby Phillip's Question to Warren Was a Miss |last1=Hall |first1=Colby |date=January 15, 2020 |website=Mediaite |language=en |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Senior reporter at ''[[HuffPost]]'' Zach Carter stated that he believes CNN \"botched\" the debate<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/cnn-botched-democratic-debate_n_5e1e981bc5b63211760b0fad |title=CNN Completely Botched The Democratic Debate |last=Carter |first=Zach |date=January 15, 2020 |website=HuffPost |language=en |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> and [[Matt Taibi]] from ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' described the moderation as \"shameful\" and \"villainous.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/political-commentary/january-democratic-debate-2020-cnn-bernie-sanders-elizabeth-warren-938365/ |title=CNN's Debate Performance Was Villainous and Shameful |last=Taibbi |first=Matt |last2=Taibbi |first2=Matt |date=January 15, 2020 |website=Rolling Stone |language=en-US |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Jeet Heer]] from ''[[The Nation]]'' commented that CNN was \"the biggest loser of the night.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/sanders-warren-cnn-debate/ |title=CNN Has It In for Bernie |last=Heer |first=Jeet |date=January 15, 2020 |access-date=January 15, 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0027-8378}}</ref> ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' senior commentary writer Becket Adams described Phillip's question as \"a hatchet job.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/cnn-eager-to-back-elizabeth-warren-in-dispute-first-reported-by-cnn |title=CNN eager to back Elizabeth Warren in dispute first reported by ... CNN |date=January 15, 2020 |last1=Adams |first1=Becket |website=Washington Examiner |language=en |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> The controversy also led to negative reactions on social media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/cnn-elizabeth-warren-bernie-sanders.amp |title=CNN blasted for 'siding' with Warren after Sanders denied sexism charge |website=Fox News |last1=Wulfsohn |first1=Joseph A. |date=January 14, 2020 |access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Michael Bloomberg's debate inclusion ===\nIn January, [[Michael Bloomberg]] became the only candidate to simultaneously reach the polling threshold and fail to reach the donor threshold since the DNC began requiring both with the [[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates#Third debate (September 12, 2019)|third debate]]. According to ''[[Politico]]'', some left-wing activists questioned whether the donor threshold should remain part of the qualification requirements,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2020/1/28/21083472/2020-democratic-primary-polls-iowa-caucuses-winning |first=Sean |last=Collins |title=Who's winning the Democratic primary in the polls, one week ahead of the Iowa caucuses |date=January 28, 2020 |website=Vox}}</ref> asserting that a candidate polling in the high single or low double digits should not be able to escape in-person scrutiny from other candidates who participate in the debates.\n\n==== DNC debate qualification rules change ====\nOn January 31, the DNC announced that it would not impose a donor threshold starting with the ninth debate.<ref name=\"politicojan31 \"/> DNC spokesperson Adrienne Watson stated that the prior rules were \"appropriate for the opening stages of the race, when candidates were building their organizations and there were no metrics available outside of polling to distinguish those making progress from those who weren't.\"<ref name=\"tpm \"/> She said the DNC always had planned to change the debate qualification thresholds and that \"we signaled it many times\". She argued that the rule change was \"not designed to benefit any one candidate\" and declared that \"every candidate has an equal opportunity to qualify\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/7-candidates-have-qualified-for-the-new-hampshire-democratic-debate/ |title=7 Candidates Have Qualified For The New Hampshire Democratic Debate |date=February 6, 2020 |first=Geoffrey |last=Skelley |website=FiveThirtyEight}}</ref>\n\n==== Other candidates' reactions to Bloomberg's inclusion ====\nFour candidates opposed the DNC's changing the rules allegedly to make sure Bloomberg qualifies for the debates. Sanders senior adviser [[Jeffrey P. Weaver]] stated that the rules changing \"in the middle of the game\" was wrong and \"the definition of a rigged system\". He also complained that Bloomberg \"is trying to buy his way into the Democratic nomination\".<ref name=\"tpm\">{{cite web |url=https://talkingpointsmemo.com/news/dem-candidates-angry-with-dnc-over-new-debate-rules-that-favor-bloomberg |title=Dem Candidates Angry With DNC Over New Debate Rules That Favor Bloomberg |first=Matt |last=Shuham |date=February 1, 2020 |website=Talking Points Memo}}</ref> Warren tweeted, referencing Bloomberg's personal wealth, that \"[b]illionaires shouldn't be allowed to play by different rules\". She further objected that the DNC failed to change the debate qualification rules to \"ensure diverse candidates could remain on the debate stage\".<ref>{{cite tweet |user=ewarren |number=1223389175468249088 |title=The DNC didn't change the rules to ensure good, diverse candidates could remain on the debate stage. They shouldn't change the rules to let a billionaire on. Billionaires shouldn't be allowed to play by different rules\u2014on the debate stage, in our democracy, or in our government. |last=Warren |first=Elizabeth |date=2020-01-31 |language=en |access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> Biden responded to a question about the issue by pointing out that Bloomberg is not \"even on the ballot in Nevada\" (the location of the first debate where Bloomberg qualified).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2020/2/1/21118038/2020-democratic-candidates-debate-rules-sanders-warren-biden-bloomberg |title=2020 Democratic candidates aren't happy about new debate rules that seem to benefit Bloomberg |first=Katelyn |last=Burns |date=February 1, 2020 |website=Vox}}</ref> Tulsi Gabbard remarked that \"The DNC's and \"corporate media partners'\" playing favorites with candidates is \"wrong\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tulsi-gabbard-dnc-debate-bloomberg-new-hampshire-election |title=Tulsi Gabbard slams DNC kowtow to Bloomberg as 'wrong,' calls for a 'straightforward' process |last=Musto |first=Julia |date=2020-02-08 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref> and that \"[t]he DNC would rather hear from a billionaire than the only person of color left in this race, the first female combat veteran ever to run for president.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/tulsi-gabbard-mike-bloomberg-2020-democratic-race |title=Tulsi Gabbard won't quit race, says she is 'still very focused on being the Democratic nominee' |last=Halon |first=Yael |date=2020-02-18 |website=Fox News |language=en-US |access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\nOn the other hand, two of the candidates welcomed Bloomberg's inclusion.  Buttigieg told reporters, \"It is important that we have that process where folks have to stand with their competitors and explain why each of us is the best.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/2020-democrats-slam-party-rule-change-that-could-let-bloomberg-debate |title=2020 Democrats slam party rule change that could let Bloomberg debate |date=February 1, 2020 |access-date=February 1, 2020 |website=Washington Examiner |author=Emily Larsen}}</ref> Klobuchar took it a bit further, and stated that he should have to answer questions and not \"hide behind the airwaves\". She claimed that although she could not beat him \"on the airwaves\", she could beat him in a debate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/483293-klobuchar-bloomberg-shouldnt-be-able-to-hide-behind-airwaves-and-huge-ad |title=Klobuchar: Bloomberg shouldn't be able to 'hide behind airwaves and massive ad buys' |website=The Hill |last1=Klar |first1=Rebecca |date=February 16, 2020 |access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticisms about the tenth debate ===\n\n==== Alleged influence efforts by Bloomberg ====\nThere were accusations online and in the media that Bloomberg had stacked the audience in his favor, though nothing was ever proven. The high ticket prices to the event were also heavily condemned.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/02/25/democratic-debate-cbs-bloomberg-draw-jeers-for-ad-buy-stacked-audience/ |title=Democratic debate: CBS, Bloomberg draw jeers for ad buy, \u2018stacked\u2019 audience |work=[[New York Post]] |author=Ebony Bowden |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> A 60-second ad for Bloomberg's campaign played during the first and second commercial breaks, drawing ire, especially online.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/cbs-criticized-for-running-bloomberg-ads-during-democratic-debate-how/ |title=CBS Criticized for Running Bloomberg Ads During Democratic Debate: 'How?' |work=[[TheWrap]] |date=February 26, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |author=Lindsey Ellefson}}</ref>\n\n==== Moderation ====\nCBS was also widely criticized for doing a poor job of moderating the  debate and letting candidates talk over each other, often leading to 10\u201320 seconds of unintelligible shouting.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://apnews.com/ed65acf1720d2cb5281aa99d2fa7e844 |title=Rough debate performance by moderators a blow to CBS News |author=David Bauder |date=February 26, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/columns/cbs-news-throws-a-chaotic-democratic-debate-column-1203516033/ |title=CBS News Throws a Chaotic Democratic Debate |author=Daniel D'Addario |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=February 25, 2020 |access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Criticisms about the eleventh debate ===\n\n==== Announcement of change from prior format ====\nFollowing Super Tuesday, the DNC and CNN announced that the eleventh debate would occur in a seated format with \"a more intimate setting\" and a \"town hall-style production featuring audience questions,\" instead of the traditional format of the prior debates led by formal moderator questioning.<ref name=mchopolitico2020>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/07/bernie-sanders-joe-biden-arizona-debate-123467 |title=Sanders, Biden camps clash over Arizona debate format |author=Marc Caputo, Holly Otterbein |date=March 7, 2020 |access-date=March 9, 2020 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> This announcement was opposed by the Sanders campaign as \"giving Biden too much of a break\" and avoiding an \"exchange of ideas,\"<ref name=mchopolitico2020 /> as well as criticized by commentators.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kZUTHdJgJ1A |title=Saagar Enjeti: Media says Joe Biden's 'cognitive decline' is Russian conspiracy theory |author=Saagar Enjeti |date=March 9, 2020 |access-date=March 9, 2020 |work=[[Hill TV: Rising with Krystal & Saagar]]}}</ref> These concerns became moot after the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] forced the debate to be changed to the traditional moderator questioning format without any audience.<ref name=\"CNNmar12\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n{{notelist|40em}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2020 Democratic primaries}}\n{{U.S. presidential primaries}}\n{{United States presidential election, 2020}}\n\n[[Category:2020 United States presidential debates]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party presidential debates|2020]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc1}}\n{{short description|Debates for 2020 Democratic presidential nomination}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{US 2020 presidential elections series}}\n\nThe '''2020 Democratic Party presidential debates''' took place among [[2020 Democratic Party presidential candidates|candidates]] in [[2020 Democratic Party presidential primaries|the campaign]] for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]'s nomination for the [[president of the United States]] in the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 presidential election]].\n\nThere were a total of 29 major Democratic candidates. Of these, 23 candidates participated in at least one debate. Only [[Joe Biden]] and [[Bernie Sanders]] participated in all the debates.\n\n== Overview ==\n{{Location map+\n| USA\n| width       = 350\n| caption     = Sites of the first eleven Democratic presidential debates; there will be twelve total (D1\u2013D12) in 2019\u201320.\n| alt         = Map of United States showing sites of all Democratic presidential debates (D1-D12) in 2019\u20132020\n| places      =\n {{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#First debates (June 26\u201327, 2019)|D1<br />Miami]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = right\n | lat_deg    = 25.787628 <!--GPS coordinates for the Arsht Center-->\n | lon_deg    = -80.189905\n }}\n {{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Second debates (July 30\u201331, 2019)|D2<br />Detroit]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 42.3385694 <!--GPS coordinates for the Fox Theatre-->\n | lon_deg    = -83.0521972\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Third debate (September 12, 2019)|D3<br />Houston]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 29.722778 <!--GPS coordinates for the Health and Physical Education arena-->\n | lon_deg    = -95.365278\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Fourth debate (October 15, 2019)|D4<br />Westerville]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 40.129810 <!--GPS coordinates for Rike Center-->\n | lon_deg    = -82.937410\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Fifth debate (November 20, 2019)|D5<br />Atlanta]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 33.7075837 <!--GPS coordinates for Oprah Winfrey Soundstage 1 (Van Horn Rd) at Tyler Perry Studios (formerly known as the Fort McPherson military base)-->\n | lon_deg    = -84.4346789\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Sixth debate (December 19, 2019)|D6<br />LA]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = right\n | lat_deg    = 33.9675 <!--GPS coordinates for Gersten Pavillion at Loyola Marymount University-->\n | lon_deg    = -118.415556\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Seventh debate (January 14, 2020)|D7<br />Des Moines]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 41.6007 <!--GPS coordinates for Drake University-->\n | lon_deg    = -93.6513\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Eighth debate (February 7, 2020)|D8<br />Manchester]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = left\n | lat_deg    = 42.9843 <!--GPS coordinates for St. Anselm College-->\n | lon_deg    = -71.5038\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Ninth debate (February 19, 2020)|D9<br />Paradise]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = right\n | lat_deg    = 36.1146 <!--GPS coordinates for Las Vegas-->\n | lon_deg    = -115.1728\n }}\n{{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Tenth debate (February 25, 2020)|D10<br />Charleston]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = right\n | lat_deg    = 32.7833 <!--GPS coordinates for Gaillard Center-->\n | lon_deg    = -79.9453\n }}\n {{Location map~ | USA\n | label      = '''[[#Eleventh debate (March 15, 2020)|D11<br />Washington, D.C.]]'''\n | label_size = 75\n | position   = right\n | lat_deg    = 38.895 <!--GPS coordinates for Washington, D.C.-->\n | lon_deg    = -77.0366\n }}\n}}\n\n=== Schedule ===\nIn December 2018, the [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC) announced the preliminary schedule for 12 official DNC-sanctioned debates, set to begin in June 2019, with six debates in 2019 and the remaining six during the first four months of 2020. Candidates are allowed to participate in [[2020 Democratic Party presidential forums|forums]] featuring multiple other candidates as long as only one candidate appears on stage at a time; if candidates participate in any unsanctioned debate with other presidential candidates, they will lose their invitation to the next DNC-sanctioned debate.<ref name=\"DNCdebates\">{{cite news |title=DNC announces framework for the 2020 Democratic presidential primary debates (December 20, 2018) |url=https://democrats.org/press/dnc-announces-framework-for-the-2020-democratic-presidential-primary-debates/ |publisher=[[Democratic National Committee]] |access-date=December 20, 2018 |date=December 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190114114326/https://democrats.org/press/dnc-announces-framework-for-the-2020-democratic-presidential-primary-debates/ |archive-date=January 14, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"DNCdebatesPerez\">{{cite news |title=Climate Change and the 2020 Debates |url=https://medium.com/@TomPerezforDNC/on-debates-3f6956696e7e |last=Perez |first=Tom |website=Medium |access-date=June 12, 2018 |date=June 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190612072844/https://medium.com/@TomPerezforDNC/on-debates-3f6956696e7e |archive-date=June 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe DNC also announced that it would not partner with [[Fox News]] as a media sponsor for any debates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/democratic-national-committee-rejects-fox-news-for-debates-citing-new-yorker-article/2019/03/06/a0bdf55c-402e-11e9-922c-64d6b7840b82_story.html |title=Democratic National Committee rejects Fox News for debates, citing New Yorker article |last1=Fahri |first1=Paul |date=March 6, 2019 |newspaper=The Washington Post |access-date=March 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306201725/https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/democratic-national-committee-rejects-fox-news-for-debates-citing-new-yorker-article/2019/03/06/a0bdf55c-402e-11e9-922c-64d6b7840b82_story.html |archive-date=March 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/5/11/18537107/dnc-tom-perez-democratic-presidential-debates |title=How DNC Chair Tom Perez plans to avoid the chaos of the GOP's 2016 debates |last=Nielsen |first=Ella |date=May 11, 2019 |publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=May 17, 2019}}</ref> Fox News had last held a Democratic debate in 2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/fox-news-key-2020-election-whether-liberals-it-or-not-ncna980701 |title=Fox News is key to the 2020 election, whether liberals like it or not. Denying it a debate only hurts Democrats. |last1=Laslo |first1=Matt |publisher=NBC News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190307212729/https://www.nbcnews.com/think/opinion/fox-news-key-2020-election-whether-liberals-it-or-not-ncna980701 |archive-date=March 7, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=March 8, 2019}}</ref> All media sponsors selected to host a debate will as a new rule be required to appoint at least one female moderator for each debate, to ensure there will not be a gender-skewed treatment of the candidates and debate topics.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2019/05/234148/democratic-presidential-debate-info-2020-dnc-female-moderator |title=Exclusive: DNC Requires Female Moderators At Every 2020 Debate |last=Gontcharova |first=Natalie |date=May 31, 2019 |publisher=[[Refinery29]] |access-date=June 7, 2019}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Debate schedule\n! Debate\n! Date\n! Time<br />{{small|([[Eastern Time Zone|ET]])}}\n! Viewers\n! Location\n! Sponsor(s)\n! Moderator(s)\n|-\n![[2020 Democratic Party presidential debates#First debates (June 26\u201327, 2019)|1A]]\n| June 26, 2019\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |9\u201311 p.m.\n| ~24.3 million <br /> (15.3m live TV; 9m streaming)<ref>{{cite news |url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/democratic-debate-ratings-strong-elizabeth-warren-julian-castro-donald-trump-nbc-msnbc-telemundo-1202638778/ |title=Democratic Debate Night 1 Gets 15.3M Viewers Across NBC, MSNBC & Telemundo; 9M Watch Via Streaming \u2013 Update |last=Patten |first=Dominic |date=June 27, 2019 |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |access-date=June 27, 2019}}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Adrienne Arsht Center for the Performing Arts|Arsht Center]],<br />[[Miami]], Florida<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/first-democratic-presidential-deb