n June 10)}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.3|1.3}}%, 10 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{yes}}\n| <ref name=\"auto7\" />\n|-\n| [[Jay Inslee|Inslee]]\n| {{yes}}{{Hs|2019-05-24}}<br />{{small|(on May 24)}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 9 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{yes}}\n| <ref name=\"auto10\" />\n|-\n| [[Marianne Williamson|Williamson]]\n| {{yes}}{{Hs|2019-05-09}}<br />{{small|(on May 9)}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 8 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{yes}}\n| <ref name=\"auto9\" /><ref name=\"auto2\" />\n|-\n| [[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.3|1.3}}%, 9 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"Hick13\">{{cite news |last1=Thompson |first1=Alex |last2=McCaskill |first2=Nolan D. |title=Hickenlooper campaign in shambles |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/02/hickenlooper-2020-campaign-1395051 |publisher=Politico |date=July 2, 2019 |access-date=July 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Ryan]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.3|1.3}}%, 9 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.3|1.3}}%, 8 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 7 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"HillBennet\" />\n|-\n|[[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Bullock]]\n| {{No}}\n|{{Yes|Yes|align=|style=|color=}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 4 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|<ref name=\"DebatesQual538Bullock\" /><ref name=\"NewQualStatus\" /><ref name=\"BullockJuly\">{{cite web |url=https://politi.co/2WQZaMd |title=Bullock qualifies for July debate |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |website=[[Politico]] |access-date=June 18, 2019 |date=June 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Bill de Blasio|de Blasio]]\n| {{No}}\n|{{Yes|Yes|align=|style=|color=}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 4 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|<ref name=\"auto3\" /><ref name=\"auto15\" /><ref name=\"NewQualStatus\" />\n|-\n| [[Mike Gravel|Gravel]]\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|(on July 12)}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(1 qualifying poll)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"GravelDonorCount\">{{cite web |url=http://www.graveldonorcount.com/ |title=Mike Gravel 2020 Donor Count |access-date=July 12, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Wayne Messam|Messam]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(2 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Seth Moulton|Moulton]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n| <ref name=\"auto6\" />\n|-\n| [[Joe Sestak|Sestak]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|-\n| [[Tom Steyer|Steyer]]\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}<br />{{small|(0 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{No}}\n|\n|- style=\"background:#f0e68c;\"\n| [[Eric Swalwell|Swalwell]]\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}<br />{{small|({{sort|01.0|1.0}}%, 3 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\" class=\"table-no\" style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{legend|#f0e68c|Withdrawn candidate}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==== Summary ====\n{{Infobox debate\n|name          = Democratic Party debates\n|image         = \n|order         = Second Democratic debates\n|host          = [[CNN]]\n|dates         = July 30, 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=CNN Hosts Democratic Debate. July 30, 2019 \u2013 8:00-10:37pm ET |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1907/30/se.01.html |website=transcripts.cnn.com |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref> <br /> July 31, 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=Second Night of Democratic Debates. July 31, 2019 \u2013 8:00-10:45pm ET |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1907/31/se.02.html |website=transcripts.cnn.com |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n|venue         = [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]]\n|location      = [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]]\n|leadmoderator = [[Jake Tapper]]\n|othermoderators = [[Dana Bash]]<br />[[Don Lemon]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Democratic Party's second presidential debates''' ahead of the [[2020 United States presidential election|2020 U.S. presidential election]] were held on July 30 and 31, 2019, in [[Detroit]], [[Michigan]].\n\nStarting at 8:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern Standard Time, they aired on [[CNN]] and were broadcast on radio by [[Westwood One (current)|Westwood One]]. [[Jake Tapper]] was the lead moderator of the debates, joined by [[Dana Bash]] and [[Don Lemon]].\n\nThe drawing of lots among the 20 invited candidates to determine when they will debate was televised in [[prime time]] on July 18.<ref name=\"houston-debate\">{{cite news |author=Michael N. Grynbaum |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/09/business/media/democratic-debate-abc-houston.html |title=Houston to Host Third Democratic Debate on ABC |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 9, 2019 |access-date=July 9, 2019}}</ref> There were three tiers of candidates that were split between two nights, as opposed to the two tiers used in the first debates.<ref>{{cite news |title=DNC tinkers with format for next debates |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/17/2020-democrats-debates-candidates-tiers-1418902 |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=July 17, 2019 |date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn total, 21 candidates qualified for the second debate. The 14 candidates who met both criteria (Biden, Sanders, Warren, Harris, Buttigieg, O'Rourke, Booker, Klobuchar, Castro, Yang, Gabbard, Gillibrand, Inslee, and Williamson) and the six candidates who met the polling criterion only (Ryan, Hickenlooper, Delaney, de Blasio, Bennet, and Bullock) were invited to participate in the debate. Gravel, the one candidate to qualify by the donor criterion only, was not invited because of the 20-candidate limit and the polling criterion's precedence over the donor criterion as mandated by the DNC. The set of participants for the second debate was identical to the first debates with one exception: Bullock replaced Swalwell, who suspended his campaign between the first and second debates.<ref name=\"npr \"/>\n\nThe debate on July 30 featured Bullock, Buttigieg, Delaney, Hickenlooper, Klobuchar, O'Rourke, Ryan, Sanders, Warren and Williamson, while the debate on July 31 featured Bennet, Biden, Booker, Castro, de Blasio, Gabbard, Gillibrand, Harris, Inslee and Yang.<ref name=\"cnndraw\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/07/here-are-the-lineups-for-the-second-democratic-debates.html |title=Here Are the Lineup for the Second Democratic Debates in CNN |date=July 18, 2019 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |author=Matt Steib, Ed Kilgore}}</ref> Both debates took place at the [[Fox Theatre (Detroit)|Fox Theatre]] in Detroit, Michigan.\n\nThe overarching theme on the first night was a clash between moderates and progressives on a variety of issues, ranging from [[Medicare for All]] to electability.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/07/30/best-debate-moments-highlights-1441225 |title=Moderates go after progressives in Democratic debate |author=Nolan D. McCaskill |date=July 30, 2019 |access-date=July 30, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref>\nCNN received criticism for allegedly inciting conflicts between candidates and making questions from Republican talking points, as well as enforcing the time limits too strictly.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2019/7/30/20747889/2020-democratic-debates-presidential-election-winners-losers-night-one |author1=German Lopez |author2=P.R Lockhart |author3=Dylan Matthews |author4=Zack Beauchamp |author5=Ella Nilsen |date=July 30, 2019 |access-date=July 31, 2019 |work=[[Vox (website)]] |title=3 winners and 4 losers from the first night of the July Democratic debates}}</ref> The second night saw significant discussion centered on candidates' differing health care plans. Additionally, Gabbard went on the offensive against Harris.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/08/01/democratic-debate-results-takeaways-1443117 |title=5 revelations from the Biden pile-on in Detroit |author=David Siders |author2=Steven Shepard |date=August 1, 2019 |access-date=August 9, 2019 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2020/president/us/2020_democratic_presidential_nomination-6730.html |title=RealClearPolitics \u2013 Election 2020 \u2013 2020 Democratic Presidential Nomination |website=[[RealClearPolitics]]}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Night one candidates'''\n|-\n! Candidates<br /> drawn for the<br /> July 30 debate\n!Drawing tier{{Efn|The drawing of lots happened from three tier groups (with the top tier comprising all qualified candidates with a polling average of over 15%), so that each tier was evenly split between each of the two debate nights.|name=second-debate}}!! Polling<br /> criterion<br /> result<ref name=\"PollingData1and2\" />\n!Airtime (min.)<ref name=\"auto16\" />\n|-\n|[[Bernie Sanders|Sanders]]\n|1|| 27% (19 polls)\n|17.6\n|-\n|[[Elizabeth Warren|Warren]]\n|1|| 19% (19 polls)\n|17.9\n|-\n|[[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n|2|| 13.3% (19 polls)\n|14.4\n|-\n|[[Beto O'Rourke|O'Rourke]]\n|2|| 10.3% (18 polls)\n|10.9\n|-\n|[[Amy Klobuchar|Klobuchar]]\n|2||4% (16 polls)\n|10.7\n|-\n|[[John Hickenlooper|Hickenlooper]]\n|3||1.3% (9 polls)\n|8.8\n|-\n|[[Tim Ryan (Ohio politician)|Ryan]]\n|3||1.3% (9 polls)\n|9.8\n|-\n|[[John Delaney (Maryland politician)|Delaney]]\n|3||1.3% (8 polls)\n|10.3\n|-\n|[[Marianne Williamson|Williamson]]\n|3||1% (8 polls)\n|8.9\n|-\n|[[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Bullock]]\n|3||1% (4 polls)\n|10.8\n|-\n|'''Average'''\n|\n|'''8%'''\n|'''12.0'''\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display:inline-table;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | '''Night two candidates'''\n|-\n! Candidates<br /> drawn for the<br /> July 31 debate\n!Drawing tier{{Efn|name=second-debate}}!! Polling<br /> criterion<br /> result<ref name=\"PollingData1and2\" />\n!Airtime (min.)<ref name=\"auto16\" />\n|-\n|[[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n|1|| 40.7% (19 polls)\n|21.2\n|-\n|[[Kamala Harris|Harris]]\n|1|| 17.7% (19 polls)\n|17.7\n|-\n|[[Cory Booker|Booker]]\n|2|| 4.3% (19 polls)\n|12.8\n|-\n|[[Julian Castro|Castro]]\n|2|| 2.7% (12 polls)\n|10.5\n|-\n|[[Andrew Yang|Yang]]\n|2||2% (18 polls)\n|8.7\n|-\n|[[Tulsi Gabbard|Gabbard]]\n|3||1.3% (12 polls)\n|10.6\n|-\n|[[Kirsten Gillibrand|Gillibrand]]\n|3||1.3% (10 polls)\n|11.6\n|-\n|[[Jay Inslee|Inslee]]\n|3||1% (9 polls)\n|10.7\n|-\n|[[Michael Bennet|Bennet]]\n|3||1% (7 polls)\n|10.6\n|-\n|[[Bill de Blasio|de Blasio]]\n|3||1% (4 polls)\n|9.7\n|-\n|'''Average'''\n|\n|'''7.3%'''\n|'''12.4'''\n|}\n\n==== Participation ====\nEach of the first two debates took place during two consecutive nights, with a maximum of 10 candidates per night. The DNC, at a public event before each debate, drew lots among the qualified candidates to determine whether they shall debate on the first or second night.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/nbc-news-first-democratic-debate-set-miami-june-26-27-n988481 |title=NBC News: First Democratic debate set for Miami, June 26\u201327 |last=Smith |first=Allan |date=March 28, 2019 |publisher=NBC News |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328212147/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/2020-election/nbc-news-first-democratic-debate-set-miami-june-26-27-n988481 |archive-date=March 28, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=March 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"cnnd\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/02/politics/cnn-2020-democratic-debate-july-detroit/index.html |title=CNN's 2020 Democratic debate set for July 30-31 in Detroit |last=Cole |first=Devan |date=April 2, 2019 |access-date=April 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190403013637/https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/02/politics/cnn-2020-democratic-debate-july-detroit/index.html |archive-date=April 3, 2019 |url-status=live |publisher=CNN}}</ref> This drawing procedure was designed to avoid the appearance of a \"kiddie table\" debate where the lowest polling candidates were grouped together with no leading candidates, which happened during the [[2016 Republican Party presidential debates and forums|2016 Republican Party presidential debates]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/05/24/democrats-undercard-june-1344368 |title=Dems institute rule to prevent 'undercard' debate in June |last1=Montellaro |first1=Zach |date=May 24, 2019 |work=[[Politico]] |access-date=May 24, 2019 |last2=Shepard |first2=Steven}}</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n=== Third debate (September 12, 2019) ===\n\n==== Qualification ====\nThe third debate took place at the [[Health and Physical Education Arena]] on the campus of [[Texas Southern University]] in [[Houston]], [[Texas]]. For participation in the third debate, candidates were required to meet both polling and fundraising criteria by August 28 (in comparison to the first and second debates, where only one criterion was necessary). Qualifying polls had to be released between June 28 and August 28.<ref name=\"QualCriteriaDebate3\">{{cite news |url=https://democrats.org/press/third-debate/ |title=DNC announces details for third presidential primary debate (May 29, 2019) |date=May 29, 2019 |access-date=June 8, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608122340/https://democrats.org/press/third-debate/ |archive-date=June 8, 2019 |publisher=Democratic National Committee |url-status=live}}</ref> Five candidates (Gravel, Hickenlooper, Inslee, Moulton, and Gillibrand) suspended their campaigns between the second and third debates.\n\nOn August 23, the Gabbard campaign [[#Poll inclusion controversy regarding third debate|criticized]] the DNC's purported lack of transparency in the process of selecting organizations/institutions to sponsor polls and how better-ranked polls were excluded. The campaign also highlighted the stark reduction in poll frequency, especially in early primary states,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2019/08/29/gabbard_confirms_she_will_not_run_as_third-party_candidate.html |title=Gabbard Confirms She Will Not Run As Third-Party Candidate |date=August 29, 2019 |access-date=September 17, 2019 |first=Tim |last=Hains |website=Real Clear Politics}}</ref> after the second debate compared to after the first debate and how they believed that that was \"particularly harmful\" to candidates with lower name recognition.<ref name=\"auto32\">{{cite web |url=http://abcnewsradioonline.com/politics-news/tulsi-gabbards-campaign-wants-the-dnc-to-change-debate-quali.html |title=Tulsi Gabbard's campaign wants the DNC to change debate qualifying poll requirements |website=ABC News Radio |language=en |last1=Ali |first1=Anthony |date=August 23, 2019 |access-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref> The campaigns of Marianne Williamson,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://eu.thestarpress.com/story/news/politics/elections/2019/08/03/qualified-third-debate-candidates/1909474001/ |title=As debate lineup solidifies, some 2020 Democrats cry foul over polling requirements |date=August 28, 2019 |access-date=September 17, 2019 |first=Todd |last=Spangler |first2=Annah |last2=Aschbrenner |website=USA Today Star Press}}</ref> Tom Steyer,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/458603-steyer-calls-on-dnc-to-expand-polling-criteria-for-debates |title=Steyer calls on DNC to expand polling criteria for debates |first=Tal |last=Axelrod |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |language=en |date=August 23, 2019 |access-date=September 17, 2019}}</ref> and Michael Bennet<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/08/29/755148906/debate-stage-cut-in-half-for-1-night-september-showdown |title=Debate Stage Cut In Half For 1-Night September Showdown |first=Jessica |last=Taylor |website=NPR |language=en |date=August 29, 2019 |access-date=September 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://michaelbennet.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/08/Bennet_for_America_Letter_08_28_19.pdf |title=Bennet for America |first=Michael |last=Bennet |website=Michael Bennet |language=en |date=August 28, 2019 |access-date=September 17, 2019}}</ref> also requested that the DNC increase the number of certified polls by expanding the list of certified poll sponsoring organizations.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\";\"\n! colspan=\"2\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\" |Qualification requirements for the third debate\n|-\n|'''Polling criterion'''\n|A candidate needed to get at '''least two percent support''' in '''four different polls''' published from a list of approved pollsters between June 28 and August 28, which cannot be based on open-ended questions and may cover either the national level or one of the first four primary/caucus states (Iowa, New Hampshire, Nevada, and South Carolina). Only one poll from each approved pollster counted towards meeting the criterion in each region. The approved pollsters were the [[Associated Press]], [[ABC News]], [[CBS News]], [[CNN]], ''[[The Des Moines Register]]'', [[Fox News]], [[Monmouth University Polling Institute|Monmouth University]], [[National Public Radio]], [[NBC News]], ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute|Quinnipiac University]], the [[University of New Hampshire]], ''[[USA Today]]'', ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', and [[Winthrop University]]. In contrast to the first two debates, polls published/sponsored by the ''Las Vegas Review-Journal'' and Reuters no longer counted towards meeting the criterion.\n|-\n|'''Fundraising criterion'''\n|Before the deadline, 11:59&nbsp;p.m. on August 28, a candidate needed to receive financial support from a minimum of 130,000 unique donors, with at least 400 unique donors per state in at least 20 states.\n|}\n\n<!--Table has presorted the candidates by this order:\n(1) All criteria met.\n(2) Polling criterion met.\n(3) Donor criterion met.\n(4) No criteria met.\nand they are further presorted within these 4 categories by polling average & polls-->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:95%;line-height:16px;\"\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"color:black; vertical-align:top; text-align:center; background-color:#B0E2FF;\" class=\"table-no\"|'''Qualified candidates for the third debate'''\n|-\n! Candidate\n! Met donor criterion<br />\n! Met polling criterion<br />{{small|(as of August 28)<ref name=\"PollingData3and4\">{{cite web |url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1dHSFg0jrAeIAqDlFZqAu-5N2x-wk8PT-6H4DbCendUM/edit#gid=1555665298 |title=2020 Democratic polls, third and fourth debate (updated July 28) |last=Montellaro |first=Zach |type=Google Sheets |work=[[Politico]] |date=July 28, 2019 |access-date=July 31, 2019}}</ref>}}\n! Met both criteria<br />\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Additional<br />Ref(s)\n|-\n| [[Joe Biden|Biden]]\n| {{Yes}}{{Hs|2019-06-18}}<br />{{small|(before June 18)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes|Yes|align=|style=|color=}}\n| <ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/18/politics/joe-biden-fundraising/index.html |title=Joe Biden announces massive $20 million raised as first debate approaches |last=Saenz |first=Arlette |publisher=CNN |access-date=June 18, 2019 |date=June 18, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"HillJuly30\">{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/455337-exclusive-dnc-rejects-yang-poll-leaving-him-off-september-debate-stage |title=DNC rejects Yang poll, leaving him off September debate stage |last=Frazin |first=Rachel |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=July 30, 2019 |date=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Pete Buttigieg|Buttigieg]]\n| {{Yes}}{{Hs|2019-06-14}}<br />{{small|(before June 14)}}\n| {{Yes}}<br />{{small|(15 qualifying polls)}}\n| {{Yes|Yes|align=|style=|color=}}\n| <ref name=\"auto\" 