{"title_page": "Fatehpur Sikri", "text_new": "{{Short description|Town in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{More footnotes|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Fatehpur Sikri\n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| image_skyline                   = File:Fatehput Sikiri Buland Darwaza gate 2010.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = [[Buland Darwaza]], the {{Convert|54|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} entrance to Fatehpur Sikri complex\n| nickname                        = \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.091|N|77.661|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Agra district|Agra]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = [[Akbar]]\n| discovered by                   = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_footnotes            =<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_total                = 32905\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = Auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1      = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|access-date=26 December 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archive-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2    = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2     = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = UP-80\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child = yes\n  |ID = 255\n  |Year = 1986\n  |Criteria = Cultural: ii, iii, iv\n  }}\n}}\n[[File:Kos Minar 793.jpg|thumb|[[Kos Minar]]#793 at 12-mile on [[Agra]]-Fatehpur Sikri Road section of [[National Highway 21 (India)|National Highway 21]]]]\n'''Fatehpur Sikri''' is a town in the [[Agra District]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]. The city itself was founded as the capital of [[Mughal Empire]] in 1571 by [[Mughal Emperor|Emperor]] [[Akbar]], serving this role from 1571 to 1585, when Akbar abandoned it due to a campaign in [[Punjab (region)|Punjab]] and was later completely abandoned in 1610.<ref name=\"Routlegde\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9A-EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82#v=onepage&f=false|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|author=Andrew Petersen|publisher=Routlegde|page=82|isbn=9781134613656|date=11 March 2002}}</ref>\n\nThe name of the city is derived from the village called ''Sikri'' which occupied the spot before. An [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) excavation from 1999-2000 indicated that there was a habitation, temples and commercial centres here before Akbar built his capital. The region was settled by [[Sunga]]s following their expansion. In 12th century, it was briefly controlled by [[Sakarwar|Sikarwar]] Rajputs.\n\nThe ''[[khanqah]]'' of [[Sheikh (Sufism)|Sheikh]] [[Salim Chisti|Salim]] existed earlier at this place. Akbar's son [[Jahangir]] was born at the village of Sikri in 1569 and that year Akbar began construction of a religious compound to commemorate the Sheikh who had predicted the birth. After Jahangir's second birthday, he began the construction of a walled city and imperial palace here. The city came to be known as ''Fatehpur Sikri'', the \"City of Victory\", after Akbar's [[Akbar's conquest of Gujarat|victorious Gujarat campaign in 1573]].\n\nAfter occupying [[Agra]] in 1803, the English established an administrative center here and it remained so until 1850. In 1815, the [[Francis Rawdon-Hastings, 1st Marquess of Hastings|Marquess of Hastings]] ordered repair of monuments at Sikri.\n\n==History==\nArchaeological evidence points to settlement of the region since the [[Painted Grey Ware culture|Painted Grey Ware period]]. According to historian Syed Ali Nadeem Rezavi, region flourished under [[Sunga]] rule and then under [[Sakarwar|Sikarwar]] Rajputs, who built a fortress when they controlled the area briefly in the 12th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rezavi |first1=Syed Ali Nadeem |title=Sikri before Akbar |date=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-908256-8 |url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780198084037.001.0001/acprof-9780198084037-chapter-2 |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Safvi |first1=Rana |title=The secrets about Fatehpur Sikri |url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/columns/the-secrets-about-fatehpur-sikri/article21381895.ece |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=10 December 2017 |language=en-IN}}</ref> \n\nBasing his arguments on the excavations by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) in 1999\u20132000 at the Chabeli Tila, senior [[Agra]] journalist Bhanu Pratap Singh said the antique pieces, statues, and structures all point to a lost \"culture and religious site,\" more than 1,000 years ago. \"The excavations yielded a rich crop of [[Jainism|Jain]] statues, hundreds of them, including the foundation stone of a temple with the date. The statues were a thousand years old of ''Bhagwan'' Adi Nath, ''Bhagwan'' [[Rishabhanatha|Rishabh Nath]], ''Bhagwan'' [[Mahavira|Mahavir]] and [[Yakshini#Yakshis in Jainism|Jain Yakshinis]],\" said Swarup Chandra Jain, senior leader of the [[Jain community]]. Historian Sugam Anand states that there is proof of habitation, temples and commercial centres before Akbar established it as his capital. He states that the open space on a ridge was used by Akbar to build his capital.<ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri, that Mughal emperor Akbar established as his capital and is now a World Heritage site, was once a \"flourishing trade and Jain pilgrimage centre\", a new book says. |url=http://indiatimes.com/lifestyle/travel/fatehpur-sikri-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre-89615.html |work=[[India Times]] |date=17 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri was once a Jain pilgrimage centre: Book |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/uttar-pradesh/fatehpur-sikri-was-once-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre-book_831821.html |work=[[Zee News]] |date=27 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri was once a Jain pilgrimage centre |url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/fatehpur-sikri-was-once-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre/154050 |work=[[The Free Press Journal]] |date=28 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBut preceding Akbar's appropriation of the site for his capital city, his predecessors [[Babur]] and [[Humayun]] did much to redesign Fatehpur Sikri's urban layout.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Petruccioli|first=Attilio|date=1984|title=The Process Evolved by Control Systems of Urban Design in the Mogul Epoch in India: The Case of Fatehpur Sikri|url=https://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/3483/original/DPC1425.pdf?1384775285|journal=Environmental Design|volume=|pages=18\u201327|via=ARCHNET}}</ref> Attilio Petruccioli, a scholar of Islamic architecture and Professor of Landscape Architecture at the Polytechnic University of Bari, Italy, notes that \"Babur and his successors\" wanted \"to get away from the noise and confusion of Agra [and] build an uninterrupted sequence of gardens on the free left bank of the Yamuna, linked both by boat and by land.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Petruccioli adds that when such escapist landscapes are envisioned, the monument becomes the organizing element of the city at large, partly due to its orientation at a significant location and partly due to its sheer size. Humayun's Tomb was one such organizing element, which at a height of 150 feet towered over the city and is now one of the most recognizable Mughal monuments in the country.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe place was much loved by [[Babur]], who called it ''Shukri'' (\"Thanks\"), after its large lake that was used by Mughal armies.<ref name=Asher>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA22|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|page=22|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref> [[Annette Beveridge]] in her translation of ''[[Baburnama]]'' noted that Babur [[diacritic|points]] \"Sikri\" to read \"Shukri\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Babur-nama: (Memoirs of Babur)|author=Annette Susannah Beveridge|publisher= Sang-e-Meel Publications, University of Michigan Press|year=2002|page=851|isbn=9789693512939}}</ref> Per his memoirs, Babur constructed a garden here called the \"Garden of Victory\" after defeating [[Rana Sangha]] at its outskirts. [[Gulbadan Begum]]'s ''Humayun-Nama'' describes that in the garden he built an octagonal pavilion which he used for relaxation and writing. In the center of the nearby lake, he built a large platform. A [[baoli]] exists at the base of a rock scarp about a kilometer from the [[Hiran Minar]]. This was probably the original site of a well-known [[Epigraphy|epigraph]] commemorating his victory.<ref name=Asher/>\n\n[[Abul Fazl]] records Akbar's reasons for the foundation of the city in ''[[Akbarnama]]'': \"Inasmuch as his exalted sons [Salim and [[Murad Mirza|Murad]]] had been born at Sikri, and the God-knowing spirit of Shaikh Salim had taken possession thereof, his holy heart desired to give outward splendour to this spot which possessed spiritual grandeur. Now that his standards had arrived at this place, his former design was pressed forward, and an order was issued that the superintendents of affairs should erect lofty buildings for the special use of the Shahinshah.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge History of India, Volume 4|author=[[Edward James Rapson]], [[Sir Wolseley Haig]], [[Sir Richard Burn]], [[H. H. Dodwell|Henry Dodwell]], [[Mortimer Wheeler]]|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1963|page=103}}</ref>\n\nAkbar remained heirless until 1569 when his son, who became known as [[Jahangir]], was born in the village of Sikri in 1569. Akbar began the construction of a religious compound in honor of the [[Chishti Order|Chisti saint]] [[Sheikh (Sufism)|Sheikh]] [[Salim Chishti|Salim]], who had predicted the birth of Jahangir. After Jahangir's second birthday, he began the construction of a walled city and imperial palace probably to test his son's stamina. By constructing his capital at the ''[[khanqah]]'' of Sheikh Salim, Akbar associated himself with this popular Sufi order and brought legitimacy to his reign through this affiliation.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA51|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|pages=51\u201353|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref>\n\nThe city was founded in 1571 and was named after the village of Sikri which occupied the spot before. The [[Buland Darwaza]] was built in honor of his [[Akbar's conquest of Gujarat|successful campaign]] in [[Gujarat Sultanate|Gujarat]], when the city came to be known as ''Fatehpur Sikri'' - \"The City of Victory\". It was named after the Sikri village which had existed on the spot before. It was abandoned by Akbar in 1585 when he went to fight a campaign in Punjab. It was later completely abandoned by 1610. The reason for its abandonment is usually given as the failure of the water supply, though Akbar's loss of interest may also have been the reason since it was built solely on his whim.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9A-EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82#v=onepage&f=false|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|author=Andrew Petersen|publisher=Routlegde|pages=82\u201384|isbn=9781134613656|date=11 March 2002}}</ref> [[Ralph Fitch]] described it as such, \"Agra and Fatehpore Sikri are two very great cities, either of them much greater than London, and very populous. Between Agra and Fatehpore are 12 miles (Kos) and all the way is a market of victuals and other things, as full as though a man were still in a town, and so many people as if a man were in a market.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Akbar the Great, Vol. III: Society and culture in 16th century India|author=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava|publisher=Shiva Lal Agarwala|year=1973|page=10|author-link=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava}}</ref>\n\nAkbar visited the city only once in 1601 after abandoning it. [[William Finch (merchant)|William Finch]], visiting it 4\u20135 years after his death, stated, \"It is all ruinate,\" writing, \"lying like a waste desert.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04ellRQx4nMC&pg=PA179|title=Emperors of the Peacock Throne: The Saga of the Great Mughals|author=Abraham Eraly|publisher=Penguin Books India|year=200|page=179|isbn=9780141001432|author-link=Abraham Eraly}}</ref> During the epidemic of [[bubonic plague]] from 1616 to 1624, [[Jahangir]] stayed for three months here in 1619.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04ellRQx4nMC&pg=PA284|title=Emperors of the Peacock Throne: The Saga of the Great Mughals|author=Abraham Eraly|publisher=Penguin Books India|year=2000|page=284|isbn=9780141001432|author-link=Abraham Eraly}}</ref> [[Muhammad Shah]] stayed here for some time and the repair works were started again. However, with the decline of Mughal Empire, the conditions of the buildings worsened.<ref name=Survey/>\n\nWhile chasing [[Daulat Rao Sindhia]]'s battalions in October 1803, [[Gerard Lake]] left the most cumbersome baggage and siege guns in the town.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qweZWra_tbwC&pg=PA200|title=The Anglo-Maratha Campaigns and the Contest for India: The Struggle for Control of the South Asian Military Economy|author=Randolf G. S. Cooper|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|page=200|isbn=9780521824446}}</ref> After occupying Agra in 1803, the English established an administrative center here and it remained so until 1850.<ref name=Survey>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4TslDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA262|title=Towns and Cities of Medieval India: A Brief Survey|author=Aniruddha Roy|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2016|page=262|isbn=9781351997317}}</ref> In 1815, the [[Francis Rawdon-Hastings, 1st Marquess of Hastings|Marquess of Hastings]] ordered repairment of monuments at Sikri and Sikandra.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Singh|first1=Upinder|author-link=Upinder Singh|title=The discovery of ancient India: early archaeologists and the beginnings of archaeology|date=2004|publisher=Permanent Black|isbn=9788178240886|page=185}}</ref> The town was a [[municipality]] from 1865 to 1904 and was later made a [[notified area]]. The population in 1901 was 7,147.<ref>{{cite book|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India: Provincial Series, Volume 24, Issue 1|date=1908|publisher=Superintendent of Government Print|page=415}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:General Plan of Fatehpur Sikri City India 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|General plan of Fatehpur Sikri city in 1917.]]\nFatehpur Sikri sits on rocky ridge, {{convert|3|km}} in length and {{convert|1|km|abbr=on}} wide and palace city is surrounded by a {{convert|6|km|abbr=on}} wall on three sides with the fourth bordered by a lake. The city is generally organized around this 40 m high ridge, and falls roughly into the shape of a rhombus. The general layout of the ground structures, especially the \"continuous and compact pattern of gardens and services and facilities\" that characterized the city leads urban archaeologists to conclude that Fatehpur Sikri was built primarily to afford leisure and luxury to its famous residents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe dynastic architecture of Fatehpur Sikri was modelled on [[Timurid architecture|Timurid forms and styles]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Islam: Art and Architecture|author=Markus Hattstein, Peter Delius|publisher=K\u00f6nemann|year=2000|pages=466}}</ref> The city was built massively and preferably with red sandstone.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P2R3a3KLl2IC&pg=PA1|title=Mughal Architecture|author=Moritz Herrmann|publisher=GRIN Verlag|year=2011|page=3|isbn=9783640930036}}</ref> Gujarati influences are also seen in its architectural vocabulary and decor of the palaces of Fatehpur Sikri.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mughal Architecture: An Outline of Its History and Development (1526-1858)|author=Ebba Koch|publisher=Prestel|year=1991|page=60|author-link=Ebba Koch}}</ref> The city's architecture reflects both the Hindu and Muslim form of domestic architecture popular in India at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA50|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|page=50|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref> The remarkable preservation of these original spaces allows modern archaeologists to reconstruct scenes of Mughal court life, and to better understand the hierarchy of the city's royal and noble residents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIt is accessed through gates along the {{convert|5|mi}} long fort wall, namely, Delhi Gate, the Lal Gate, the Agra Gate and Birbal's Gate, Chandanpal Gate, The Gwalior Gate, the Tehra Gate, the Chor Gate, and the Ajmeri Gate. The palace contains summer palace and winter palace for Queen Jodha.\n\n[[File:Jama Masjid-Sikri-Fatehpur Sikri-India0008.JPG|thumb|250px|[[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri]]]]\n[[File:Fatehpur Sikiri Salim Chishti Tomb 2010.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Tomb of Salim Chishti]] in [[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri|Jama Masjid]] courtyard, Fatehpur Sikri]]\n[[File:Panch Mahal-Fatehpur-Fatehpur Sikri India0014.JPG|thumb|250px|[[Panch Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri]]]]\n[[File:Hiran Minar FatehpurSikri.jpg|thumb|Hiran Minar, Fatehpur Sikri]]\n\nSome of the important buildings in this city, both religious and secular are:\n\n* [[Buland Darwaza]]: Set into the south wall of congregational mosque, the Buland Darwaza at Fatehpur Sikri is {{convert|55|m}} high, from the ground, gradually making a transition to a human scale in the inside. The gate was added around five years after the completion of the mosque c. 1576-1577 as a victory arch, to commemorate [[Akbar]]'s successful Gujarat campaign. It carries two inscriptions in the archway, one of which reads: \"Isa, Son of Mariam said: The world is a bridge, pass over it, but build no houses on it. He who hopes for an hour may hope for eternity. The world endures but an hour. Spend it in prayer, for the rest is unseen\". <br/> The central portico comprises three arched entrances, with the largest one, in the centre, is known locally as the Horseshoe Gate, after the custom of nailing horseshoes to its large wooden doors for luck. Outside the giant steps of the Buland Darwaza to the left is a deep well.\n* [[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri|Jama Masjid]]: It is a ''[[Jama Mosque]]'' meaning the congregational mosque and was perhaps one of the first buildings to be constructed in the complex, as its epigraph gives [[Hijri year|AH]] 979 (A.D. 1571-72) as the date of its completion, with a massive entrance to the courtyard, the Buland-Darwaza added some five years later. It was built in the manner of Indian mosques, with iwans around a central courtyard. A distinguishing feature is the row of [[chhatri]] over the sanctuary. There are three [[mihrab]]s in each of the seven bays, while the large central mihrab is covered by a dome, it is decorated with white marble [[inlay]], in geometric patterns.\n* [[Tomb of Salim Chishti]]: A white marble encased tomb of the [[Sufi]] saint, [[Salim Chisti]] (1478\u20131572), within the Jama Masjid's ''[[sahn]]'', courtyard. The single-storey structure is built around a central square chamber, within which is the grave of the saint, under an ornate wooden canopy encrusted with [[mother-of-pearl]] mosaic. Surrounding it is a covered passageway for [[circumambulation]], with carved ''[[Jali]]s'', stone pierced screens all around with intricate geometric design and an entrance to the south. The tomb is influenced by earlier mausolea of the early 15th century [[Gujarat Sultanate]] period. Other striking features of the tomb are white marble serpentine [[Bracket (architecture)|bracket]]s, which support sloping [[eave]]s around the [[parapet]]. <br/> On the left of the tomb, to the east, stands a red sandstone tomb of [[Islam Khan I]], son of Shaikh Badruddin Chisti and grandson of Shaikh Salim Chishti, who became a general in the Mughal army in the reign of [[Jahangir]]. The tomb is topped by a dome and thirty-six small domed ''[[chattri]]s'' and contains a number of graves, some unnamed, all male descendants of Shaikh Salim Chisti.\n* Diwan-i-Aam: ''Diwan-i-Aam'' or Hall of Public Audience, is a building typology found in many cities where the ruler meets the general public. In this case, it is a pavilion-like multi-bayed rectangular structure fronting a large open space. South west of the Diwan-i-Am and next to the Turkic Sultana's House stand Turkic Baths.\n* Diwan-i-Khas: the ''Diwan-i-Khas'' or Hall of Private Audience, is a plain square building with four ''chhatris'' on the roof. However it is famous for its central pillar, which has a square base and an octagonal shaft, both carved with bands of geometric and floral designs, further its thirty-six serpentine [[Bracket (architecture)|bracket]]s support a circular platform for Akbar, which is connected to each corner of the building on the first floor, by four stone walkways. It is here that Akbar had representatives of different religions discuss their faiths and gave private audience.\n* [[Ibadat Khana]]: (House of Worship) was a meeting house built in 1575 CE by the Mughal Emperor Akbar, where the foundations of a new [[Syncretistic]] faith, ''[[Din-e-Ilahi]]'' were laid by Akbar.\n* Anup Talao: Anup Talao was built by Raja Anup Singh Sikarwar A ornamental pool with a central platform and four bridges leading up to it. Some of the important buildings of the royal enclave are surround by it including, ''Khwabgah'' (House of Dreams) Akbar's residence, ''Panch Mahal'', a five-storey palace, ''Diwan-i-Khas''(Hall of Private Audience), ''Ankh Michauli'' and the Astrologer's Seat, in the south-west corner of the Pachisi Court.\n* Hujra-i-Anup Talao: Said to be the residence of Akbar's Muslim wife, although this is disputed due to its small size.\n* [[Mariam-uz-Zamani]]'s Palace: The building of Akbar's Rajput wives, including [[Mariam-uz-Zamani]], shows Gujarati influence and is built around a courtyard, with special care being taken to ensure privacy.\n* [[Naubat Khana]]: Also known as [[Naqqar Khana]] meaning a ''drum house'', where musician used drums to announce the arrival of the Emperor. It is situated ahead of the ''Hathi Pol Gate'' or the Elephant Gate, the south entrance to the complex, suggesting that it was the imperial entrance.\n* Pachisi Court: A square marked out as a large board game, the precursor to modern day [[Ludo (board game)|Ludo]] game where people served as the playing pieces.\n* [[Panch Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri|Panch Mahal]]: A five-storied palatial structure, with the tiers gradually diminishing in size, till the final one, which is a single large-domed [[chhatri]]. Originally pierced stone screens faced the facade and probably sub-divided the interior as well, suggesting it was built for the ladies of the court. The floors are supported by intricately carved columns on each level, totalling to 176 columns in all.\n* [[Birbal]]'s House: The house of Akbar's favourite minister, who was a Hindu. Notable features of the building are the horizontal sloping sunshades or ''chajjas'' and the brackets which support them.\n* Hiran Minar: The Hiran Minar, or Elephant Tower, is a circular tower covered with stone projections in the form of elephant tusks. Traditionally it was thought to have been erected as a memorial to the Emperor Akbar's favourite elephant. However, it was probably a used as a starting point for subsequent mileposts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/apac/photocoll/g/019pho000001003u00568000.html|title=General view of the Hiran Minar, Fatehpur Sikri|first=Colin|last=Wright|website=www.bl.uk|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther buildings included ''Taksal'' (mint), ''Daftar Khana'' (Records Office), ''Karkhana'' (royal workshop), ''Khazana'' (Treasury), ''Hammam'' (Turkic Baths), ''Darogha's'' Quarters, stables, Caravan sarai, [[Hakim (title)|Hakim]]'s quarters, etc.\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of [[2011 Indian Census]], Fatehpur Sikri had a total population of 32,905, of which 17,392 were males and 15,513 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 5,139. The total number of literates in Fatehpur Sikri was 17,236, which constituted 52.4% of the population with male literacy of 60.4% and female literacy of 43.4%. The effective literacy rate of 7+ population of Fatehpur Sikri was 62.1%, of which male literacy rate was 71.6% and female literacy rate was 51.4%. The [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] population was 4,110 and 1 respectively. Fatehpur Sikri had 4936 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Fatehpur Sikri |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=144061 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nFatehpur Sikri is one of the fifteen [[Block (country subdivision)|Block]] headquarters in the [[Agra district]]. It has 52 [[Gram panchayat]]s (Village [[Panchayat]]) under it.\n\nThe [[Fatehpur Sikri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Fatehpur Sikri]], is a constituency of the [[Lok Sabha]], Lower house of the [[Indian Parliament]], and further comprises five [[Vidhan Sabha]]([[legislative assembly]]) segments:\n* Agra Rural\n* Fatehpur Sikri\n* [[Kheragarh]]\n* [[Fatehabad, Agra|Fatehabad]]\n* [[Bah]]\n\nIn all, there are 12 villages of [[Sisodia]] Rajputs near Fatehpur Sikri fort in Agra district. These are [[Daultabad]], Nayavas, Satha, Korai, Behrawati, Byara, Undera, Kachora, Singarpur, Vidyapur, Onera, Arrua.\n\n==Transport==\n\nFatehpur Sikri is about {{convert|39|km}} from Agra. The nearest Airport is [[Agra Airport]] (also known as [[Kheria Airport]]), {{convert|40|km}} from Fatehpur Sikri. The nearest railway station is [[Fatehpur Sikri railway station]], about {{convert|1|km}} from the city centre. It is connected to Agra and neighbouring centres by road, where regular bus services operated by [[UPSRTC]] ply, in addition to tourist buses and taxis.\n\n==In literature==\n\n{{Wikisource|Letitia Elizabeth Landon (L. E. L.) in Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1833/Futtypore Sicri|'Futtypore Sicri',<br/>a poem by L. E. L.}}\nIn her poem ''Futtypore Sicri'' (Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1833), [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]] associates its abandonment with 'the revenge of the dead'.\n\n[[Vita Sackville-West]], in her novel ''[[All Passion Spent]]'', places the key meeting between Deborah, Lady Slane, and Mr FitzGeorge, at Fatehpur Sikri. \n<blockquote>\nShe stood again on the terrace of the deserted Indian city looking across the brown landscape where puffs of rising dust marked at intervals the road to Agra. She leaned her arms upon the warm parapet and slowly twirled her parasol. She twirled it because she was slightly ill at ease. She and the young man beside her were isolated from the rest of the world.<ref>From ''All Passion Spent'' (Hogarth Press,1931)</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" height=\"150px\" perrow=\"6\" align=\"center\">\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 099.JPG|Buland Darwaza\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri near Agra 2016-03 img05.jpg|Buland Darwaza back side.\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 042.JPG|King's Gate\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 120.JPG|Entrance to Queen's Palace\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 175.JPG|Diwan-i-Khas\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 146.JPG|[[Mariam-uz-Zamani]] House\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 163.JPG|Anup Talao\nFile:Panoramic vie of Fahpur Sikri Palace.jpg|Panoramic view of Fatehpur Sikri Palace\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India}}\n\n*[[Lahore Fort]]\n*[[Tomb of Jehangir]]\n*[[Jama Masjid]]\n*[[Tomb of Salim Chishti]]\n*[[Ibadat Khana]]\n*[[Mariam-uz-Zamani]]\n*[[Naubat Khana]]\n*[[Buland Darwaza]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite book |last=Latif |first=Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Agra, Historical & Descriptive |url=https://archive.org/stream/agrahistoricald00latgoog#page/n9/mode/1up |year=1896 |publisher=Calcutta Central Press}}\n*{{cite book |last=Fazl |first=Abul |authorlink=Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak |translator=[[H. Beveridge]] |title=The Akbarnama (Vol. I-III) |url=http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00701020%26ct%3D0 |date=1897\u20131939 |publisher=[[Asiatic Society]] |location=Calcutta |access-date=6 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100604053747/http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00701020%26ct%3D0 |archive-date=4 June 2010 |url-status=dead }}\n*{{cite book |last= Keene |first=Henry George |authorlink=Henry George Keene (1826\u20131915) |title=A Handbook for Visitors to Agra and Its Neighbourhood |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/ahandbookforvis00keengoog#page/n71/mode/1up |chapter=Fatehpur Sikri |year=1899 |edition=Sixth |publisher=Thacker, Spink & Co. |page=53}}\n*{{cite book |last=Malleson |first=G. B., Colonel |title=Akbar and the rise of the Mughal Empire |series=[[Rulers of India series]] |url=https://archive.org/stream/rulersofindiaakb009177mbp#page/n7/mode/2up |year=1899 |publisher=Oxford at the Clarendon Press}}\n*{{cite book |last=Havell |first=E. B. |authorlink=Ernest Binfield Havell |title=A handbook to Agra and the Taj, Sikandra, Fatehpur-Sikri and the neighbourhood (1904) |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924024120200#page/n11/mode/2up |year=1904 |publisher=Longmans, Greens & Co. |location=London}}\n*{{cite book |last=Garbe |first=Dr.Richard von |title=Akbar&nbsp;\u2013 Emperor of India. A picture of life and customs from the sixteenth century |url=https://archive.org/stream/akbaremperorofin00garb#page/n7/mode/2up |year=1909 |publisher=The Opencourt Publishing Company |location=Chicago}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Vincent Arthur |authorlink=Vincent Arthur Smith |title=Akbar the Great Mogul, 1542-1605 |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924024056503#page/n7/mode/2up |year=1917 |publisher=Oxford at The Clarendon Press}}\n*{{cite book |last=Hussain |first=Muhammad Ashraf |title=A Guide To Fatehpur Sikri |url=https://archive.org/stream/guidetofatehpurs035312mbp#page/n3/mode/2up |year=1947 |publisher=The Manager, Government of India Press}}\n*{{cite book |last=Rezavi |first=S. Ali Nadeem |title=Exploring Mughal Gardens at Fathpur Sikri |url=https://archive.org/stream/ExploringMughalGardensAtFathpurSikri/MughalGardens#page/n1/mode/2up |year=1998 |publisher=Indian History Congress}}\n*{{cite book |last=Petruccioli |first=Attilio |title=Fatehpur Sikri |year=1992 |publisher=Ernst & Sohn}}\n*{{cite book |last=Rizvi |first=Athar Abbas |title=Fatehpur Sikri (World heritage series) |year=2002 |publisher=Archaeological Survey of India |isbn=81-87780-09-6}}\n*{{cite book |last=Rezavi |first=Syed Ali Nadeem |title=\"Iranian Influence on Medieval Indian Architecture\", The Growth of Civilizations in India and Iran |url=https://archive.org/stream/iranianInfluenceOnMedievalIndianArchitectureTheGrowthOf/IranianIndianArchitecture#page/n1/mode/2up |year=2002 |publisher=Tulika}}\n*{{cite book |last=Jain |first=Kulbhushan |title=Fatehpur Sikri: where spaces touch perfection |year=2003 |publisher=VDG |isbn=3-89739-363-8}}\n*{{cite book |last= Rezavi |first=Dr. Syed Ali Nadeem |title=Religious Disputation and Imperial Ideology: The Purpose and Location of Akbar's Ibadatkhana |url=https://archive.org/stream/ReligiousDisputationAndImperialIdeologyThePurposeAndLocationOf/Ibadatkhana#page/n0/mode/2up |year=2008 |publisher=SAGE Publications}}\n*{{cite book |last=Havell |first=E. B. |authorlink=Ernest Binfield Havell |title=A handbook to Agra and the Taj, Sikandra, Fatehpur-Sikri and the neighbourhood (1904) |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924024120200#page/n11/mode/2up |year=1904 |publisher=Longmans, Greens & Co., London |ref=Ha}}\n*{{cite book |last=Smith |first=Vincent Arthur |authorlink=Vincent Arthur Smith |title=Akbar the Great Mogul, 1542-1605 |url=https://archive.org/stream/cu31924024056503#page/n7/mode/2up |year=1917 |publisher=Oxford at The Clarendon Press |ref=Sm}}\n* {{cite book |last=Asher |first=Catherine Ella Blanshard |title=Architecture of Mughal India, (Part 1) |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA65 |year=1992 |publisher=Cambridge University Press | isbn=0-521-26728-5 |chapter=Age of Akbar |ref=harv}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110629172350/http://archnet.org/library/places/one-place.jsp?place_id=1672 Fatehpur Sikri, Detailed study] ''Arch Net Digital Library''\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110905082441/http://asi.nic.in/asi_monu_whs_fatehpursikri.asp Fatehpur Sikri] at ''[[Archaeological Survey of India]]''\n* [http://www.art-and-archaeology.com/india/fatehpur/fatmap1.html An interactive map of Fatehpur Sikri]\n* [http://thinkingparticle.com/articles/fatehpur-sikri-history-agra-india Fatehpur Sikri History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141230010913/http://places.wonobo.com/agra/Fatehpur-Sikri/1564605/Interior 360 degree walkthrough of Fatehpur Sikri]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Agra}}\n{{World Heritage Sites in India}}\n{{Mughal Empire|state=collapsed}}\n{{Agra Division topics}}\n\n[[Category:Fatehpur Sikri| ]]\n[[Category:Forts in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Sites in India]]\n[[Category:Medieval India]]\n[[Category:History of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Mughal fortress gardens in India]]\n[[Category:Mughal architecture]]\n[[Category:Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Ghost towns in India]]\n[[Category:Former capital cities in India]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in India]]\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Agra district]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Agra district]]\n[[Category:Sandstone buildings in India]]\n[[Category:Royal residences in India]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Agra]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Archaeological monuments in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1571]]\n[[Category:1571 in India]]\n[[Category:Akbar]]\n[[Category:1659 establishments in the Mughal Empire]]\n[[Category:Agra district]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Town in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2016}}\n{{More footnotes|date=March 2016}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Fatehpur Sikri\n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| image_skyline                   = File:Fatehput Sikiri Buland Darwaza gate 2010.jpg\n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = [[Buland Darwaza]], the {{Convert|54|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} entrance to Fatehpur Sikri complex\n| nickname                        = \n| image_map                       = \n| map_alt                         = \n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Uttar Pradesh#India#Asia\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = \n| coordinates                     = {{coord|27.091|N|77.661|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Agra district|Agra]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = [[Akbar]]\n| discovered by                   = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"Census2011Gov\"/>\n| population_total                = 32905\n| population_as_of                = \n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = Auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| demographics_type1      = [[Language]]\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]<ref name=\"langoff\">{{cite web|title=52nd REPORT OF THE COMMISSIONER FOR LINGUISTIC MINORITIES IN INDIA|url=http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|website=nclm.nic.in|publisher=[[Ministry of Minority Affairs]]|access-date=26 December 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525141614/http://nclm.nic.in/shared/linkimages/NCLM52ndReport.pdf|archive-date=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n| demographics1_title2    = Additional&nbsp;official\n| demographics1_info2     = [[Urdu]]<ref name=\"langoff\"/>\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| registration_plate              = UP-80\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site\n  |child = yes\n  |ID = 255\n  |Year = 1986\n  |Criteria = Cultural: ii, iii, iv\n  }}\n}}\n[[File:Kos Minar 793.jpg|thumb|[[Kos Minar]]#793 at 12 mile on [[Agra]]-Fatehpur Sikri Road section of [[National Highway 21 (India)|National Highway 21]]]]\n'''Fatehpur Sikri''' is a town in the [[Agra District]] of [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]. The city itself was founded as the capital of [[Mughal Empire]] in 1571 by [[Mughal Emperor|Emperor]] [[Akbar]], serving this role from 1571 to 1585, when Akbar abandoned it due to a campaign in [[Punjab (region)|Punjab]] and was later completely abandoned in 1610.<ref name=\"Routlegde\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9A-EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82#v=onepage&f=false|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|author=Andrew Petersen|publisher=Routlegde|page=82|isbn=9781134613656|date=11 March 2002}}</ref>\n\nThe name of the city is derived from the village called ''Sikri'' which occupied the spot before. An [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) excavation from 1999-2000 indicated that there was a habitation, temples and commercial centres here before Akbar built his capital. The region was settled by [[Sunga]]s following their expansion. In 12th century, it was briefly controlled by [[Sakarwar|Sikarwar]] Rajputs.\n\nThe ''[[khanqah]]'' of [[Sheikh (Sufism)|Sheikh]] [[Salim Chisti|Salim]] existed earlier at this place. Akbar's son [[Jahangir]] was born at the village of Sikri in 1569 and that year Akbar began construction of a religious compound to commemorate the Sheikh who had predicted the birth. After Jahangir's second birthday, he began the construction of a walled city and imperial palace here. The city came to be known as ''Fatehpur Sikri'', the \"City of Victory\", after Akbar's [[Akbar's conquest of Gujarat|victorious Gujarat campaign in 1573]].\n\nAfter occupying [[Agra]] in 1803, the English established an administrative center here and it remained so until 1850. In 1815, the [[Francis Rawdon-Hastings, 1st Marquess of Hastings|Marquess of Hastings]] ordered repair of monuments at Sikri.\n\n==History==\nArchaeological evidence points to settlement of the region since the [[Painted Grey Ware culture|Painted Grey Ware period]]. According to historian Syed Ali Nadeem Rezavi, region flourished under [[Sunga]] rule and then under [[Sakarwar|Sikarwar]] Rajputs, who built a fortress when they controlled the area briefly in the 12th century.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Rezavi |first1=Syed Ali Nadeem |title=Sikri before Akbar |date=2013 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-908256-8 |url=https://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/acprof:oso/9780198084037.001.0001/acprof-9780198084037-chapter-2 |accessdate=13 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Safvi |first1=Rana |title=The secrets about Fatehpur Sikri |url=https://www.thehindu.com/opinion/columns/the-secrets-about-fatehpur-sikri/article21381895.ece |accessdate=13 January 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=10 December 2017 |language=en-IN}}</ref> \n\nBasing his arguments on the excavations by the [[Archaeological Survey of India]] (ASI) in 1999\u20132000 at the Chabeli Tila, senior [[Agra]] journalist Bhanu Pratap Singh said the antique pieces, statues, and structures all point to a lost \"culture and religious site,\" more than 1,000 years ago. \"The excavations yielded a rich crop of [[Jainism|Jain]] statues, hundreds of them, including the foundation stone of a temple with the date. The statues were a thousand years old of ''Bhagwan'' Adi Nath, ''Bhagwan'' [[Rishabhanatha|Rishabh Nath]], ''Bhagwan'' [[Mahavira|Mahavir]] and [[Yakshini#Yakshis in Jainism|Jain Yakshinis]],\" said Swarup Chandra Jain, senior leader of the [[Jain community]]. Historian Sugam Anand states that there is proof of habitation, temples and commercial centres before Akbar established it as his capital. He states that the open space on a ridge was used by Akbar to build his capital.<ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri, that Mughal emperor Akbar established as his capital and is now a World Heritage site, was once a \"flourishing trade and Jain pilgrimage centre\", a new book says. |url=http://indiatimes.com/lifestyle/travel/fatehpur-sikri-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre-89615.html |work=[[India Times]] |date=17 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri was once a Jain pilgrimage centre: Book |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/uttar-pradesh/fatehpur-sikri-was-once-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre-book_831821.html |work=[[Zee News]] |date=27 February 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Fatehpur Sikri was once a Jain pilgrimage centre |url=http://www.freepressjournal.in/fatehpur-sikri-was-once-a-jain-pilgrimage-centre/154050 |work=[[The Free Press Journal]] |date=28 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nBut preceding Akbar's appropriation of the site for his capital city, his predecessors [[Babur]] and [[Humayun]] did much to redesign Fatehpur Sikri's urban layout.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Petruccioli|first=Attilio|date=1984|title=The Process Evolved by Control Systems of Urban Design in the Mogul Epoch in India: The Case of Fatehpur Sikri|url=https://archnet.org/system/publications/contents/3483/original/DPC1425.pdf?1384775285|journal=Environmental Design|volume=|pages=18\u201327|via=ARCHNET}}</ref> Attilio Petruccioli, a scholar of Islamic architecture and Professor of Landscape Architecture at the Polytechnic University of Bari, Italy, notes that \"Babur and his successors\" wanted \"to get away from the noise and confusion of Agra [and] build an uninterrupted sequence of gardens on the free left bank of the Yamuna, linked both by boat and by land.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Petruccioli adds that when such escapist landscapes are envisioned, the monument becomes the organizing element of the city at large, partly due to its orientation at a significant location and partly due to its sheer size. Humayun's Tomb was one such organizing element, which at a height of 150 feet towered over the city and is now one of the most recognizable Mughal monuments in the country.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe place was much loved by [[Babur]], who called it ''Shukri'' (\"Thanks\"), after its large lake that was used by Mughal armies.<ref name=Asher>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA22|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|page=22|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref> [[Annette Beveridge]] in her translation of ''[[Baburnama]]'' noted that Babur [[diacritic|points]] \"Sikri\" to read \"Shukri\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Babur-nama: (Memoirs of Babur)|author=Annette Susannah Beveridge|publisher= Sang-e-Meel Publications, University of Michigan Press|year=2002|page=851|isbn=9789693512939}}</ref> Per his memoirs, Babur constructed a garden here called the \"Garden of Victory\" after defeating [[Rana Sangha]] at its outskirts. [[Gulbadan Begum]]'s ''Humayun-Nama'' describes that in the garden he built an octagonal pavilion which he used for relaxation and writing. In the center of the nearby lake, he built a large platform. A [[baoli]] exists at the base of a rock scarp about a kilometer from the [[Hiran Minar]]. This was probably the original site of a well-known [[Epigraphy|epigraph]] commemorating his victory.<ref name=Asher/>\n\n[[Abul Fazl]] records Akbar's reasons for the foundation of the city in ''[[Akbarnama]]'': \"Inasmuch as his exalted sons [Salim and [[Murad Mirza|Murad]]] had been born at Sikri, and the God-knowing spirit of Shaikh Salim had taken possession thereof, his holy heart desired to give outward splendour to this spot which possessed spiritual grandeur. Now that his standards had arrived at this place, his former design was pressed forward, and an order was issued that the superintendents of affairs should erect lofty buildings for the special use of the Shahinshah.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=The Cambridge History of India, Volume 4|author=[[Edward James Rapson]], [[Sir Wolseley Haig]], [[Sir Richard Burn]], [[H. H. Dodwell|Henry Dodwell]], [[Mortimer Wheeler]]|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1963|page=103}}</ref>\n\nAkbar remained heirless until 1569 when his son, who became known as [[Jahangir]], was born in the village of Sikri in 1569. Akbar began the construction of a religious compound in honor of the [[Chishti Order|Chisti saint]] [[Sheikh (Sufism)|Sheikh]] [[Salim Chishti|Salim]], who had predicted the birth of Jahangir. After Jahangir's second birthday, he began the construction of a walled city and imperial palace probably to test his son's stamina. By constructing his capital at the ''[[khanqah]]'' of Sheikh Salim, Akbar associated himself with this popular Sufi order and brought legitimacy to his reign through this affiliation.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA51|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|pages=51\u201353|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref>\n\nThe city was founded in 1571 and was named after the village of Sikri which occupied the spot before. The [[Buland Darwaza]] was built in honor of his [[Akbar's conquest of Gujarat|successful campaign]] in [[Gujarat Sultanate|Gujarat]], when the city came to be known as ''Fatehpur Sikri'' - \"The City of Victory\". It was named after the Sikri village which had existed on the spot before. It was abandoned by Akbar in 1585 when he went to fight a campaign in Punjab. It was later completely abandoned by 1610. The reason for its abandonment is usually given as the failure of the water supply, though Akbar's loss of interest may also have been the reason since it was built solely on his whim.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=9A-EAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA82#v=onepage&f=false|title=Dictionary of Islamic Architecture|author=Andrew Petersen|publisher=Routlegde|pages=82\u201384|isbn=9781134613656|date=11 March 2002}}</ref> [[Ralph Fitch]] described it as such, \"Agra and Fatehpore Sikri are two very great cities, either of them much greater than London, and very populous. Between Agra and Fatehpore are 12 miles (Kos) and all the way is a market of victuals and other things, as full as though a man were still in a town, and so many people as if a man were in a market.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Akbar the Great, Vol. III: Society and culture in 16th century India|author=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava|publisher=Shiva Lal Agarwala|year=1973|page=10|author-link=Ashirbadi Lal Srivastava}}</ref>\n\nAkbar visited the city only once in 1601 after abandoning it. [[William Finch (merchant)|William Finch]], visiting it 4\u20135 years after his death, stated, \"It is all ruinate,\" writing, \"lying like a waste desert.\"<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04ellRQx4nMC&pg=PA179|title=Emperors of the Peacock Throne: The Saga of the Great Mughals|author=Abraham Eraly|publisher=Penguin Books India|year=200|page=179|isbn=9780141001432|author-link=Abraham Eraly}}</ref> During the epidemic of [[bubonic plague]] from 1616\u20131624, [[Jahangir]] stayed for three months here in 1619.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=04ellRQx4nMC&pg=PA284|title=Emperors of the Peacock Throne: The Saga of the Great Mughals|author=Abraham Eraly|publisher=Penguin Books India|year=2000|page=284|isbn=9780141001432|author-link=Abraham Eraly}}</ref> [[Muhammad Shah]] stayed here for some time and the repair works were started again. However, with the decline of Mughal Empire, the conditions of the buildings worsened.<ref name=Survey/>\n\nWhile chasing [[Daulat Rao Sindhia]]'s battalions in October 1803, [[Gerard Lake]] left the most cumbersome baggage and siege guns in the town.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qweZWra_tbwC&pg=PA200|title=The Anglo-Maratha Campaigns and the Contest for India: The Struggle for Control of the South Asian Military Economy|author=Randolf G. S. Cooper|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2003|page=200|isbn=9780521824446}}</ref> After occupying Agra in 1803, the English established an administrative center here and it remained so until 1850.<ref name=Survey>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4TslDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA262|title=Towns and Cities of Medieval India: A Brief Survey|author=Aniruddha Roy|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=2016|page=262|isbn=9781351997317}}</ref> In 1815,  the [[Francis Rawdon-Hastings, 1st Marquess of Hastings|Marquess of Hastings]] ordered repairment of monuments at Sikri and Sikandra.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Singh|first1=Upinder|author-link=Upinder Singh|title=The discovery of ancient India: early archaeologists and the beginnings of archaeology|date=2004|publisher=Permanent Black|isbn=9788178240886|page=185}}</ref> The town was a [[municipality]] from 1865 to 1904 and was later made a [[notified area]]. The population in 1901 was 7,147.<ref>{{cite book|title=Imperial Gazetteer of India: Provincial Series, Volume 24, Issue 1|date=1908|publisher=Superintendent of Government Print|page=415}}</ref>\n\n==Architecture==\n[[File:General Plan of Fatehpur Sikri City India 1917.jpg|thumb|250px|General plan of Fatehpur Sikri city in 1917.]]\nFatehpur Sikri sits on rocky ridge, {{convert|3|km}} in length and {{convert|1|km|abbr=on}} wide and palace city is surrounded by a {{convert|6|km|abbr=on}} wall on three sides with the fourth bordered by a lake. The city is generally organized around this 40 m high ridge, and falls roughly into the shape of a rhombus. The general layout of the ground structures, especially the \"continuous and compact pattern of gardens and services and facilities\" that characterized the city leads urban archaeologists to conclude that Fatehpur Sikri was built primarily to afford leisure and luxury to its famous residents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe dynastic architecture of Fatehpur Sikri was modelled on [[Timurid architecture|Timurid forms and styles]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Islam: Art and Architecture|author=Markus Hattstein, Peter Delius|publisher=K\u00f6nemann|year=2000|pages=466}}</ref> The city was built massively and preferably with red sandstone.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P2R3a3KLl2IC&pg=PA1|title=Mughal Architecture|author=Moritz Herrmann|publisher=GRIN Verlag|year=2011|page=3|isbn=9783640930036}}</ref> Gujarati influences are also seen in its architectural vocabulary and decor of the palaces of Fatehpur Sikri.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mughal Architecture: An Outline of Its History and Development (1526-1858)|author=Ebba Koch|publisher=Prestel|year=1991|page=60|author-link=Ebba Koch}}</ref> The city's architecture reflects both the Hindu and Muslim form of domestic architecture popular in India at the time.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3ctLNvx68hIC&pg=PA50|title=Architecture of Mughal India, Part 1, Volume 4|author=Catherine Ella Blanshard Asher|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1992|page=50|isbn=9780521267281}}</ref> The remarkable preservation of these original spaces allows modern archaeologists to reconstruct scenes of Mughal court life, and to better understand the hierarchy of the city's royal and noble residents.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIt is accessed through gates along the {{convert|5|mi}} long fort wall, namely, Delhi Gate, the Lal Gate, the Agra Gate and Birbal's Gate, Chandanpal Gate, The Gwalior Gate, the Tehra Gate, the Chor Gate, and the Ajmeri Gate. The palace contains summer palace and winter palace for Queen Jodha.\n\n[[File:Jama Masjid-Sikri-Fatehpur Sikri-India0008.JPG|thumb|250px|[[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri]]]]\n[[File:Fatehpur Sikiri Salim Chishti Tomb 2010.jpg|thumb|250px|[[Tomb of Salim Chishti]] in [[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri|Jama Masjid]] courtyard, Fatehpur Sikri]]\n[[File:Panch Mahal-Fatehpur-Fatehpur Sikri India0014.JPG|thumb|250px|[[Panch Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri]]]]\n[[File:Hiran Minar FatehpurSikri.jpg|thumb|Hiran Minar, Fatehpur Sikri]]\n\nSome of the important buildings in this city, both religious and secular are:\n\n* [[Buland Darwaza]]: Set into the south wall of congregational mosque, the Buland Darwaza at Fatehpur Sikri is {{convert|55|m}} high, from the ground, gradually making a transition to a human scale in the inside. The gate was added around five years after the completion of the mosque c. 1576-1577 as a victory arch, to commemorate [[Akbar]]'s successful Gujarat campaign. It carries two inscriptions in the archway, one of which reads: \"Isa, Son of Mariam said: The world is a bridge, pass over it, but build no houses on it. He who hopes for an hour may hope for eternity. The world endures but an hour. Spend it in prayer, for the rest is unseen\". <br/> The central portico comprises three arched entrances, with the largest one, in the centre, is known locally as the Horseshoe Gate, after the custom of nailing horseshoes to its large wooden doors for luck. Outside the giant steps of the Buland Darwaza to the left is a deep well.\n* [[Jama Masjid, Fatehpur Sikri|Jama Masjid]]: It is a ''[[Jama Mosque]]'' meaning the congregational mosque and was perhaps one of the first buildings to be constructed in the complex, as its epigraph gives [[Hijri year|AH]] 979 (A.D. 1571-72) as the date of its completion, with a massive entrance to the courtyard, the Buland-Darwaza added some five years later. It was built in the manner of Indian mosques, with iwans around a central courtyard. A distinguishing feature is the row of [[chhatri]] over the sanctuary. There are three [[mihrab]]s in each of the seven bays, while the large central mihrab is covered by a dome, it is decorated with white marble [[inlay]], in geometric patterns.\n* [[Tomb of Salim Chishti]]: A white marble encased tomb of the [[Sufi]] saint, [[Salim Chisti]] (1478\u20131572), within the Jama Masjid's ''[[sahn]]'', courtyard. The single-storey structure is built around a central square chamber, within which is the grave of the saint, under an ornate wooden canopy encrusted with [[mother-of-pearl]] mosaic. Surrounding it is a covered passageway for [[circumambulation]], with carved ''[[Jali]]s'', stone pierced screens all around with intricate geometric design and an entrance to the south. The tomb is influenced by earlier mausolea of the early 15th century [[Gujarat Sultanate]] period. Other striking features of the tomb are white marble serpentine [[Bracket (architecture)|bracket]]s, which support sloping [[eave]]s around the [[parapet]]. <br/> On the left of the tomb, to the east, stands a red sandstone tomb of [[Islam Khan I]], son of Shaikh Badruddin Chisti and grandson of Shaikh Salim Chishti, who became a general in the Mughal army in the reign of [[Jahangir]]. The tomb is topped by a dome and thirty-six small domed ''[[chattri]]s'' and contains a number of graves, some unnamed, all male descendants of Shaikh Salim Chisti.\n* Diwan-i-Aam: ''Diwan-i-Aam'' or Hall of Public Audience, is a building typology found in many cities where the ruler meets the general public. In this case, it is a pavilion-like multi-bayed rectangular structure fronting a large open space. South west of the Diwan-i-Am and next to the Turkic Sultana's House stand Turkic Baths.\n* Diwan-i-Khas: the ''Diwan-i-Khas'' or Hall of Private Audience, is a plain square building with four ''chhatris'' on the roof. However it is famous for its central pillar, which has a square base and an octagonal shaft, both carved with bands of geometric and floral designs, further its thirty-six serpentine [[Bracket (architecture)|bracket]]s support a circular platform for Akbar, which is connected to each corner of the building on the first floor, by four stone walkways. It is here that Akbar had representatives of different religions discuss their faiths and gave private audience.\n* [[Ibadat Khana]]: (House of Worship) was a meeting house built in 1575 CE by the Mughal Emperor Akbar, where the foundations of a new [[Syncretistic]] faith, ''[[Din-e-Ilahi]]'' were laid by Akbar.\n* Anup Talao: Anup Talao was built by Raja Anup Singh Sikarwar A ornamental pool with a central platform and four bridges leading up to it. Some of the important buildings of the royal enclave are surround by it including, ''Khwabgah'' (House of Dreams) Akbar's residence, ''Panch Mahal'', a five-storey palace, ''Diwan-i-Khas''(Hall of Private Audience), ''Ankh Michauli'' and the Astrologer's Seat, in the south-west corner of the Pachisi Court.\n* Hujra-i-Anup Talao: Said to be the residence of Akbar's Muslim wife, although this is disputed due to its small size.\n* [[Mariam-uz-Zamani]]'s Palace: The building of Akbar's Rajput wives, including [[Mariam-uz-Zamani]], shows Gujarati influence and is built around a courtyard, with special care being taken to ensure privacy.\n* [[Naubat Khana]]: Also known as [[Naqqar Khana]] meaning a ''drum house'', where musician used drums to announce the arrival of the Emperor. It is situated ahead of the ''Hathi Pol Gate'' or the Elephant Gate, the south entrance to the complex, suggesting that it was the imperial entrance.\n* Pachisi Court: A square marked out as a large board game, the precursor to modern day [[Ludo (board game)|Ludo]] game where people served as the playing pieces.\n* [[Panch Mahal, Fatehpur Sikri|Panch Mahal]]: A five-storied palatial structure, with the tiers gradually diminishing in size, till the final one, which is a single large-domed [[chhatri]]. Originally pierced stone screens faced the facade and probably sub-divided the interior as well, suggesting it was built for the ladies of the court. The floors are supported by intricately carved columns on each level, totalling to 176 columns in all.\n* [[Birbal]]'s House: The house of Akbar's favourite minister, who was a Hindu. Notable features of the building are the horizontal sloping sunshades or ''chajjas'' and the brackets which support them.\n* Hiran Minar: The Hiran Minar, or Elephant Tower, is a circular tower covered with stone projections in the form of elephant tusks. Traditionally it was thought to have been erected as a memorial to the Emperor Akbar's favourite elephant. However, it was probably a used as a starting point for subsequent mileposts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/onlineex/apac/photocoll/g/019pho000001003u00568000.html|title=General view of the Hiran Minar, Fatehpur Sikri|first=Colin|last=Wright|website=www.bl.uk|accessdate=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nOther buildings included ''Taksal'' (mint), ''Daftar Khana'' (Records Office), ''Karkhana'' (royal workshop), ''Khazana'' (Treasury), ''Hammam'' (Turkic Baths), ''Darogha's'' Quarters, stables, Caravan sarai, [[Hakim (title)|Hakim]]'s quarters, etc.\n\n==Demographics==\nAs of [[2011 Indian Census]], Fatehpur Sikri had a total population of 32,905, of which 17,392 were males and 15,513 were females. Population within the age group of 0 to 6 years was 5,139. The total number of literates in Fatehpur Sikri was 17,236, which constituted 52.4% of the population with male literacy of 60.4% and female literacy of 43.4%. The effective literacy rate of 7+ population of Fatehpur Sikri was 62.1%, of which male literacy rate was 71.6% and female literacy rate was 51.4%. The [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes]] population was 4,110 and 1 respectively. Fatehpur Sikri had 4936 households in 2011.<ref name=\"Census2011Gov\">{{cite web |title=Census of India: Fatehpur Sikri |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=144061 |website=www.censusindia.gov.in |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Administration==\nFatehpur Sikri is one of the fifteen [[Block (country subdivision)|Block]] headquarters in the [[Agra district]]. It has 52 [[Gram panchayat]]s (Village [[Panchayat]]) under it.\n\nThe [[Fatehpur Sikri (Lok Sabha constituency)|Fatehpur Sikri]], is a constituency of the [[Lok Sabha]], Lower house of the [[Indian Parliament]], and further comprises five [[Vidhan Sabha]]([[legislative assembly]]) segments:\n* Agra Rural\n* Fatehpur Sikri\n* [[Kheragarh]]\n* [[Fatehabad, Agra|Fatehabad]]\n* [[Bah]]\n\nIn all, there are 12 villages of [[Sisodia]] Rajputs near Fatehpur Sikri fort in Agra district. These are [[Daultabad]], Nayavas, Satha, Korai, Behrawati, Byara, Undera, Kachora, Singarpur, Vidyapur, Onera, Arrua.\n\n==Transport==\n\nFatehpur Sikri is about {{convert|39|km}} from Agra. The nearest Airport is [[Agra Airport]] (also known as [[Kheria Airport]]), {{convert|40|km}} from Fatehpur Sikri. The nearest railway station is [[Fatehpur Sikri railway station]], about {{convert|1|km}} from the city centre. It is connected to Agra and neighbouring centres by road, where regular bus services operated by [[UPSRTC]] ply, in addition to tourist buses and taxis.\n\n==In literature==\n\n{{Wikisource|Letitia Elizabeth Landon (L. E. L.) in Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1833/Futtypore Sicri|'Futtypore Sicri',<br/>a poem by L. E. L.}}\nIn her poem ''Futtypore Sicri'' (Fisher's Drawing Room Scrap Book, 1833), [[Letitia Elizabeth Landon]] associates its abandonment with 'the revenge of the dead'.\n\n[[Vita Sackville-West]], in her novel ''[[All Passion Spent]]'', places the key meeting between Deborah, Lady Slane, and Mr FitzGeorge, at Fatehpur Sikri. \n<blockquote>\nShe stood again on the terrace of the deserted Indian city looking across the brown landscape where puffs of rising dust marked at intervals the road to Agra. She leaned her arms upon the warm parapet and slowly twirled her parasol. She twirled it because she was slightly ill at ease. She and the young man beside her were isolated from the rest of the world.<ref>From ''All Passion Spent'' (Hogarth Press,1931)</ref>\n</blockquote>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" height=\"150px\" perrow=\"6\" align=\"center\">\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 099.JPG|Buland Darwaza\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri near Agra 2016-03 img05.jpg|Buland Darwaza back side.\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 042.JPG|King's Gate\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 120.JPG|Entrance to Queen's Palace\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 175.JPG|Diwan-i-Khas\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 146.JPG|[[Mariam-uz-Zamani]] House\nFile:Fatehpur Sikri 163.JPG|Anup Talao\nFile:Panoramic vie of Fahpur Sikri Palace.jpg|Panoramic view of Fatehpur Sikri Palace\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|India}}\n\n*[[Lahore Fort]]\n*[[Tomb of Jehangir]]\n*[[Jama Masjid]]\n*[[Tomb of Salim Chishti]]\n*[[Ibadat Khana]]\n*[[Mariam-uz-Zamani]]\n*[[Naubat Khana]]\n*[[Buland Darwaza]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*{{cite book |last=Latif |first=Mu\u1e25ammad |title=Agra, Historical & Descriptive |url=https://archive.org/stream/agrahistoricald00latgoog#page/n9/mode/1up |year=1896 |publisher=Calcutta Central Press}}\n*{{cite book |last=Fazl |first=Abul |authorlink=Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak