{"title_page": "Mark Beno", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = \n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth year|1951}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = {{death date and age |2019|08|24|1951}}\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = \n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = work on [[YBa2Cu3O7]]\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = 1\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Mark Beno''' (1951 \u2013 August 24, 2019) was a Senior Chemist at the [[Argonne National Laboratory]] best known for his work in chemical crystallography. He was the first to determine the crystal structure of the high temperature superconductor, YBa2Cu3O7, and his research continues to help researchers understand the types and structures that are likely to form this class. Beno was posthumously awarded the distinction of Fellow by the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS).<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\" />\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Personal life ===\nMark married Mary Beno and has a son. He is also survived by his mother and father (Genevieve and Donald), his brother (Henry) and his sister (Donna).<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aps.anl.gov/APS-News/2019-08-27/dr-mark-beno-aps-supporter-advocate-and-mentor-has-passed-away/2019-08-27/dr|title=Dr. Mark Beno, APS Supporter, Advocate, and Mentor, has Passed Away {{!}} Advanced Photon Source|website=www.aps.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nMark Beno received his B.S. in chemistry and mathematics from [[Marquette University]] in 1973 and a Ph.D in physical chemistry from [[Ohio State University]] in 1979.<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\" />\n\n=== Work ===\nMark Beno was a Senior Chemist at the [[United States Department of Energy|US Department of Energy]]'s (DOE) Argonne national Laboratory, joining the company in 1982.<ref name=\"anl.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/article/senior-chemist-mark-beno-receives-posthumous-aaas-fellow-distinction-for-lifetime-achievements|title=Senior Chemist Mark Beno Receives Posthumous AAAS Fellow Distinction for Lifetime Achievements {{!}} Argonne National Laboratory|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHis early work was focused on solving the crystal structures of [[Superconductivity|superconductors]], which are materials that conduct electricity with no resistance. He was the first to person to determine the crystal structure of the high temperature superconductor, YBa2Cu3O7, and published his results in a paper in 1989.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nAfter this, Beno became a member of the Synchrotron Radiation Science group in the Materials Science Division where he was in charge of the design, construction, and operations of the Basic Energy Sciences Synchrotron Radiation Center (BESSRC) beamlines at Sectors 11 and 12 of the Advanced Photon Source (APS), a DOE Office of Science User Facility.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nIn the mid-90s when APS was moving from construction to operations he was asked to help develop the scientific programs coming online. Beno was appointed the BESSRC group leader and moved with his group of colleagues to what is now the X-ray Science Division (XSD) in 2003. In 2005 he was named the deputy director for XSD, and has twice served as its interim division director.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nBeno's research has produced more than 190 publications which resulted in three awards from the DOE Basic Energy Sciences, Division of Materials Sciences, for Outstanding Scientific Accomplishment.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\n== Honours & awards ==\nIn 2019 Mark Beno was posthumously awarded the distinction of Fellow by the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS) for his expertise in chemical crystallography. He was the only Argonne scientist awarded this honour in 2019.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nThe AAAS honour recognizes diverse accomplishments, including pioneering research, leadership, teaching and mentoring, fostering collaborations and advancing public understanding of science. To be considered for the rank of Fellow, an AAAS member has to be nominated by three previously elected fellows, the steering group of an AAAS section, or the organization's CEO.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beno, Mark}}\n\n[[Category:Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Science]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| honorific_prefix  = \n| name              = \n| honorific_suffix  = \n| native_name       = \n| native_name_lang  = \n| image             = <!--(filename only, i.e. without \"File:\" prefix)-->\n| image_size        = \n| image_upright     = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = <!-- if different from \"name\" -->\n| birth_date        = {{birth year|1951}}\n| birth_place       = \n| death_date        = {{death date and age |2019|08|24|1951}}\n| death_place       = \n| death_cause       = \n| resting_place     = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}-->\n| home_town         =\n| other_names       = \n| siglum            =\n| pronounce         =\n| residence         = \n| citizenship       = \n| nationality       = \n| fields            = \n| workplaces        = \n| patrons           = \n| education         = \n| alma_mater        = \n| thesis_title      = <!--(or  | thesis1_title =  and  | thesis2_title = )-->\n| thesis_url        = <!--(or  | thesis1_url  =   and  | thesis2_url  =  )-->\n| thesis_year       = <!--(or  | thesis1_year =   and  | thesis2_year =  )-->\n| doctoral_advisor  = <!--(or  | doctoral_advisors = )-->\n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  = \n| known_for         = work on [[YBa2Cu3O7]]\n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| awards            = \n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| spouse            = <!--(or | spouses = )-->\n| partner           = <!--(or | partners = )-->\n| children          = 1\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     = \n| website           = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}-->\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Mark Beno''' (1951 \u2013 August 24, 2019) was a Senior Chemist at the [[Argonne National Laboratory]] best known for his work in chemical crystallography. He was the first to determine the crystal structure of the high temperature superconductor, YBa2Cu3O7, and his research continues to help researchers understand the types and structures that are likely to form this class. Beno was posthumously awarded the distinction of Fellow by the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS)<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\" />.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Personal life ===\nMark married Mary Beno and has a son. He is also survived by his mother and father (Genevieve and Donald), his brother (Henry) and his sister (Donna)<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aps.anl.gov/APS-News/2019-08-27/dr-mark-beno-aps-supporter-advocate-and-mentor-has-passed-away/2019-08-27/dr|title=Dr. Mark Beno, APS Supporter, Advocate, and Mentor, has Passed Away {{!}} Advanced Photon Source|website=www.aps.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>.\n\n=== Education ===\nMark Beno received his B.S. in chemistry and mathematics from [[Marquette University]] in 1973 and a Ph.D in physical chemistry from [[Ohio State University]] in 1979.<ref name=\"aps.anl.gov\" />\n\n=== Work ===\nMark Beno was a Senior Chemist at the [[United States Department of Energy|US Department of Energy]]'s (DOE) Argonne national Laboratory, joining the company in 1982.<ref name=\"anl.gov\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/article/senior-chemist-mark-beno-receives-posthumous-aaas-fellow-distinction-for-lifetime-achievements|title=Senior Chemist Mark Beno Receives Posthumous AAAS Fellow Distinction for Lifetime Achievements {{!}} Argonne National Laboratory|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref>\n\nHis early work was focused on solving the crystal structures of [[Superconductivity|superconductors]], which are materials that conduct electricity with no resistance. He was the first to person to determine the crystal structure of the high temperature superconductor, YBa2Cu3O7, and published his results in a paper in 1989.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nAfter this, Beno became a member of the Synchrotron Radiation Science group in the Materials Science Division where he was in charge of the design, construction, and operations of the Basic Energy Sciences Synchrotron Radiation Center (BESSRC) beamlines at Sectors 11 and 12 of the Advanced Photon Source (APS), a DOE Office of Science User Facility.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nIn the mid-90s when APS was moving from construction to operations he was asked to help develop the scientific programs coming online. Beno was appointed the BESSRC group leader and moved with his group of colleagues to what is now the X-ray Science Division (XSD) in 2003. In 2005 he was named the deputy director for XSD, and has twice served as its interim division director.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nBeno's research has produced more than 190 publications which resulted in three awards from the DOE Basic Energy Sciences, Division of Materials Sciences, for Outstanding Scientific Accomplishment.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\n== Honours & awards ==\nIn 2019 Mark Beno was posthumously awarded the distinction of Fellow by the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]] (AAAS) for his expertise in chemical crystallography. He was the only Argonne scientist awarded this honour in 2019.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\nThe AAAS honour recognizes diverse accomplishments, including pioneering research, leadership, teaching and mentoring, fostering collaborations and advancing public understanding of science. To be considered for the rank of Fellow, an AAAS member has to be nominated by three previously elected fellows, the steering group of an AAAS section, or the organization's CEO.<ref name=\"anl.gov\" />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beno, Mark}}\n\n[[Category:Chemistry]]\n[[Category:Science]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n", "name_user": "Andrybak", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix perMOS:PUNCTREF", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Beno"}
{"title_page": "Bengal Chemicals and Pharmaceuticals", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.\n| logo = Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd. logo.jpg\n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| logo_caption =\n| logo_padding =\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption =\n| trading_name =\n| former_name = Bengal Chemical & Pharmaceutical Works Ltd. (BCPW)\n| type =\n| traded_as =\n| ISIN =\n| industry =\n| predecessor = Bengal Chemical Works (1892\u20131901)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1901|04|12}} in [[Calcutta]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British India]]\n| founder = [[Prafulla Chandra R\u00e2y]]\n| hq_location = 6 Ganesh Chandra Avenue\n| hq_location_city = [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]]\n| hq_location_country = India\n| num_locations =\n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people =\n| products = [[Hospitol]]<br />[[Naphthalene]] balls<br />[[Phenyl]]\n| brands =\n| production =\n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services =\n| revenue =\n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income =\n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| profit = {{INR}}4 crore\n| profit_year = 2006-07\n| assets =\n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity =\n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owner = [[Government of India]]\n| members =\n| members_year = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees =\n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent =\n| divisions = * Aluminum Sulphate\n* drugs and pharmaceuticals\n* cosmetics and home products\n| subsid =\n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|http://bengalchemicals.co.in/}}\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.''', formerly '''Bengal Chemical & Pharmaceutical Works Ltd. (BCPW)''', is a [[Public Sector Undertaking]] (PSU). Established in [[Kolkata]], West Bengal in 1901 by [[Prafulla Chandra R\u00e2y]], it is India's first [[Pharmaceutical industry|pharmaceutical]] company.<ref name=\"profit\" /> The company manufactures such household Indian products as \"Hospitol\", \"[[naphthalene]] balls\", and \"Phenyl\".<ref name=\"bengalchemicals\" /><ref name=\"highbeam\" /> It is one of the first Indian companies to manufacture anti-snake venom serum (ASVS).<ref name=\"unions\" /> Following over 6 decades of losses, BCPL posted a profit of {{INRConvert|4|c}} in the fiscal year 2016-17.\n\n==History==\nIn 1892, Prafulla Chandra Ray rented house at 91 Upper Circular Road, Kolkata and founded Bengal Chemical Works with a capital of {{INRConvert|700|year=1892}}.<ref name=\"telegraph\" /> <ref name=\"about\" /> Ray founded the company as an individual initiative with the intention with fostering a spirit of entrepreneurship among the Bengali youth, and provide an alternative to jobs from the colonial British government. The company presented its herbal products the 1893 session of the Indian Medical Congress in Kolkata.<ref name=\"times\" />\n\nThe reputation of the company grew, and Ray added additional funds of {{INRConvert|2|l|year=1901}} to the company to increase the scale of production. The business was converted into a Limited Company, and on 12 April 1901 the company was renamed Bengal Chemical and Pharmaceutical Works Ltd. (BCPW), retaining the same premises at 91 Upper Circular Road, [[Kolkata|Calcutta]].<ref name=\"about\" /><ref name=\"telegraph\" /> In 1908, John Cumming wrote in the \"Review of the Industrial Position and Prospects in Bengal\" that the \"enterprise shows signs of resourcefulness and business capacity, which should be an object lesson to capitalists of this province\".<ref name=\"times\" />\n[[File:Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Limited - Kolkata 7336.JPG|thumb|The main gate of the Maniktala Main Road factory of BCPL, Kolkata]]\nFrom a beginning with one factory in Maniktala (Kolkata) in 1905, three more factories were established \u2013 one in [[Panihati]] in 1920,  one in [[Mumbai]] in 1938 and one in [[Kanpur]] in 1949 with its Registered Office at 6 Ganesh Chandra Avenue.<ref name=\"about\" /><ref name=\"times\" /> The company began to struggle after Roy's death in 1942. Since the 1950s, it recorded losses every year for the next 6 decades until finally posting a profit of {{INRConvert|4|c}} in the 2016\u20132017 fiscal year.<ref name=\"times\" /> The company has nine sales outlets and various C & F Agencies across [[India]].\n\nDuring the 1965s, the market situation acted as deterrent to growth and the company entered a dark phase in 1970s. The management of the company was taken over by the government of India on 15 December 1977 and nationalized on 15 December 1980. A new company was formed under the name and style Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd. in 1981.\n\nBCPL has received WHO-GMP Certificate, DGQA Certificate and [[ISO 9001 Licence]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2013}}.\n\nBCPL has entered the production of sera and vaccines. Besides the anti-snake venom serum that is already manufactures, it has plans to manufacture [[Rabies immunoglobulin|anti rabies vaccine]] (ARV), Anti Rabies Serum (ARS), Diphtheria Anti Toxin (DAT),  Kalazar, etc.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} It is planned to open a new Pharma Division in the areas of cardiovascular medicines, hypolipidemic drugs, anticancer drugs, new cephalosporin antibiotics. Negotiation is going on to evaluate the possibility of manufacturing anti-retroviral products for which the nation is dependent on imports. It has opened various sales depots and C&F agents in the year 2014 and is now having a Pan India distribution network. The company is major supplier to defence, ESIC and has also various rate contracts in DGS&D.{{clarify|What do all the letters mean?|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Divisions==\nThe Company expanded and diversified into a multi-product conglomerate, with three divisions.\n* '''Division I''' - Magnesium Sulphate (Alum),\n* '''Division II''' - drugs and pharmaceuticals, such as analgesics and Antipyretics, antitussive, expectorants, enzymes & hepatobiliary preparations, diuretics, topical anti-infective amd antifungals, mon-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs, muscle relaxants, antibiotics and antibacterials, anti-tubercular drugs, [[Antimalarial medication|antimalarial drugs]], [[vitamin]]s, oral electrolytes, antiasthmatic preparations, anti-venom serum\n* '''Division III''' - cosmetics and home products, namely cantharidine hair oil, disinfectant fluid (Lamp Brand phenol), moth repellent (naphthalene ball), aguru (perfume), floor cleanser (White Tiger) and toilet cleaner (Klin Toilet).\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"about\">{{cite web|title=Our Founder & BCPL History|url=http://bengalchemicals.co.in/our-founder-history/|website=Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.|accessdate=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"bengalchemicals\">{{cite web|title=Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.|url=http://www.bengalchemicals.gov.in/|publisher=bengalchemicals.gov.in|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"highbeam\">{{cite web|title=Bengal Chemicals and Pharmaceuticals Ltd.|url=http://business.highbeam.com/company-profiles/info/1340957/bengal-chemicals-and-pharmaceuticals-ltd|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140307135241/http://business.highbeam.com/company-profiles/info/1340957/bengal-chemicals-and-pharmaceuticals-ltd|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 March 2014|publisher=business.highbeam.com|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"profit\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/bengal-chemicals-fy19-profit-jumps-150-to-25-crore/article27005105.ece|title=Bengal Chemicals FY19 profit jumps 150% to \u20b925 crore|date=2019-05-01|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-05-19|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web|title=Chemistry of nationalism|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1081207/jsp/calcutta/story_10215243.jsp|publisher=telegraphindia.com|accessdate=7 March 2014}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"times\">{{cite web|title=How India\u2019s oldest pharma company smelt success after 6 decades|url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/kolkata/india-s-oldest-pharma-company-makes-profit-after-six-decades/story-xOYRYfMI1DOtVFSuIYKIsK.html|website=Hindustan Times|accessdate=13 April 2017|language=en|date=13 April 2017}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"unions\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/bengal-chemicals-sale-plan-leaves-unions-fuming/article28713248.ece|title=Bengal Chemicals \u2018sale\u2019 plan leaves unions fuming|last=Dutta|first=Indrani|date=2019-07-25|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-07-28|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://bengalchemicals.co.in/}}\n\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of India]]\n[[Category:Chemical companies of India]]\n[[Category:Pharmaceutical companies of India]]\n[[Category:Pharmaceutical companies established in 1901]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Indian companies established in 1901]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd.\n| logo = Bengal Chemicals & Pharmaceuticals Ltd. logo.jpg\n| logo_size =\n| logo_alt =\n| logo_caption =\n| logo_padding =\n| image =\n| image_size =\n| image_alt =\n| image_caption =\n| trading_name =\n| former_name = Bengal Chemical & Pharmaceutical Works Ltd. (BCPW)\n| type =\n| traded_as =\n| ISIN =\n| industry =\n| predecessor = Bengal Chemical Works (1892\u20131901)\n| founded = {{Start date and age|df=yes|1901|04|12}} in [[Calcutta]], [[Bengal Presidency]], [[British Indi